rom the hash.','One-way: easy to compute, infeasible to reverse.','Reproducible: produces different outputs each time it runs.','Variable: output length depends on the input data given.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q176','K',NULL,'5','Hashing','[]'),(1221,5,'Which sorting algorithm has an average-case time complexity of O(n²)?','Heap sort.','Merge sort.','Quick sort.','Bubble sort.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q177','K',NULL,'5','Big-O','[]'),(1222,5,'Which of the following is a key difference between TCP and UDP protocols?','TCP guarantees delivery and order; UDP does neither.','TCP is faster than UDP for media streaming use cases.','TCP is application-layer; UDP is transport-layer.','TCP is connectionless; UDP is connection-oriented.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q178','K',NULL,'5','TCP vs UDP','[]'),(1223,5,'What is the primary difference between a Docker container and a virtual machine (VM)?','Containers are stateless; VMs maintain persistent state by default.','Containers share the host kernel; VMs run a full guest OS.','Containers run on cloud servers; VMs run on local hardware.','Containers run one process; VMs run many processes at once.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q179','K',NULL,'5','Container','[]'),(1224,5,'What does \'CI/CD\' stand for in modern software development?','Continuous Integration / Continuous Delivery.','Code Integration / Code Deployment.','Container Integration / Container Distribution.','Cloud Integration / Cloud Deployment.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q180','K',NULL,'5','CI/CD','[]'),(1225,5,'Two-factor authentication (2FA) typically combines:','Something you know with something you have or are.','A user identifier plus a secret password.','Two different passwords used during the login sequence.','A password plus a security question used as backup.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q181','K',NULL,'5','Authentication','[]'),(1226,5,'What does \'overfitting\' mean in a machine learning context?','Model has more parameters than the available training data.','Model takes too long to converge on a training run.','Model fits the training data but fails on new data.','Model is trained on too large a dataset for its design.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q182','K',NULL,'5','Machine Learning','[]'),(1227,5,'What does an LLM (Large Language Model) like GPT or Claude fundamentally do at the token level?','Predict the next token based on the preceding tokens.','Match the user\'s input to the closest known answer.','Apply logical rules to interpret the user\'s question.','Retrieve relevant content from a stored knowledge base.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q183','K',NULL,'5','Generative AI','[]'),(1228,5,'Which of the following best describes \'end-to-end encryption\' (E2EE)?','Data is encrypted while moving between two servers.','Only sender and recipient can read the message content.','Data is encrypted on disk wherever it is stored.','The service provider holds keys to decrypt all messages.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q184','K',NULL,'5','Encryption','[]'),(1229,5,'In JavaScript, what is the primary purpose of \'async/await\'?','Writing asynchronous code that reads like synchronous code.','Running multiple tasks in parallel across multiple CPU threads.','Avoiding callbacks entirely in modern JavaScript code patterns.','Delaying code execution until a specific clock time arrives.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q185','K',NULL,'5','Asynchronous','[]'),(1230,5,'What is an \'API key\' typically used for?','Uniquely identifying a user across multiple services.','Authorising payment for usage of a service.','Authenticating and authorising calls to a service.','Encrypting requests sent to a third-party service.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q186','K',NULL,'5','API Authentication','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1231,5,'What is the term for a function that calls itself, typically with a smaller input each time?','Branching.','Iteration.','Looping.','Recursion.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q187','K',NULL,'5','Recursion','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1232,5,'You\'ve written code that has just been deployed to production. A user reports it is causing errors. What is the MOST appropriate first action?','Investigate the root cause fully and completely before taking any action on the issue.','Wait for more user reports to come in to confirm whether the issue is real or one-off.','Roll back to the previous version immediately without investigating what the actual issue is.','Verify the issue, assess severity and scope, then roll back, hotfix, or mitigate as needed.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q188','SJT',NULL,'5','Production Bug','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1233,5,'A teammate has submitted code for review. You notice 5 issues — 3 are stylistic preferences, 2 are real bugs. The MOST effective review approach is:','Flag all 5 issues with equal emphasis to be thorough in your review of their work.','Let it go entirely — code reviews shouldn\'t be too picky about minor stylistic things.','Flag the 2 bugs as required changes and mention stylistic items as optional suggestions.','Flag only the 2 bugs and ignore the stylistic preferences since they are not real issues.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q189','SJT',NULL,'5','Code Review','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":2}}'),(1234,5,'You are using an AI coding assistant (like Copilot or Claude) to write code for an assignment. The MOST professionally appropriate approach is:','Use AI freely but make small edits to the output before submitting the final assignment.','Use AI as an aid: review each line, ensure you understand, test it, disclose if required.','Refuse to use AI tools at all to ensure that all of your submitted work is original.','Submit the AI\'s output as your own work without any disclosure of where it came from.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q190','SJT',NULL,'5','AI Tool Use','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1235,5,'Your team is moving to a new technology stack you don\'t know. You have one month before you\'ll be expected to contribute. The MOST effective learning approach is:','Take an expensive certification course to ensure your preparation is thorough and complete.','Wait until your team\'s projects start and learn the new stack on the job as you go.','Read every book and tutorial available on the stack before writing any of your own code.','Combine quick orientation with hands-on practice, build small projects, ask questions.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q191','SJT',NULL,'5','Learning New Tech','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1236,5,'You discover a bug in an open-source library you use, and you have a working fix. The MOST professionally valuable action is:','Open an issue describing the bug, then submit a pull request following the project guide.','Fork the library and maintain your own version of it going forward for your own use.','Keep the fix to yourself and apply it locally — it\'s not your job to fix the library.','Email the maintainer of the project directly to share your fix with them privately.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q192','SJT',NULL,'5','Open Source','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1237,5,'You notice that a colleague\'s code is exposing API credentials in plain text on a public repository. The MOST appropriate immediate action is:','Email the team manager about the issue so the colleague is formally held responsible.','Make the repo private quietly without telling the colleague or anyone else about it.','Post a comment on the public repo identifying the exposed credentials so they see it.','Notify them privately, suggest rotating credentials, scrub git history, use secrets.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q193','SJT',NULL,'5','Security Reporting','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1238,5,'I am confident in my ability to learn a new programming language or framework when needed.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q194','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Tech Confidence','{\"likert\":true}'),(1239,5,'I enjoy exploring new technologies even when they are not directly required for my current work.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q195','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Curiosity','{\"likert\":true}'),(1240,5,'When my code breaks, I am methodical about isolating the cause rather than guessing randomly.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q196','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Debugging','{\"likert\":true}'),(1241,5,'When I encounter an unfamiliar tool or library, I am comfortable reading official documentation as a first step.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q197','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Documentation','{\"likert\":true}'),(1242,5,'I use AI tools (ChatGPT, Claude, Copilot, etc.) thoughtfully in my work — verifying outputs rather than copy-pasting blindly.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q198','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','AI Use','{\"likert\":true}'),(1243,5,'How often do you work on personal coding/tech projects outside of class or work requirements?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q199','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','5','Side Projects','{\"likert\":true}'),(1244,5,'How often do you read technical blogs, papers, or release notes related to technologies you use?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q200','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','5','Tech Reading','{\"likert\":true}'),(1245,6,'The SPIN selling framework, developed by Neil Rackham, structures consultative selling questions in which sequence?','Strategy, Process, Information, Next steps.','Solution, Plan, Implementation, Negotiation.','Situation, Problem, Implication, Need-payoff.','Specific, Practical, Insightful, Negotiable.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q001','K',NULL,'1','SPIN Framework','[]'),(1246,6,'Geoffrey Moore\'s value proposition formula begins with the words:','\"The market opportunity is [size] driven by [trend]...\"','\"For [target customer] who [stated need], our offering...\"','\"Our mission is to [purpose] for [target audience]...\"','\"We help companies that [their challenge] by [our offering]...\"','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q002','K',NULL,'1','Value Proposition','[]'),(1247,6,'In a classic marketing funnel (AIDA), the stages are:','Approach, Inform, Decide, Act.','Acquisition, Interaction, Decision, Adoption.','Awareness, Interest, Desire, Action.','Audience, Insight, Direction, Advocacy.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q003','K',NULL,'1','Sales Funnel','[]'),(1248,6,'\'Value-based pricing\' differs from \'cost-plus pricing\' in that:','It sets price by perceived value to the customer.','It is always more expensive than cost-plus pricing.','It adds a higher profit margin on top of costs.','It is used only in services and not in products.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q004','K',NULL,'1','Pricing Strategy','[]'),(1249,6,'Customer Lifetime Value (CLV or LTV) is most accurately defined as:','The total cost of acquiring one new paying customer.','The number of years a customer remains active with your firm.','Total revenue expected from a customer over their lifetime.','The size of the first purchase made by a paying customer.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q005','K',NULL,'1','Customer Lifetime Value','[]'),(1250,6,'Which of the following is generally TRUE of B2C selling vs B2B selling?','B2B has no emotional component in the buyer\'s decisions.','B2C requires no relationship-building with the customers.','B2C cycles are shorter; B2B involves more stakeholders.','B2B always has higher transaction value per deal than B2C.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q006','K',NULL,'1','B2C vs B2B','[]'),(1251,6,'In sales, a \'smokescreen\' objection is best described as:','An objection sent in writing rather than raised verbally.','An objection raised by a non-decision-maker in the room.','A price objection raised in the final stage of a deal.','A stated objection that hides the real underlying concern.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q007','K',NULL,'1','Objection Types','[]'),(1252,6,'The classic 4 Ps of marketing are:','Product, Price, Place, Promotion.','People, Profit, Process, Promotion.','Positioning, Pricing, Persuasion, Process.','Plan, Produce, Promote, Profit.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q008','K',NULL,'1','Marketing 4Ps','[]'),(1253,6,'In negotiation theory, ZOPA stands for:','Zonal Operational Pricing Authority.','Zone of Possible Agreement.','Zero-Point Agreement Authority.','Zone of Permitted Activity.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q009','K',NULL,'1','Negotiation ZOPA','[]'),(1254,6,'Cialdini\'s six principles of influence include all EXCEPT:','Scarcity.','Reciprocity.','Aggression.','Authority.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q010','K',NULL,'1','Persuasion','[]'),(1255,6,'The 80/20 rule (Pareto principle) in account management typically suggests:','About 80% of deals should close in 20% of the time available.','About 20% of time on existing customers and 80% on new ones.','About 80% of revenue comes from about 20% of customers.','About 80% margins are preserved by capping discounts at 20%.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q011','K',NULL,'1','Account Management','[]'),(1256,6,'If a sales team has a 25% conversion rate from qualified leads to closed deals, and needs ₹50 lakhs in closed business, with an average deal of ₹5 lakhs, how many qualified leads do they need?','100 leads.','10 leads.','20 leads.','40 leads.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q012','K',NULL,'1','Pipeline Math','[]'),(1257,6,'In marketing, \'brand marketing\' and \'demand marketing\' differ primarily in that:','Brand and demand are the same activity described in two different ways.','Brand builds long-term preference; demand drives short-term sales.','Brand is used only in B2C contexts; demand is used only in B2B ones.','Brand is digital while demand is offline in most modern marketing.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q013','K',NULL,'1','Brand vs Demand','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":2,\"d\":3}}'),(1258,6,'When meeting a potential client for the first time, what percentage of the conversation should ideally be you talking vs them?','Roughly 50/50 — balanced conversations are most effective.','Roughly 70% you, 30% them — to share what you offer.','Roughly 30% you, 70% them — to understand their context.','It depends entirely on the client\'s stated preference.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q014','K',NULL,'1','Discovery','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":2,\"d\":3}}'),(1259,6,'You are an MBA intern. Your manager assigns you to meet a prospective client. The MOST effective opening approach is:','Ask directly what their budget for the project is to qualify the opportunity early.','Present your company\'s capabilities thoroughly to establish strong credibility upfront.','Open with friendly conversation about non-work topics to build personal rapport first.','Open with broad questions about their priorities and what would make this meeting useful.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q015','SJT',NULL,'1','Discovery Conversation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":2,\"d\":3}}'),(1260,6,'Three meetings into a complex sale, you realise the person you have been engaging cannot actually approve the purchase. The MOST appropriate next move is:','Bypass the current contact and approach the actual decision-maker at the company directly.','Continue with the current contact since they have been engaged in the conversation so far.','Ask: \"Beyond yourself, who else would typically be involved in a decision like this one?\"','Send a formal proposal anyway — the decision-maker will see it eventually through them.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q016','SJT',NULL,'1','Identifying Decision-Maker','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1261,6,'A prospective client says: \'Your price is significantly higher than competitors.\' The MOST effective response is:','Defend the price firmly: \"We\'re worth it because of the quality we consistently deliver.\"','Agree and acknowledge the pricing gap, then move directly to closing the conversation.','Ask: \"What\'s the comparison — same scope, support, outcomes?\" Then quantify the value.','Offer a 15 percent discount to bridge the gap between the two prices being compared.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q017','SJT',NULL,'1','Price Objection','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1262,6,'In a SPIN-selling conversation, a client says: \'Our current system is slow.\' Your strongest follow-up is:','\"What impact does the slowness have on productivity, customer experience, or revenue?\"','\"Our system is the fastest one currently available in the market for your use case.\"','\"How much faster would you like the current system to be for your team\'s needs?\"','\"Many of our clients report similar issues with the current systems they use.\"','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q018','SJT',NULL,'1','Implication Question','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1263,6,'You have a strong idea for a new product feature but need engineering\'s buy-in to build it. The MOST effective approach is:','Meet the lead engineer: share customer evidence, ask reaction, explore feasibility together.','Build a working proof of concept yourself first before raising it with the engineering team.','Send a written proposal to engineering and formally request that they implement it soon.','Go to senior leadership first to get top-down support before engaging engineering team.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q019','SJT',NULL,'1','Internal Selling','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1264,6,'You just lost a major deal you were sure you would win. The MOST useful next action is:','Move on quickly to the next opportunity — dwelling on losses is generally unproductive.','Lower your prices for similar future deals to become more competitive in the market.','Identify a more junior buyer in the same company to start a fresh sales conversation.','Schedule a brief debrief: ask honestly why they chose differently and listen openly.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q020','SJT',NULL,'1','Lost Deal Analysis','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1265,6,'You need to send a cold email to a senior executive at a target company. The MOST effective opening is:','A short, specific message: reference their work, share one insight, ask for 15 minutes.','A flattering paragraph about their company and their notable accomplishments to date.','A comprehensive overview of your company\'s capabilities and your full range of offerings.','A direct ask for a meeting without any introduction or context provided beforehand.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q021','SJT',NULL,'1','Cold Outreach','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1266,6,'Your client has stated they will \'think about it\' for the third time in three meetings. The MOST effective response is:','Apply pressure with an artificial deadline or scarcity message to force a decision now.','Walk away from the deal entirely and reset the relationship for a later opportunity.','Ask: \"What are you still working through — fit, timing, price, or something else?\"','Send a follow-up email reiterating the value proposition for the client\'s consideration.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q022','SJT',NULL,'1','Closing','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1267,6,'In a B2B sale, the procurement contact is pushing for a 30% discount but the technical buyer loves your product. The MOST effective approach is:','Concede the full discount to keep procurement happy and protect the overall deal timing.','Escalate to the technical buyer\'s senior leadership to override procurement\'s request.','Refuse the discount firmly to maintain pricing integrity across all other customers.','Engage both: validate procurement\'s role, use technical buyer enthusiasm to expand scope.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q023','SJT',NULL,'1','Multi-stakeholder Sale','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1268,6,'A long-time client is happy with your service. The MOST effective approach to growing the account is:','Offer aggressively discounted bundle deals on additional services to tempt expansion.','Run a business review on evolving challenges, then propose solutions tied to priorities.','Aggressively pitch additional services in every meeting to surface every opportunity.','Wait for them to ask for more services when they have a new need on their side.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q024','SJT',NULL,'1','Account Expansion','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1269,6,'You need to inform a client that a project will be delayed by 6 weeks. The MOST effective communication is:','Wait until the original deadline approaches to inform them, hoping the situation improves.','Have your senior manager deliver the news instead to preserve your client relationship.','Communicate the news only by email so the conversation is fully documented in writing.','Communicate now: explain cause, action being taken, revised plan, meaningful accommodation.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q025','SJT',NULL,'1','Bad-News Communication','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1270,6,'You are assigned a new strategic account. The FIRST action you should take is:','Send a polished introduction email outlining your role and how you can help their team.','Schedule introduction meetings with as many people in the account as possible quickly.','Send your best case studies and customer references to demonstrate value upfront.','Research the account: business model, recent news, priorities, structure, prior history.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q026','SJT',NULL,'1','Strategic Account Planning','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1271,6,'A client signed up for one of your services 6 months ago and is satisfied. They are not aware of your other offerings. The MOST appropriate cross-selling approach is:','Wait for them to discover your other offerings on their own through organic channels.','Offer them a discount on a second service to encourage them to try it out soon.','In the next review, ask about priorities and mention one relevant additional service.','Send them a comprehensive catalogue of all your services to surface every possible offering.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q027','SJT',NULL,'1','Cross-selling','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1272,6,'After a first meeting, a prospect says: \'Just send me a proposal.\' The MOST effective response is:','Ask: \"Happy to — can we take 15 more minutes so the proposal reflects what matters most?\"','Decline to send anything until the prospect commits to scheduling a follow-up meeting first.','Send a generic capabilities document instead of a specific proposal at this early stage.','Send a comprehensive formal proposal within 24 hours to capitalise on the early momentum.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q028','SJT',NULL,'1','Handling \"Send a Proposal\"','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1273,6,'In a complex B2B sale, you have one enthusiastic internal advocate at the prospect company. The MOST effective use of this relationship is:','Maintain only formal communications with them to avoid any appearance of favouritism.','Rely on the advocate to sell internally on your behalf to the broader decision group.','Equip them: understand internal politics, prepare materials, brief on objections, attend key.','Bypass the advocate and engage the senior decision-makers directly to move things faster.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q029','SJT',NULL,'1','Champion Building','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1274,6,'You are representing your company at a trade show. A visitor approaches your booth and looks interested but says little. The MOST effective opening is:','Launch directly into a polished elevator pitch about your product to capture their interest.','Ask: \"What brought you to the show today? Are you exploring something specific in mind?\"','Offer a free giveaway item to engage them and build a moment of positive interaction.','Stay silent and wait until they speak first to indicate what they are actually looking for.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q030','SJT',NULL,'1','Trade-show Conversation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1275,6,'A potential client wants to buy directly from you, but your company has a channel partner who covers that region. The MOST appropriate response is:','Refuse to engage and tell the client to find the right partner on their own time.','Connect them: \"Our partner handles this region — I\'ll introduce you and stay involved.\"','Sell directly to the client — closing the deal is ultimately what matters most for revenue.','Sell to them directly and quietly offer the channel partner a referral fee privately.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q031','SJT',NULL,'1','Channel Conflict','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1276,6,'A client\'s annual contract is coming up for renewal in 60 days. The MOST effective preparation is:','Run a structured business review: revisit goals, document value, address concerns, discuss.','Wait for the client to initiate the renewal conversation when they are ready to discuss.','Offer an aggressive renewal discount upfront to lock them in early before any competition.','Send a standard renewal email 30 days before contract expiry to maintain the relationship.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q032','SJT',NULL,'1','Renewal','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1277,6,'When meeting someone with a problem, my instinct is to ask questions before recommending solutions.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q033','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Consultative Mindset','{\"likert\":true}'),(1278,6,'I am confident discussing money, pricing, and commercial terms with clients or stakeholders.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q034','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Commercial Confidence','{\"likert\":true}'),(1279,6,'I can step back from operational details and think about the bigger strategic picture.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q035','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Strategic Thinking','{\"likert\":true}'),(1280,6,'I am comfortable negotiating, even when the other party is more senior or experienced.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q036','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Negotiation Comfort','{\"likert\":true}'),(1281,6,'I can usually understand what is most important to a client even when they do not say it directly.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q037','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Client Empathy','{\"likert\":true}'),(1282,6,'After a \'no\', I can come back with a thoughtful follow-up rather than giving up.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q038','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Persistence','{\"likert\":true}'),(1283,6,'I am comfortable doing quick mental math (percentages, margins, conversions) in business conversations.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q039','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Numeracy','{\"likert\":true}'),(1284,6,'I can use stories and examples effectively to illustrate business points.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q040','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Storytelling','{\"likert\":true}'),(1285,6,'I am comfortable asking directly for what I want (a decision, a referral, an introduction).','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q041','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Closing Confidence','{\"likert\":true}'),(1286,6,'I find selling and persuasion uncomfortable, even when I believe in what I\'m selling.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q042','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','1','Avoidance of Selling','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1287,6,'I find it difficult to ask for a price or fee that reflects the true value of what I provide.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q043','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','1','Price Anxiety','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1288,6,'How often do you rehearse important business conversations or pitches in advance?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q044','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','1','Practising Pitches','{\"likert\":true}'),(1289,6,'How often do you read books, case studies, or analyses related to business, strategy, or sales? PILLAR 02  ·  LEADERSHIP & INFLUENCE Self-leadership, situational leadership, influence without authority, decision-making under uncertainty, and the foundational leadership behaviours that distinguish strong managers from average ones. Items in this pillar: 50','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q045','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','1','Reading Business Books','{\"likert\":true}'),(1290,6,'Hersey and Blanchard\'s Situational Leadership model proposes that effective leadership style should vary based on:','The personal leadership style preferences of the leader involved.','The industry context in which the team is currently working.','The development level of the team member for the specific task.','The size of the organisation in which the team operates.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q046','K',NULL,'2','Situational Leadership','[]'),(1291,6,'Servant leadership, as articulated by Robert Greenleaf, places the primary responsibility of the leader as:','Serving the growth and success of those they lead.','Modelling perfect behaviour for followers to copy.','Achieving organisational results through firm control.','Making the important decisions on behalf of the team.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q047','K',NULL,'2','Servant Leadership','[]'),(1292,6,'Daniel Goleman\'s four domains of emotional intelligence are:','Self-awareness, self-management, social awareness, relationship.','Thinking, feeling, acting, and reflecting on outcomes ahead.','Listening, speaking, reading, and writing across all contexts.','Awareness, empathy, action, and influence over self and others.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q048','K',NULL,'2','Emotional Intelligence','[]'),(1293,6,'Kotter\'s 8-step change model begins with which step?','Communicate the change vision.','Form a guiding coalition.','Develop a vision and strategy.','Create a sense of urgency.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q049','K',NULL,'2','Change Management','[]'),(1294,6,'The OODA loop — used in military and business decision-making — stands for:','Open, Organise, Deliver, Adjust.','Outcome, Objective, Decision, Action.','Order, Operate, Deliver, Audit.','Observe, Orient, Decide, Act.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q050','K',NULL,'2','Decision-Making','[]'),(1295,6,'\'Confirmation bias\' in decision-making is the tendency to:','Confirm critical details twice before taking any action.','Confirm decisions through input from multiple stakeholders.','Follow the opinion of the most senior decision-maker.','Favour information that confirms one\'s existing beliefs.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q051','K',NULL,'2','Bias','[]'),(1296,6,'Bruce Tuckman\'s model of team development stages are:','Planning, Executing, Reviewing, Improving.','Starting, Building, Maturing, Concluding.','Forming, Storming, Norming, Performing.','Setup, Sprint, Synthesise, Solidify.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q052','K',NULL,'2','Team Dynamics','[]'),(1297,6,'According to Daniel Pink\'s research (Drive, 2009), the three core elements of intrinsic motivation in modern work are:','Achievement, Power, Affiliation.','Autonomy, Mastery, Purpose.','Salary, Title, Recognition.','Safety, Belonging, Esteem.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q053','K',NULL,'2','Motivation','[]'),(1298,6,'Michael Porter\'s Five Forces framework analyses competitive intensity in an industry through:','Customer, competitor, capability, channel, and cost.','Marketing, sales, operations, finance, and HR functions.','Team capabilities, technology, brand, capital, culture.','New entrants, suppliers, buyers, substitutes, rivalry.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q054','K',NULL,'2','Strategy','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1299,6,'In delegation, telling someone exactly what to do and how to do it is most appropriate when:','The task is creative and open-ended in its outcome.','You want to maximise their learning and personal growth.','They are new to the task and have low competence in it.','They have high competence in the task and need direction.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q055','K',NULL,'2','Delegation Levels','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1300,6,'You have just been appointed team leader of a 6-person team you joined recently. On Day 1 in the role, the MOST effective first action is:','Spend 2 weeks in 1:1 listening: their work, frustrations, aspirations, what they need.','Continue everything exactly as the previous leader did to provide continuity for the team.','Make a visible quick-win decision early to establish your authority and credibility.','Announce your vision and immediate priorities to the team to set clear direction quickly.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q056','SJT',NULL,'2','New Team Leader Day 1','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1301,6,'A team member you inherited is consistently missing deadlines. Their previous manager rated them well. The MOST appropriate first step is:','Issue a formal warning to set very clear expectations about the standard required.','Have a private conversation: share observations, ask what\'s happening, explore what\'s needed.','Ignore the issue — they were rated well before, so the problem might resolve itself soon.','Assume the person is coasting and quietly reassign their work to other team members.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q057','SJT',NULL,'2','Underperformer','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1302,6,'Your senior manager asks you to deliver a project in 4 weeks. You believe it requires 8 weeks for quality delivery. The MOST appropriate response is:','Refuse the 4-week timeline outright as unachievable within the existing constraints.','Agree to the 4 weeks to show commitment, then renegotiate the timeline later as needed.','Accept the deadline and plan to deliver a lower-quality version within the 4 weeks.','Go back: \"For 4 weeks I\'d need to cut X from scope or get Y resource. Which works?\"','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q058','SJT',NULL,'2','Conflicting Priorities','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1303,6,'Your manager (who is senior to you) made a comment in a recent meeting that you believe was inappropriate. You feel uncomfortable but unsure whether to raise it. The MOST professionally mature response is:','Submit a formal complaint to HR to escalate the issue through official company channels.','Stay silent — they are senior to you; it is not your place to raise it with them.','Request a private chat: \"When you said X, I felt Y. I wanted to share because I respect us.\"','Discuss your discomfort with peers first to validate whether you are overreacting to it.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q059','SJT',NULL,'2','Feedback to Senior','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1304,6,'You need engineering\'s cooperation on a marketing initiative, but they have no incentive to prioritise it. The MOST effective approach is:','Escalate the request to senior leadership to mandate cooperation from the engineering team.','Build your case in writing and rely on email exchanges to make the request to them.','Meet the engineering lead: understand priorities, frame work as serving their goals too.','Offer to do all of the work yourself if the engineering team supplies guidance only.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q060','SJT',NULL,'2','Cross-Functional Influence','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1305,6,'In a leadership meeting, the senior VP makes a strategic claim you believe is factually wrong. The MOST appropriate response is:','Add gently: \"Building on that — one data point that might add nuance to the picture.\"','Counter directly with: \"Actually that\'s not quite right — let me explain why it isn\'t.\"','Stay silent — openly disagreeing in this kind of public forum can be career-limiting.','Send the VP a private email after the meeting ends with the correct information attached.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q061','SJT',NULL,'2','Disagreement in Meeting','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":2}}'),(1306,6,'A junior team member proposes an approach that you think is sub-optimal but not seriously flawed. The MOST developmentally effective response is:','Tell them the right way to do it from your experience to save the team valuable time.','Let them try it, ask questions to surface risks, let them adjust as they learn from doing.','Veto their approach and reassign the work to a more experienced team member instead.','Approve their approach without any further comment to encourage their initiative going forward.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q062','SJT',NULL,'2','Empowering Team','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1307,6,'You notice a high-performing team member is showing signs of burnout (working late constantly, withdrawal, missed details). The MOST appropriate action is:','Force them to take a vacation by mandating they take time off from work immediately.','Quietly redistribute some of their current work to other team members without telling them.','Wait for them to come to you when they are ready to ask for help with their workload.','Have a caring private chat: share observations, ask how they are, work on workload together.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q063','SJT',NULL,'2','Burnout in Team','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1308,6,'In a leadership team of 8, you notice the two female members rarely speak in strategic discussions. The MOST appropriate action as a peer is:','Ask them privately what is working and isn\'t, then advocate for changes to meeting dynamics.','Publicly call on them by name during meetings to actively encourage their participation.','Raise the lack of voice diversity to leadership as a structural issue needing attention.','Conclude they are introverted by nature and let them speak when they feel comfortable doing so.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q064','SJT',NULL,'2','Diversity & Inclusion','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":2,\"d\":0}}'),(1309,6,'Your team can pursue Project A (large, slow, transformational) or Project B (small, fast, quick win). Resources allow only one. The MOST strategically rigorous approach is:','Defer the decision entirely to your manager since they hold the final accountability.','Pick A — bigger payoff usually means bigger career impact over the long term for the team.','Pick B — quick wins build credibility and momentum for the team to take on bigger work.','Evaluate each on expected value and risk; choose with explicit reasoning shared with team.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q065','SJT',NULL,'2','Strategic Trade-Off','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1310,6,'Your team has just delivered a project that failed publicly. The MOST appropriate first action with the team is:','Identify the people who are most responsible for the failure and address them privately.','Wait for senior leadership\'s reaction before responding so you can align the messaging.','Move on quickly to the next project to maintain team morale and forward momentum.','Run a retrospective: focus on systemic causes; own the failure publicly as the leader.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q066','SJT',NULL,'2','Leading Through Failure','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1311,6,'Your manager asks you to slightly misrepresent project status to a senior leader to avoid difficult conversations. The MOST professional response is:','Push back: \"I\'m not comfortable misrepresenting. Can we discuss what\'s honest?\"','Comply with the request since they are your manager and they have called the judgement here.','Report the manager to their senior leader to escalate the ethical concern through channels.','Comply with the request but document your discomfort about the situation in writing.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q067','SJT',NULL,'2','Ethics','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1312,6,'A direct report keeps asking you to solve problems for them. The MOST developmentally effective response is:','Refuse to solve any of their problems and tell them they need to figure them out alone.','Move them to a role with less complexity so they can deliver more reliably for the team.','Solve the problems efficiently for them to save the team\'s time across the whole quarter.','Ask coaching questions: \"What have you tried? What are the options? Which would you choose?\"','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q068','SJT',NULL,'2','Coaching','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1313,6,'Your team has had an exceptional quarter. The MOST effective way to recognise them is:','Request a modest team bonus from leadership to acknowledge the team\'s hard work fairly.','Wait until the annual review to formally recognise the team in performance documents.','Combine specific public recognition by name with meaningful non-monetary gestures together.','Send out a generic \"great job team!\" message at the end of the quarter to thank them.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q069','SJT',NULL,'2','Recognition','{\"weights\":{\"a\":2,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1314,6,'Your CEO asks you to take on a high-visibility initiative that would seriously over-extend you. The MOST mature response is:','Accept enthusiastically — career opportunities at this level of visibility are quite rare.','Refuse the request to protect your current commitments and the quality of existing work.','Show enthusiasm, share current capacity honestly, offer alternatives or partial scope.','Accept the request and quietly deprioritise existing work to make room for the new ask.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q070','SJT',NULL,'2','Saying No','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1315,6,'A project you led has just been completed successfully. You\'re invited to present results to senior leadership. The MOST effective leadership posture is:','Send team members to present in your place so they get direct exposure to senior leaders.','Present the project as the team\'s success, naming individual contributions where they shaped it.','Insist that the entire team present together to share the spotlight as a group effort.','Present it as your own personal achievement to maximise your career visibility with leaders.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q071','SJT',NULL,'2','Sharing Credit','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1316,6,'You are interviewing for an open role on your team. One candidate has strong skills but a few values you find concerning. Another candidate has weaker skills but very strong values fit. Time-to-hire is pressure. The MOST appropriate choice usually is:','Hire the values-fit candidate if core capability allows them to grow into the role over time.','Hire the strong-skills candidate quickly to relieve the immediate pressure on the team.','Continue the search for a perfect candidate who has both strong skills and values fit.','Hire the strong-skills candidate — skills tend to be harder to teach than values overall.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q072','SJT',NULL,'2','Hiring','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1317,6,'Two of your direct reports are in open conflict that is affecting the team. The MOST effective intervention is:','Tell them to resolve the conflict between themselves without further manager involvement.','Meet each separately, then facilitate jointly: shared goals, agreements, accountability.','Restructure the team so the two of them don\'t have to interact regularly going forward.','Take a side with whichever of them is correct on the substantive matter under dispute.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q073','SJT',NULL,'2','Team Conflict','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1318,6,'You receive 360 feedback indicating you are perceived as \'too aggressive\' and \'difficult to disagree with\'. The MOST mature response is:','Identify specifically who said the feedback and address their concerns directly with them.','Apologise publicly to the entire team for any past behaviour that may have hurt people.','Reflect: is there truth? Pick 1-2 behaviour changes, share publicly, ask team to call out.','Dismiss the feedback — strong leaders sometimes need to be assertive to drive things forward.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q074','SJT',NULL,'2','Receiving 360 Feedback','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1319,6,'Your team has been doing things the same way for years. The MOST effective way to introduce innovation is:','Announce mandatory new processes that the team must adopt to break the old habits decisively.','Wait for organic change to happen — forcing innovation tends to breed strong resistance.','Hire external consultants to redesign the team\'s workflows from a fresh objective perspective.','Run small time-bounded experiments: try a new approach for 4 weeks, measure, decide together.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q075','SJT',NULL,'2','Innovation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1320,6,'You have been asked to reduce your team by 20%. The MOST humane and professional approach is:','Decide on capability needs, deliver news personally, provide support, communicate openly.','Apply pure performance criteria to make objective decisions about who to keep on the team.','Announce the reductions broadly to the company first, then handle individuals afterwards.','Delegate the difficult conversations entirely to HR to handle on behalf of the company.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q076','SJT',NULL,'2','Layoffs','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1321,6,'You want to drive a major change across the organisation. You have one senior sponsor but limited authority. The MOST effective coalition-building approach is:','Build the change quietly behind the scenes and announce it publicly when it is ready.','Move quickly to demonstrate visible momentum before opposition has time to mobilise against it.','Rely on your sponsor to use their formal authority to drive the change across the org.','Map stakeholders, meet each individually, listen first, share vision, build coalition before push.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q077','SJT',NULL,'2','Building Coalition','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1322,6,'A major decision you championed has just failed publicly. The MOST effective leadership posture in the days that follow is:','Defend the decision firmly until the evidence against it becomes truly overwhelming for all.','Distance yourself from the decision quickly to protect your reputation with senior leadership.','Take some leave from the role to reset emotionally before returning to lead the team.','Own the decision publicly, share what you\'ve learned, show you are still steady and engaged.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q078','SJT',NULL,'2','Resilience as Leader','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1323,6,'You are leading a virtual team across 4 countries. Meetings are dominated by 2 high-context cultures while the others stay quiet. The MOST effective intervention is:','Call on the quieter members specifically by name during meetings to draw them into discussion.','Continue with the meetings as they are now — those who want to participate eventually will.','Redesign meetings: pre-shared agendas, round-robin input, written async channels for thinkers.','Split the team into separate regional teams to reduce cross-cultural communication friction.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q079','SJT',NULL,'2','Working Across Cultures','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1324,6,'I lead myself effectively without needing external supervision or pressure.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q080','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Self-leadership','{\"likert\":true}'),(1325,6,'I can make good decisions even when I don\'t have complete information.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q081','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Decision Quality','{\"likert\":true}'),(1326,6,'I can articulate a clear picture of what I\'m trying to achieve, and inspire others around it.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q082','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Vision','{\"likert\":true}'),(1327,6,'People who work with me would say I am trustworthy and consistent.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q083','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Trust-Building','{\"likert\":true}'),(1328,6,'I am willing to have difficult conversations rather than letting issues fester.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q084','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Difficult Conversations','{\"likert\":true}'),(1329,6,'I can usually persuade people to support an idea I believe in, even when I lack formal authority.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q085','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Influence','{\"likert\":true}'),(1330,6,'I am willing to sacrifice short-term gains for better long-term outcomes when the trade-off is clearly worth it.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q086','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Long-term Thinking','{\"likert\":true}'),(1331,6,'I can stay composed and effective when others are stressed or in crisis around me.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q087','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Resilience','{\"likert\":true}'),(1332,6,'I enjoy developing others and find satisfaction in their growth.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q088','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Coaching Others','{\"likert\":true}'),(1333,6,'When facing a complex problem, I instinctively try to understand the system before recommending interventions.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q089','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Strategic Thinking','{\"likert\":true}'),(1334,6,'I actively try to identify and counter my own biases in important decisions.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q090','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Bias Awareness','{\"likert\":true}'),(1335,6,'I take action to improve situations rather than waiting for someone else to.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q091','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Initiative','{\"likert\":true}'),(1336,6,'I tend to avoid direct conflict even when something important needs to be addressed.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q092','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','2','Avoidance of Conflict','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1337,6,'I rely heavily on my manager\'s or others\' approval to feel I am doing a good job.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q093','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','2','External Validation','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1338,6,'How often do you read or study leadership content (books, case studies, biographies)?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q094','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','2','Reading Leadership','{\"likert\":true}'),(1339,6,'How often do you reflect, write, or talk through significant decisions you\'ve made — looking at what worked and what didn\'t? PILLAR 03  ·  PERSONALITY & COMMUNICATION Executive presence, structured communication (Pyramid Principle), feedback, difficult conversations, and cross-cultural communication for management contexts. Items in this pillar: 45','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q095','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','2','Reflection','{\"likert\":true}'),(1340,6,'The Pyramid Principle (Barbara Minto) for structured business communication recommends:','Present arguments in chronological order of their discovery.','Lead with the main message, then support with grouped arguments.','Start with background context and build up to the conclusion.','Present every possible counter-argument upfront before yours.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q096','K',NULL,'3','Pyramid Principle','[]'),(1341,6,'The \'Big Five\' personality traits (OCEAN) include all EXCEPT:','Conscientiousness.','Extraversion.','Neuroticism.','Aggressiveness.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q097','K',NULL,'3','Big 5 Personality','[]'),(1342,6,'The book Difficult Conversations (Stone, Patton, Heen) identifies three layers in every difficult conversation:','Past, present, and future of the issue.','Facts, opinions, and underlying emotions.','What happened, feelings, and identity.','Listener, speaker, and topic in the discussion.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q098','K',NULL,'3','Difficult Conversations','[]'),(1343,6,'Nancy Duarte\'s research on great presentations highlights which structural pattern:','A linear progression of setup, conflict, and resolution stages.','Alternating between \'what is\' and \'what could be\' for contrast.','An academic structure of hypothesis, methodology, findings.','A strict three-act structure borrowed from classical theatre.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q099','K',NULL,'3','Presentation Structure','[]'),(1344,6,'Amy Cuddy\'s research on body language proposes that:','Open expansive posture can shift how confident one feels.','Body language matters mainly in face-to-face meetings.','Posture affects external perception but not internal state.','Body language reveals true intentions that cannot be hidden.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q100','K',NULL,'3','Nonverbal Communication','[]'),(1345,6,'Otto Scharmer\'s four levels of listening progress from:','Hearing → understanding → agreeing → responding wisely.','Surface → middle → deep → transcendent listening levels.','Downloading → factual → empathic → generative listening.','Passive → active → reflective → directive listening stages.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q101','K',NULL,'3','Listening Levels','[]'),(1346,6,'\'Getting to Yes\' (Fisher & Ury) proposes the core principle of principled negotiation as:','Apply pressure until the more aggressive party prevails in talks.','Always negotiate in a setting that gives you a clear advantage.','Open with the most extreme position that you can plausibly defend.','Separate people from problem; focus on interests not positions.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q102','K',NULL,'3','Negotiation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1347,6,'Which is the MOST effective subject line for an email requesting a senior leader\'s decision by Friday?','\"Decision needed by Friday: pricing approach.\"','\"Quick question on next quarter\'s marketing plan.\"','\"Important: please read this at your earliest.\"','\"Following up on our earlier email discussion.\"','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q103','K',NULL,'3','Email Best Practice','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1348,6,'You have 5 minutes to present quarterly results to the CEO. The MOST effective structure is:','Walk through chronologically what happened across the team during the quarter as it unfolded.','Start with detailed methodology, then the findings, then the implications for the quarter ahead.','Lead with the headline takeaway in one sentence, then 3 supporting facts, then implications.','Present all the charts in detail and let the CEO ask questions about what matters to them.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q104','SJT',NULL,'3','Executive Presentation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1349,6,'In a meeting with a client, your senior colleague makes a commitment to the client that you believe will be hard to deliver. The MOST appropriate immediate response is:','Publicly correct your colleague in the meeting to protect the client from a future failure.','Mention the concern publicly but framed as a \"just to add nuance\" addition to their comment.','Stay silent in the meeting; raise the concern with your colleague privately right after it.','Subtly signal disagreement through your body language during the meeting to flag your concern.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q105','SJT',NULL,'3','Public Disagreement','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":2,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1350,6,'You are negotiating with a counterpart from a culture where direct refusal is rare. They say \'we will consider it\' to your proposal. The MOST appropriate interpretation is:','Insist on a clear yes or no immediately so the negotiation can move forward decisively.','Take the statement at face value — they will consider it carefully and respond when ready.','Probe gently: \"Is there anything about the proposal that doesn\'t work that we should discuss?\"','Assume it is essentially a soft yes and start planning execution of the agreement now.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q106','SJT',NULL,'3','Cross-cultural Negotiation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1351,6,'A peer has been talking over others in team meetings. You want to address it without damaging the relationship. The MOST effective approach is:','Address the behaviour publicly in the next meeting to model the kind of behaviour you want.','Mention the issue to your shared manager and let them handle the conversation with the peer.','Privately: \"I\'ve noticed people get cut off. Wanted you to know how it\'s landing. Thoughts?\"','Mention it indirectly with: \"maybe we should all watch our talking time in meetings going forward.\"','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q107','SJT',NULL,'3','Feedback to Peer','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1352,6,'You need to send a difficult email to a major client. The MOST effective approach to writing it is:','Send the first draft immediately to ensure timeliness while the situation is still fresh.','Have a long phone call with the client instead of writing because tone travels better.','Ask three colleagues to review the draft before sending it to make sure it reads well.','Draft it, re-read after an hour or overnight: check tone, clarity, sceptical-reader test.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q108','SJT',NULL,'3','Writing Under Pressure','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1353,6,'You are about to give an important presentation and feel extremely nervous. The MOST effective in-the-moment response is:','Skip the opening pleasantries entirely to get the speaking portion over with as quickly as you can.','Apologise to the audience for being nervous upfront to set expectations about your delivery.','Reframe nerves as excitement — physiologically the body\'s response overlaps with excitement.','Tell yourself firmly to calm down and try to slow your breathing before going on stage.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q109','SJT',NULL,'3','Public Speaking Nerves','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1354,6,'You are presenting to a room where one senior person is openly skeptical and asks pointed questions throughout. The MOST effective response is:','Match their energy and push back firmly to defend your position from their challenges.','Defer their questions to the end so that you can complete your presentation without interruption.','Engage seriously: \"That\'s a fair concern — let me address it\"; acknowledge, stay confident.','Ask the meeting chair to redirect them so the rest of the room can hear the full content.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q110','SJT',NULL,'3','Handling Hostile Audience','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1355,6,'Which of the following slide design choices is MOST effective for a business presentation?','Just the company logo and a section title to keep the slide visually clean and uncluttered.','Many supporting charts on each slide to demonstrate the analytical rigour of the work done.','Comprehensive bullet points covering all the points the presenter wants to make on a slide.','One clear headline message in a sentence, supported by one visual or 3 simple bullet points.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q111','SJT',NULL,'3','Slide Design','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1356,6,'You need to brief your manager on a complex project decision. The MOST effective email format is:','Lead with TL;DR or \"Bottom Line\" first, then Background, then Considerations, then Recommendation.','Send just the recommendation and a request to schedule a meeting to discuss the details further.','Send a comprehensive narrative covering everything that happened chronologically across the project.','Send a bullet list of every consideration you analysed in detail to demonstrate thoroughness.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q112','SJT',NULL,'3','Email Length','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1357,6,'A long-standing client has become unreasonably demanding and frequently raises their voice in meetings. The MOST professional response is:','Escalate the situation to your manager to handle them on behalf of the account team.','Have a calm private chat outside the heat: name the pattern, state commitment, set expectations.','Tolerate the behaviour — the client pays the bills and that is ultimately what matters here.','Drop them as a client entirely since the relationship has become unworkable for the team.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q113','SJT',NULL,'3','Difficult Client','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1358,6,'A peer asks you for help on something that would take 4 hours of your time on top of your existing commitments. The MOST appropriate response is:','Engage briefly: \"I have a tight week — could you share more so I can see if there\'s a faster way?\"','Say yes to the request — being helpful generally builds strong workplace relationships over time.','Say no without any further explanation to keep the conversation simple and time-efficient.','Say yes but quietly deliver less than they expect so the cost to you is more bearable.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q114','SJT',NULL,'3','Saying No','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1359,6,'A colleague is technically excellent but consistently sharp and dismissive in communication. The MOST mature response is:','Have a direct chat: share one specific instance, ask if there\'s context, propose new norms.','Avoid the colleague and minimise interactions to keep the working dynamic tolerable for both.','Stay quiet and just let them be themselves — that is simply their personal style of working.','Mirror their communication style yourself to even out the dynamic between the two of you.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q115','SJT',NULL,'3','Working with Difficult Personalities','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1360,6,'You need to influence a peer in another department to support an initiative they have no incentive to care about. The MOST effective approach is:','Offer them something useful in return for their support as a transactional exchange of value.','Understand their world — what they\'re measured on — and frame your ask in their interest.','Ask them as a personal favour with an appeal to your working relationship over the years.','Mention that senior leaders are watching the initiative to create indirect pressure to support.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q116','SJT',NULL,'3','Influence Without Authority','{\"weights\":{\"a\":2,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1361,6,'In a leadership meeting, you have a strong contrarian view on the strategy being discussed. You are the most junior person present. The MOST mature response is:','Wait until after the meeting and raise your concern to your direct manager privately.','Speak up: \"I may be missing something — want to share a different angle here.\"','Stay silent through the meeting since you are the most junior person in the discussion.','Withhold the view until you are more senior and can express it without career consequences.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q117','SJT',NULL,'3','Speaking Up','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1362,6,'You are building your professional online presence (LinkedIn). The MOST effective long-term content strategy is:','Post viral content about trending topics each week to maximise reach across the platform.','Avoid posting publicly and engage only through private networking with people you already know.','Post inspirational quotes and motivational content regularly to attract a wider audience base.','Share your specific perspective on your domain over time — observations and real lessons learned.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q118','SJT',NULL,'3','Personal Brand Online','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1363,6,'You want to deepen your relationship with a more senior person you respect. The MOST effective approach is:','Ask for one specific piece of advice, follow through, return to share outcome, give back later.','Engage with their content publicly to show interest in their work and stay visible to them.','Ask them explicitly to be your formal mentor and commit to a regular cadence of meetings.','Send periodic \"just checking in\" messages to keep yourself on their radar over the months.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q119','SJT',NULL,'3','Networking','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1364,6,'I have a clear and accurate sense of my own strengths and limitations.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q120','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Self-Awareness','{\"likert\":true}'),(1365,6,'I can stay calm and effective when facing strong emotions, in myself or others.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q121','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Emotional Regulation','{\"likert\":true}'),(1366,6,'I adapt my communication style to different audiences without losing my authenticity.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q122','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Adaptability','{\"likert\":true}'),(1367,6,'I am genuinely interested in people whose backgrounds and views differ from mine.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q123','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Curiosity About Others','{\"likert\":true}'),(1368,6,'I can persuade others to a position when I genuinely believe in it.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q124','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Persuasiveness','{\"likert\":true}'),(1369,6,'When listening, I am usually fully present, not formulating my reply.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q125','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Listening Depth','{\"likert\":true}'),(1370,6,'My writing is clear, concise, and well-structured.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q126','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Written Clarity','{\"likert\":true}'),(1371,6,'When presenting to an audience, I feel confident and command the room.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q127','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Stage Presence','{\"likert\":true}'),(1372,6,'I give feedback to others in a way that is honest, specific, and constructive.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q128','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Constructive Feedback Giving','{\"likert\":true}'),(1373,6,'I behave consistently with my values, even when there is social pressure to do otherwise.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q129','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Authenticity','{\"likert\":true}'),(1374,6,'I am comfortable in professional networking settings.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q130','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Networking Comfort','{\"likert\":true}'),(1375,6,'I am willing to initiate difficult conversations rather than letting issues simmer.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q131','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Difficult Conversation Comfort','{\"likert\":true}'),(1376,6,'I can usually tell when someone is upset, even if they say they are fine.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q132','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Empathy','{\"likert\":true}'),(1377,6,'I tend to avoid disagreements with peers to preserve harmony.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q133','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','3','Conflict Avoidance','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1378,6,'I often have something to add in meetings but don\'t speak up.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q134','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','3','Self-censoring','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1379,6,'Before speaking in important meetings, I often second-guess whether what I have to say is worth saying.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q135','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','3','Self-Doubt','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1380,6,'When someone challenges my idea, my first reaction is to defend rather than consider.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q136','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','3','Defensiveness','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1381,6,'How often do you re-read and edit your important written communications before sending?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q137','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','3','Writing Practice','{\"likert\":true}'),(1382,6,'How often do you ask thoughtful questions in meetings rather than just sharing your own views?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q138','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','3','Asking Questions','{\"likert\":true}'),(1383,6,'How often do you proactively maintain professional relationships (a coffee, a check-in message, a thoughtful share)?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q139','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','3','Network-Building','{\"likert\":true}'),(1384,6,'How often do you intentionally tell stories or use specific examples to make business points (rather than abstract generalities)? PILLAR 04  ·  MENTAL WELLNESS & RESILIENCE Career anxiety, impostor phenomenon, healthy ambition, recovery, and the sustainable performance habits required for a long management career. Items in this pillar: 35','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q140','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','3','Storytelling Practice','{\"likert\":true}'),(1385,6,'Research on professional resilience identifies which factor as MOST important for long-term resilience?','Social support, meaning, and recovery habits — all developable.','High intelligence combined with strong educational achievements.','Avoidance of stressful situations across personal and work life.','Innate temperament that a person is born with and cannot change.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q141','K',NULL,'4','Resilience Research','[]'),(1386,6,'Impostor phenomenon, identified by Pauline Clance and Suzanne Imes, is best described as:','A cognitive bias only experienced by women in professional contexts.','A character flaw causing chronic self-promotion in the workplace.','A diagnosable anxiety disorder requiring formal clinical treatment.','Competent people feeling like frauds despite their achievements.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q142','K',NULL,'4','Impostor Phenomenon','[]'),(1387,6,'Research on sleep and professional performance has consistently shown:','Sleep needs vary dramatically between healthy individuals of similar ages.','Most adults can adapt to five hours of sleep without measurable impact.','Sleep quality matters far more than total sleep quantity for performance.','Chronic short sleep degrades cognition even when self-perception adapts.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q143','K',NULL,'4','Sleep & Performance','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1388,6,'Research by Alia Crum and others on \'stress mindset\' has shown:','Stress can be eliminated entirely through regular meditation.','How we frame stress changes its physiological effect on us.','Stress is purely physiological and is unrelated to mindset.','All stress is harmful and should be minimised wherever possible.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q144','K',NULL,'4','Stress Reframing','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1389,6,'You are 3 months into a rigorous MBA program and feeling persistently overwhelmed. The MOST constructive response is:','Push harder through the overwhelm — that level of intensity is just part of business school.','Take a temporary break from the program to reset before returning fresh to the work.','Diagnose honestly (workload, anxiety, sleep) and commit to 1-2 interventions for 4 weeks.','Drop one of your courses to lighten the load and reduce the academic burden a bit.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q145','SJT',NULL,'4','Overwhelm at MBA','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1390,6,'You feel anxious about your career trajectory while peers seem confidently ahead. The MOST healthy response is:','Work harder to try to catch up with your peers and close the perceived career trajectory gap.','Switch your career direction entirely to something less competitive to reduce the pressure.','Ask your peers directly for their honest career advice on what is working for them right now.','Recognise comparison is unreliable — refocus on your own goals, reduce comparison inputs.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q146','SJT',NULL,'4','Career Anxiety','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":2,\"d\":3}}'),(1391,6,'You bombed a major case competition in front of your peers. The MOST psychologically healthy response is:','Take a break from all challenging activities for a few weeks to reset and recover fully.','Avoid all future case competitions to prevent the chance of a repeat public embarrassment.','Tell yourself the judges were simply wrong and your team\'s analysis was actually correct.','Feel embarrassed briefly, then review specific factors honestly, apply learning to the next.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q147','SJT',NULL,'4','Failure Recovery','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1392,6,'You have just landed a prestigious role and you feel everyone will soon discover you are not as capable as they thought. The MOST healthy response is:','Decline the role altogether to avoid the inevitable risk of public exposure of your gaps.','Suppress the feelings completely and act with full confidence in every interaction at work.','Work double-time to ensure no one notices any gap between your actual and perceived ability.','Recognise this as impostor phenomenon — talk to a mentor, focus on the work, trust growth.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q148','SJT',NULL,'4','Impostor Syndrome','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1393,6,'Your MBA cohort has an intense social culture with events most evenings. You are exhausted but feel pressure to attend. The MOST healthy response is:','Attend everything but leave early from each to balance social showing with rest needed.','Push through and attend everything since networking in business school really does matter.','Choose deliberately: a few high-quality events, deeper relationships, protected sleep time.','Skip all of the social events to focus exclusively on academic work and your wellbeing.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q149','SJT',NULL,'4','Boundaries in MBA Culture','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1394,6,'After a particularly intense week, the MOST effective form of recovery is typically:','Catch up on backlog work during the weekend to feel a sense of productive accomplishment.','Sleep in for 12 hours on Saturday morning to make up for all the missed sleep that week.','Active recovery: adequate sleep, physical activity, restorative people, low pressure.','Binge-watch TV shows over the weekend to fully switch off from anything work-related.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q150','SJT',NULL,'4','Recovery','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1395,6,'Over the past 3 weeks, you have been feeling persistently low, losing interest in things, and struggling to concentrate. The MOST appropriate action is:','Take more weekend vacations to feel better and reset before any deeper intervention is tried.','Try harder to power through it with willpower until the symptoms eventually subside on their own.','Talk to a trusted person and proactively reach out to a counsellor or wellness service.','Wait another month or so — these things often pass on their own with a bit of time.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q151','SJT',NULL,'4','When to Seek Help','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1396,6,'You are working 80-hour weeks consistently. You feel productive but notice your physical and mental health declining. The MOST mature response is:','Recognise 80-hour weeks reduce effective output over time; restructure to invest in recovery.','Continue working at that intensity — short-term sacrifice for the long-term career payoff later.','Try to be more efficient within the 80 hours so the same workload feels less draining.','Take a single long vacation later in the year to compensate for the period of overwork.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q152','SJT',NULL,'4','Healthy Ambition','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1397,6,'I have effective ways to manage stress in my daily life.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q153','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Stress Management','{\"likert\":true}'),(1398,6,'I maintain regular sleep habits even during demanding periods.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q154','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Sleep Discipline','{\"likert\":true}'),(1399,6,'I have ways to genuinely recover from intense periods (not just collapse or distract).','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q155','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Recovery','{\"likert\":true}'),(1400,6,'I have a clear sense of what gives my work meaning.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q156','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Purpose','{\"likert\":true}'),(1401,6,'I can usually pause before reacting when something stressful happens.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q157','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Emotional Regulation','{\"likert\":true}'),(1402,6,'I have at least one person I can be completely honest with about my struggles.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q158','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Support Network','{\"likert\":true}'),(1403,6,'When I fail at something, I treat myself with kindness rather than harshness.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q159','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Self-compassion','{\"likert\":true}'),(1404,6,'My sense of self does not depend entirely on my career achievements.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q160','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Identity Beyond Work','{\"likert\":true}'),(1405,6,'I am comfortable asking for help when I need it.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q161','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Help-Seeking','{\"likert\":true}'),(1406,6,'I generally believe that things tend to work out when I act with focus and integrity.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q162','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Optimism','{\"likert\":true}'),(1407,6,'I can say no to requests that would compromise my wellbeing.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q163','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Boundaries','{\"likert\":true}'),(1408,6,'I maintain my physical health as a foundation for sustained performance.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q164','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Physical Health','{\"likert\":true}'),(1409,6,'I often compare myself unfavourably to peers.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q165','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','4','Comparison','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1410,6,'I worry about my career path more than I think is healthy.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q166','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','4','Anxiety','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1411,6,'When things get stressful, I distract myself with screens, food, or other things rather than addressing what I\'m feeling.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q167','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','4','Avoidance Coping','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1412,6,'How often do you get at least 7 hours of sleep per night?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q168','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Sleep','{\"likert\":true}'),(1413,6,'How often do you exercise (any movement that raises your heart rate) for at least 30 minutes?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q169','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Exercise','{\"likert\":true}'),(1414,6,'How often do you spend time mindfully (meditation, journaling, time in nature, technology-free reflection)?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q170','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Mindfulness','{\"likert\":true}'),(1415,6,'How often do you have a real conversation with someone you care about (not just messages)?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:45','Q171','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Connection','{\"likert\":true}'),(1416,6,'How often do you say no to requests that would exceed your capacity?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q172','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Boundaries','{\"likert\":true}'),(1417,6,'How often do you eat regular meals with nourishing food?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q173','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Nutrition','{\"likert\":true}'),(1418,6,'How often do you set aside time to reflect, journal, or think — without input from screens or other people?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q174','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Reflection','{\"likert\":true}'),(1419,6,'How often do you have at least one continuous hour each day with no screens? PILLAR 05  ·  TECHNOLOGY & DIGITAL FLUENCY Business-relevant technology fluency: data, analytics, AI tools, cybersecurity, and the digital judgment expected of modern managers. Items in this pillar: 25','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q175','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Screen Breaks','{\"likert\":true}'),(1420,6,'In Excel, which function would you use to look up a value from one table in another table?','SUM with cell references.','VLOOKUP function or XLOOKUP.','AVERAGE across two ranges.','CONCATENATE on key columns.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q176','K',NULL,'5','Excel Skills','[]'),(1421,6,'To compare proportions of a single whole (e.g., market share by company), the MOST appropriate chart type is generally:','Histogram of company values.','Line chart with multiple series.','Scatter plot with grouped points.','Pie chart or stacked bar chart.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q177','K',NULL,'5','Data Visualisation','[]'),(1422,6,'When an LLM like ChatGPT confidently produces a piece of information that is actually wrong, this is called:','Hallucination.','Training bias.','Network lag.','Software bug.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q178','K',NULL,'5','AI Literacy','[]'),(1423,6,'Your company emails you asking you to urgently click a link and reset your password. The MOST appropriate response is:','Forward the email to your team to ask them for confirmation.','Verify through a separate channel before any action is taken.','Click the link immediately to comply with the urgent request.','Reply to the email asking the sender for further verification.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q179','K',NULL,'5','Cybersecurity','[]'),(1424,6,'The European GDPR regulation broadly governs:','Personal data processing for EU residents, by any organisation.','Cybersecurity standards adopted by EU government bodies only.','Trade tariffs and customs procedures between EU member states.','Marketing standards applicable inside European Union markets.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q180','K',NULL,'5','Data Privacy','[]'),(1425,6,'SaaS, PaaS, and IaaS are levels of cloud services. From most managed-for-you to least, the order is:','SaaS, then PaaS, then IaaS.','All three are equally managed.','IaaS, then PaaS, then SaaS.','PaaS, then SaaS, then IaaS.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q181','K',NULL,'5','Cloud Basics','[]'),(1426,6,'A/B testing in business contexts refers to:','A method for grading individual employee performance fairly.','A qualitative user research interview method for product fit.','Randomly assigning users to variants and measuring outcomes.','A two-stage software testing protocol with code review steps.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q182','K',NULL,'5','A/B Testing','[]'),(1427,6,'In digital marketing, \'CAC\' refers to:','Customer Acquisition Cost.','Click-and-Capture rate.','Conversion Audit Cost.','Customer Annual Charge.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q183','K',NULL,'5','Digital Marketing','[]'),(1428,6,'The \'bounce rate\' on a website is most accurately defined as:','Number of times a page is shared on social media by visitors.','Percentage who leave without taking any action on the site.','Percentage of pages that fail to load when visitors request them.','Percentage of visitors who return again to the site later.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q184','K',NULL,'5','Analytics','[]'),(1429,6,'When using AI tools (like ChatGPT) for business analysis, the MOST important practice is:','Verify claims and numbers from independent sources before use.','Always trust the output since models are trained on vast data.','Avoid disclosing AI use in any professional output that you produce.','Use AI only for creative tasks and never for any analytical work.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q185','K',NULL,'5','AI Use','[]'),(1430,6,'\'Agile\' methodology in project management is best characterised by:','Single-person project execution to maximise speed of delivery.','Speed-prioritised delivery without any defined process steps.','Iterative delivery in short cycles with continuous learning.','Detailed long-term planning with strict milestone-gated steps.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q186','K',NULL,'5','Project Management','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1431,6,'In a financial model, what does NPV (Net Present Value) account for that simple cash-flow sums do not?','Currency conversion across multiple-country operations.','Inflation impact on currency over the period in scope.','Tax effects applied to projected revenues and expenses.','Time value of money via discounting future cash flows.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q187','K',NULL,'5','Financial Modelling','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1432,6,'Your CEO asks for your recommendation on a major decision. You have some data but it is incomplete. The MOST effective response is:','Present the data you have, state limits, share your recommendation, note what would change it.','Recommend the safest option available to minimise the risk of being wrong on the call.','Recommend based on your intuition since the available data is incomplete for the decision.','Refuse to make a recommendation until more complete data has been gathered for analysis.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q188','SJT',NULL,'5','Data-Driven Decision','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1433,6,'You are preparing a competitive analysis. You use ChatGPT for a first draft. The MOST appropriate next step is:','Submit the AI\'s output as your own work to save time and meet the deadline efficiently.','Use AI only for formatting the document and write all of the content from scratch yourself.','Make small edits to the AI\'s output and then submit the resulting document as your work.','Verify every claim, replace generic content with original insight, disclose AI use clearly.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q189','SJT',NULL,'5','AI Tool Use','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1434,6,'You discover that your team has been storing customer email addresses in a shared spreadsheet without proper protection. The MOST appropriate action is:','Delete the spreadsheet immediately to remove the privacy risk to the customers in the data.','Quietly secure the spreadsheet\'s access controls without raising the issue with the wider team.','Raise it with your manager and IT, propose a secure system, review against policy and law.','Continue as before — the existing practice has worked without any issues for the team so far.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q190','SJT',NULL,'5','Data Privacy','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1435,6,'You need to present complex analytics findings to a non-technical executive. The MOST effective approach is:','Send the raw data file across in advance and offer to discuss it with them at any time.','Lead with the headline insight in plain English; 2-3 visuals; methodology in the appendix.','Present every chart from the analysis and let the executive choose what matters most to them.','Walk through the methodology in detail to demonstrate the analytical rigour of your work.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q191','SJT',NULL,'5','Stakeholder Reporting','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1436,6,'Your team is debating whether to adopt a new productivity tool that promises efficiency gains. The MOST effective evaluation approach is:','Pilot with a small group for a defined period; measure specific outcomes; decide on real evidence.','Stick with current tools — the cost of switching is generally higher than the efficiency gains.','Adopt it immediately to capture the early-mover advantage in productivity gains for the team.','Wait for industry peers to validate the tool first before the team takes the time to evaluate.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q192','SJT',NULL,'5','Adopting New Tools','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1437,6,'You need to convince a non-technical executive to invest in upgrading legacy technology. The MOST effective framing is:','Bring in a vendor to make the technical case directly with the executive on your behalf.','Explain the technical limitations in detail to demonstrate the urgent need for the upgrade now.','Emphasise that competitors are advancing on their stack to create a sense of urgency to act.','Translate into business: quantify cost, connect to priorities, present a phased ROI projection.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q193','SJT',NULL,'5','Tech-Business Translation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1438,6,'I am comfortable working with data — spreadsheets, dashboards, and analytics.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q194','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Data Comfort','{\"likert\":true}'),(1439,6,'I use AI tools (ChatGPT, Claude, etc.) thoughtfully — as productivity aids that I verify, not as oracles.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q195','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','AI Sophistication','{\"likert\":true}'),(1440,6,'I can translate technical concepts into business language for non-technical audiences.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q196','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Tech Translation','{\"likert\":true}'),(1441,6,'I am confident in my ability to learn new business software and tools.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q197','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Learning Tech','{\"likert\":true}'),(1442,6,'I follow good digital security practices (strong passwords, 2FA, careful with links, etc.).','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q198','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Digital Hygiene','{\"likert\":true}'),(1443,6,'How often do you read or learn about technology trends relevant to your industry?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q199','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','5','Tech Learning','{\"likert\":true}'),(1444,6,'How often do you invest time in deepening your skills with existing tools (Excel, BI tools, presentation tools, AI tools) rather than always learning new ones?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q200','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','5','Tool Mastery','{\"likert\":true}'),(1445,7,'In consultative selling, the most important shift from product-oriented selling is:','Selling at a higher price point than competitors.','Focusing on quarterly sales targets and pipeline.','Shifting from \'what we offer\' to \'what they need\'.','Using more case studies in every customer meeting.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q001','K',NULL,'1','Consultative Selling','[]'),(1446,7,'Research consistently shows that the cost of acquiring a new customer compared to retaining an existing customer is roughly:','Less expensive due to economies of scale in acquisition.','5–7 times more expensive to acquire than to retain.','About twice as expensive to acquire as to retain.','About the same when measured over a full sales cycle.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q002','K',NULL,'1','Customer Retention','[]'),(1447,7,'Net Promoter Score (NPS) is calculated as:','Total number of Promoters divided by all the respondents.','Simple average of all responses on the 0–10 rating scale.','Percentage of Promoters minus Percentage of Detractors.','Total number of repeat customers within a single year.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q003','K',NULL,'1','NPS','[]'),(1448,7,'In key account management, \'whitespace analysis\' refers to:','Identifying untapped opportunities within an existing account.','Studying the customer base of your strongest direct competitor.','Analysing the unused capacity in your active sales pipeline.','Analysing time gaps between repeat customer transactions.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q004','K',NULL,'1','Account Management','[]'),(1449,7,'RFM customer segmentation analyses three dimensions:','Reach, Funnel, Marketing spend.','Region, Function, Market segment.','Recency, Frequency, Monetary value.','Revenue, Forecast, Margin level.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q005','K',NULL,'1','Customer Segmentation','[]'),(1450,7,'Clayton Christensen\'s \'Jobs to be Done\' framework reframes customer needs as:','Stages of the sales funnel the customer moves through.','Product features the customer would like to see added.','The job the customer wants done in a situation.','Demographic categories describing who the customer is.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q006','K',NULL,'1','Jobs-to-be-Done','[]'),(1451,7,'If a sales rep has a 10% close rate (lead-to-customer), and the average customer is worth ₹2 lakhs, what is the average revenue value of a single lead?','₹50,000.','₹2,000.','₹200,000.','₹20,000.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q007','K',NULL,'1','Funnel Metrics','[]'),(1452,7,'A \'weighted pipeline\' forecast multiplies each opportunity\'s value by:','Its expected probability of closing.','The time already spent on the deal.','The number of stakeholders involved.','The salesperson\'s individual quota.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q008','K',NULL,'1','Sales Forecasting','[]'),(1453,7,'In modern B2C sales, \'product-led growth\' refers to:','Product roadmaps prioritising growth-oriented features.','Letting the product drive acquisition and retention.','Sales driven by aggressive feature development cycles.','Growth driven by product managers, not by sales teams.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q009','K',NULL,'1','Cross-functional Selling','[]'),(1454,7,'Research on consumer pricing has consistently shown that \'charm pricing\' (e.g., ₹999 instead of ₹1000) works because:','Odd numbers are aesthetically preferred over even numbers.','Consumers genuinely cannot do basic mental arithmetic well.','Left-digit anchoring affects how magnitude is perceived.','It signals a discount to buyers even when none exists.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q010','K',NULL,'1','Behavioural Pricing','[]'),(1455,7,'From a unit-economics perspective, when offering a 20% discount, the equivalent volume increase required to maintain the same gross profit (with a 50% gross margin) is approximately:','20% volume increase.','40% volume increase.','67% volume increase.','100% volume increase.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q011','K',NULL,'1','Discount Logic','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1456,7,'David Maister\'s \'Trust Equation\' for professional relationships is:','Skill + Track record + Likeability across interactions.','(Competence + Authority) × Communication consistency.','Honesty × Competence × Time spent working together.','(Credibility + Reliability + Intimacy) / Self-focus.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q012','K',NULL,'1','Trust Equation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1457,7,'A long-time customer has just informed you they are leaving for a competitor. The MOST appropriate response is:','Escalate to your manager to handle the retention conversation on your behalf today.','Immediately offer a significant discount to retain them and prevent the loss.','Schedule a call: listen, ask what would solve it, respect their decision.','Send a formal thank-you email and accept the loss gracefully to preserve goodwill.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q013','SJT',NULL,'1','Customer Churn','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1458,7,'A client says: \'Either reduce your price by 25% or we move our business to a competitor.\' The MOST effective response is:','Ask: \"What\'s behind the 25% — competitor pricing, budget, or something else?\" Explore.','Walk away and let them go to their competitor of choice without further discussion.','Reduce the price by the full 25% to retain the business and protect the relationship.','Counter with a 10% discount as a compromise to bridge the pricing gap between you.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q014','SJT',NULL,'1','Complex Pricing Negotiation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1459,7,'Your main contact at a major client has just left the company. The replacement is unknown. The MOST effective approach is:','Continue execution and let the relationship rebuild naturally over the next few months.','Wait for the replacement to reach out to you when they are settled into their new role.','Use the relationship with your former contact to set up the introduction to the replacement.','Email the replacement, request intro meeting, share continuity context, listen to priorities.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q015','SJT',NULL,'1','Lost Champion','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":2,\"d\":3}}'),(1460,7,'A senior client repeatedly behaves disrespectfully (raising voice, dismissive comments). Your company values the account. The MOST professional response is:','Schedule a calm 1:1 outside heated moments: name the pattern, set respectful expectations.','Tolerate it — they\'re a senior client and the account matters to your company overall.','Stop engaging with them and let your manager handle the day-to-day relationship instead.','Mirror their behaviour to assert yourself and signal you won\'t accept the disrespect.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q016','SJT',NULL,'1','Difficult Client Behaviour','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1461,7,'You are managing a large account with multiple stakeholders. Two of them — Operations and Finance — have conflicting priorities about your proposal. The MOST effective approach is:','Propose two different options and let the two stakeholders debate it amongst themselves.','Escalate the conflict to their senior leadership to resolve before continuing the work.','Meet each separately to understand interests, then design a proposal that addresses both.','Pick the more senior of the two stakeholders and align your proposal with their view.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q017','SJT',NULL,'1','Complex Stakeholder Management','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1462,7,'Your team is debating whether to raise prices by 8%. Customer surveys show modest sensitivity; revenue is strong. The MOST rigorous approach to the decision is:','Hold prices — better not to disturb a working revenue model when things are going well.','Test the increase on a defined segment for 90 days; decide based on the real evidence.','Raise prices — current strong demand and modest sensitivity supports the proposed increase.','Survey customers directly about their willingness to pay more for the current product.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q018','SJT',NULL,'1','Pricing Decision','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1463,7,'A customer has been using your core product happily for 2 years. You have an adjacent product that could add value. The MOST effective approach is:','Run a business review: listen for pain points; share the adjacent product only if it fits.','Wait for them to ask about your other offerings when they are ready to consider more.','Send them marketing material about the adjacent product to introduce it to their team.','Offer a discount on the adjacent product as an incentive to encourage them to trial it.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q019','SJT',NULL,'1','Cross-Sell Approach','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1464,7,'Your manager pushes you to forecast aggressively (high probability on uncertain deals). The MOST mature response is:','Comply with the request — managers are ultimately responsible for forecast accuracy.','Refuse to provide any forecast at all until the data warrants a clearer projection.','Use the manager\'s preferred number publicly but track your real number privately.','Push back: \"My honest read is X. I\'d rather under-promise — let me know if different.\"','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q020','SJT',NULL,'1','Forecasting Conservatism','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1465,7,'A long-time client requests a service that you don\'t offer well and would be better served by a competitor. The MOST ethical response is:','Be honest: \"This is outside our strength. [Company X] does it well — I\'d recommend them.\"','Try to deliver it anyway to retain the relationship and avoid losing them to a rival.','Decline the request politely without any further explanation to the long-time client.','Propose an inflated price to discourage them while still keeping the relationship open.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q021','SJT',NULL,'1','Saying No to Client','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1466,7,'A multi-year contract is up for renewal in 90 days. The client is satisfied but you suspect a competitor is being evaluated. The MOST effective approach is:','Offer a multi-year renewal discount to lock them in before any competitive evaluation.','Reach out to senior leadership at the client to bypass the buyer team\'s process.','Run a business review now: revisit goals, quantify value, surface any evaluation openly.','Wait for the client to make the first move when they are ready to discuss renewal terms.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q022','SJT',NULL,'1','Renewals Strategy','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1467,7,'Before a major proposal, the MOST effective preparation is to:','Polish the deck and rehearse the pitch to deliver a confident professional presentation.','Lead with your company\'s credentials and history to establish strong opening credibility.','Identify the 2-3 things the client cares most about and build the proposal around them.','Include every possible feature and capability to demonstrate the breadth of your offer.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q023','SJT',NULL,'1','Win Theme','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1468,7,'You need engineering and finance buy-in for a customer commitment you want to make. They are reluctant. The MOST effective approach is:','Drop the opportunity entirely if the internal teams won\'t support what the customer needs.','Escalate the request to senior leadership to mandate cooperation from both functions.','Make the commitment to the customer and figure out internal alignment afterwards as needed.','Engage both: understand concerns, find a version that works, go to customer with one offer.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q024','SJT',NULL,'1','Internal Selling','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1469,7,'You discover an important pattern in customer feedback that should change how your product is developed. The MOST effective way to communicate this is:','Send a long email to the product team with all the details of the pattern you found.','Build a small prototype yourself to demonstrate the need to the product team visually.','Mention the insight casually in a meeting where the product team happens to be present.','Create a brief: pattern, evidence, implication, recommendation; meet to debate it.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q025','SJT',NULL,'1','Customer Insight Sharing','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1470,7,'Your company is entering a new market segment. As an experienced commercial professional, the MOST effective first 90 days are:','Run 20-30 discovery conversations; refine positioning and offer; then begin prospecting.','Begin direct prospecting immediately to generate pipeline and validate market interest fast.','Build a comprehensive marketing campaign first to generate awareness in the new segment.','Replicate the playbook from your existing market and adjust as you learn from the segment.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q026','SJT',NULL,'1','New Market','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1471,7,'Your team is significantly below quota with one month to go in the quarter. The MOST effective response as team lead is:','Offer discounts on existing pipeline to close faster within the remaining time window.','Ask senior leadership to lower the quota since the team won\'t be able to meet it now.','Diagnose with team: where\'s the leak in the funnel? Targeted intervention on bottleneck.','Push the team to make more outbound calls to generate volume in the time remaining.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q027','SJT',NULL,'1','Team Quota Pressure','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1472,7,'A junior salesperson on your team consistently loses deals at the proposal stage. The MOST effective coaching intervention is:','Listen in on next discovery calls, debrief, co-design a proposal together next opportunity.','Take over their accounts personally for a quarter until they are ready to return to selling.','Send them to a structured sales training programme to upskill on proposal writing craft.','Review their proposals and rewrite them so the next ones land better with the customer.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q028','SJT',NULL,'1','Coaching Junior Salespeople','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1473,7,'Your team\'s CRM hygiene is poor — incomplete data, missed updates. The MOST effective intervention as team lead is:','Hire an admin to update the CRM for the team so reps can focus on selling not data entry.','Send a strongly-worded email demanding compliance from the team going forward immediately.','Make CRM accuracy visible in weekly forecast calls: stale deals can\'t be discussed there.','Threaten consequences for non-compliance to make the seriousness clear to all the team.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q029','SJT',NULL,'1','CRM Discipline','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1474,7,'You believe you are underpaid relative to your market value and contribution. The MOST effective approach is:','Wait for the annual review and hope your compensation gets addressed at that point.','Schedule a focused conversation: market data, your contributions, what you are asking for.','Get a competing offer from another company and use it as leverage in the conversation.','Mention your dissatisfaction broadly to peers to see if others feel the same way too.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q030','SJT',NULL,'1','Compensation Conversation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1475,7,'A customer is about to sign a contract for a solution that you suspect doesn\'t actually fit their need. The MOST ethical response is:','Reduce the scope of the contract to minimise any potential harm from the wrong solution.','Pause and ask: \"Before we sign, I want to make sure this is right. Here\'s my concern.\"','Close the deal — they made their own decision and they are the ones with the authority.','Mention the concern only to your manager so they can decide whether to flag it externally.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q031','SJT',NULL,'1','Ethics in Selling','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1476,7,'To strengthen your position as a trusted advisor, the MOST effective ongoing practice is:','Develop deep industry expertise: read, build relationships, write or speak publicly.','Attend more sales training to sharpen your skills in selling and customer engagement.','Increase the polish and visual quality of your proposals to differentiate your offering.','Reach out to your customers more frequently to stay top of mind in their day-to-day work.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q032','SJT',NULL,'1','Industry Insight','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1477,7,'I instinctively understand what a customer is really trying to accomplish, even when they describe it imprecisely.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q033','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Discovery Skill','{\"likert\":true}'),(1478,7,'I am confident negotiating high-stakes commercial terms with senior decision-makers.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q034','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Negotiation Confidence','{\"likert\":true}'),(1479,7,'I have deep, specific knowledge about my industry that customers find valuable.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q035','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Industry Expertise','{\"likert\":true}'),(1480,7,'I think about my key accounts strategically (whitespace, stakeholder maps, growth opportunities), not just transactionally.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q036','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Strategic Account Thinking','{\"likert\":true}'),(1481,7,'I am comfortable with the commercial math — unit economics, margins, customer LTV, pricing analysis.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q037','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Commercial Numeracy','{\"likert\":true}'),(1482,7,'I can effectively coordinate internal stakeholders (engineering, finance, ops) to deliver for customers.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q038','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Cross-Functional Influence','{\"likert\":true}'),(1483,7,'After losing a major deal, I can reflect, learn, and move forward without lingering damage to my motivation.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q039','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Resilience to Loss','{\"likert\":true}'),(1484,7,'I am comfortable investing in customer relationships and pipeline that may take 12+ months to convert.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q040','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Long-game Patience','{\"likert\":true}'),(1485,7,'I am willing to walk away from deals that don\'t fit, even when the revenue would help my numbers.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q041','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Walking Away','{\"likert\":true}'),(1486,7,'I enjoy coaching other commercial professionals and can identify what they need to develop.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q042','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Coaching Others','{\"likert\":true}'),(1487,7,'When deals are stuck, my first instinct is usually to offer a discount.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q043','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','1','Discount Reflex','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1488,7,'I tend to deprioritise time with difficult customers in favour of easier ones.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q044','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','1','Avoidance of Difficult Customers','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1489,7,'How often do you read industry publications, attend industry events, or have conversations with industry peers outside your customer base? PILLAR 02  ·  LEADERSHIP & INFLUENCE Leading teams, coaching, difficult conversations, cross-functional influence, organisational change, and the mid-career leadership behaviours that separate strong individual contributors from credible leaders. Items in this pillar: 45','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q045','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','1','Industry Learning','{\"likert\":true}'),(1490,7,'The GROW coaching model (developed by Sir John Whitmore) structures coaching conversations through:','Growth, Resilience, Outcomes, Wins.','Goal, Risk, Outcomes, Wins captured.','Goal, Reality, Options, Will.','Guide, Review, Optimise, Wrap up.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q046','K',NULL,'2','Coaching Model','[]'),(1491,7,'Patrick Lencioni\'s \'Five Dysfunctions of a Team\' identifies the foundational dysfunction as:','Absence of trust.','Unclear strategy.','Lack of skill diversity.','Inadequate resources.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q047','K',NULL,'2','Trust','[]'),(1492,7,'Adam Grant\'s research distinguishes \'givers\' from \'takers\' in workplace relationships. His finding about givers is:','Givers cluster at both the top and the bottom of outcomes.','Takers consistently outperform givers in competitive contexts.','Givers and takers achieve identical career outcomes overall.','Givers consistently finish last in their career outcomes.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q048','K',NULL,'2','Influence','[]'),(1493,7,'In Kim Scott\'s \'Radical Candor\' framework, effective feedback combines:','Strict professionalism with no personal warmth shown.','Maximum directness regardless of relationship.','Caring without challenge, to protect the relationship.','Caring personally and challenging directly.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q049','K',NULL,'2','Difficult Conversations','[]'),(1494,7,'Brené Brown\'s research on leadership identifies vulnerability as:','Sharing personal details widely across the workplace teams.','A form of weakness that should be hidden from colleagues.','An optional quality found in some highly effective leaders.','The willingness to show up when the outcome is uncertain.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q050','K',NULL,'2','Vulnerability','[]'),(1495,7,'French and Raven\'s classic taxonomy of social power identifies five (later six) bases. The ones grounded in personal qualities rather than position are:','Legitimate and reward power.','Reward and coercive power.','Coercive and legitimate power.','Expert and referent power.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q051','K',NULL,'2','Power Dynamics','[]'),(1496,7,'In \'Crucial Conversations\' (Patterson et al.), the recommended first step when a difficult conversation goes wrong is to:','Push your point more forcefully to keep the conversation alive.','End the conversation and try again at a later time.','Step back and restore psychological safety before continuing.','Apologise and concede ground to keep the relationship intact.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q052','K',NULL,'2','Crucial Conversations','[]'),(1497,7,'BJ Fogg\'s Behaviour Model proposes that behaviour occurs when three elements converge simultaneously:','Knowledge, Skill, and Desire.','Motivation, Ability, and Prompt.','Intention, Capability, and Time.','Habit, Reward, and Trigger Cue.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q053','K',NULL,'2','Behavioural Change','[]'),(1498,7,'Edwin Locke\'s goal-setting theory (one of the most empirically supported theories in management) shows that the most effective goals are:','Vague but inspiring, leaving room for personal interpretation.','Easy enough that success is virtually guaranteed.','Privately held to avoid social pressure of any kind.','Specific and challenging, with clear feedback on progress.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q054','K',NULL,'2','Goal Setting','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1499,7,'The distinction between a mentor and a sponsor in career development is:','Mentors are external to the company; sponsors are always internal.','Mentor and sponsor describe essentially the same role today.','Mentors advise you; sponsors actively advocate for your advancement.','Sponsors are paid for their time; mentors typically work without pay.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q055','K',NULL,'2','Mentorship','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1500,7,'You have just been promoted to manage a team that has been underperforming for 18 months. Your boss expects rapid improvement. The MOST effective first 30 days are:','Run 1:1s, observe meetings, talk to customers and boss — diagnose root cause first.','Maintain current operations and observe for 90 days before making any major changes.','Announce a new strategy and set ambitious targets immediately to drive a step change.','Replace the lowest performers immediately to signal change and create capacity for new hires.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q056','SJT',NULL,'2','Inheriting Underperforming Team','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1501,7,'You have just been promoted to manage former peers. The MOST effective first conversation with each direct report is:','Acknowledge change: \"Our relationship is shifting. Let\'s talk about what we each need.\"','Continue as if nothing has changed in the relationship to avoid creating awkwardness.','Avoid one-on-one meetings until the new dynamic between you settles down naturally.','Establish authority by making clear changes immediately to set the new dynamic up front.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q057','SJT',NULL,'2','Promoted Above Peers','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1502,7,'One of your top-performing team members consistently exhibits behaviour that damages team morale (sarcasm, exclusion, talking over others). The MOST effective action is:','Move them to a more isolated role where their behaviour affects other team members less.','Tolerate the behaviour — their high performance is essential to the team\'s results overall.','Address it through subtle hints in team meetings to model the behaviour you want from them.','Direct conversation: name behaviours, share impact, make clear it\'s non-negotiable now.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q058','SJT',NULL,'2','High-Performer With Behaviour Issue','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1503,7,'Your boss has set a strategic direction you strongly disagree with. You have already raised your view; the boss has decided. The MOST mature response is:','Maintain professional distance — implement the strategy but don\'t actively support it.','Implement the strategy and signal to your team that it wasn\'t the choice you would have made.','Commit fully: \"The call has been made; my job is to make it succeed. Here\'s why we do this.\"','Continue to lobby internally for your view to try to influence the decision over time.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q059','SJT',NULL,'2','Strategic Disagreement','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1504,7,'Two of your direct reports are in conflict over resource allocation — each believes they need a key team member full-time. The MOST effective approach is:','Decide for them yourself based on which of the two initiatives seems more important now.','Tell them to figure it out between themselves without further involvement from you.','Bring them together: define criteria, have them present cases, mediate trade-off together.','Split the resource 50/50 between the two of them to be fair to both initiatives equally.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q060','SJT',NULL,'2','Resource Allocation Conflict','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1505,7,'Your company has just announced major restructuring. Your team is anxious and rumours are flying. The MOST effective leadership posture is:','Be present and honest: share what\'s known, acknowledge what\'s not, hold space for concerns.','Share your own uncertainty and worries openly to bond with the team during the upheaval.','Reassure them that everything will be fine and that there is nothing they need to worry about.','Avoid the topic of restructuring and focus the team on their day-to-day work instead.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q061','SJT',NULL,'2','Leading During Crisis','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1506,7,'You are leading a project with team members from multiple departments who don\'t report to you. Two members are not delivering. The MOST effective approach is:','Escalate the issue to their managers immediately to enforce accountability through them.','Private conversation with each: share observations, agree changes; escalate if needed.','Take over their work yourself to keep the project on track without confronting the issue.','Send a strongly worded email to the entire project group to put pressure on the laggards.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q062','SJT',NULL,'2','Cross-Functional Project Lead','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1507,7,'It is annual review time. A direct report has had a strong year overall but with one significant negative incident. The MOST effective approach is:','Discuss both with evidence; use the negative incident as development not defining narrative.','Skip the negative incident because the year was strong overall on most other measures.','Focus on the strengths and minimise the incident to maintain the team member\'s morale.','Lead with the negative incident upfront to make the consequences of it very clear to them.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q063','SJT',NULL,'2','Performance Review','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1508,7,'You need your team to adopt a major new way of working. You announce it; resistance is significant. The MOST effective response is:','Slow down: listening sessions, address concerns, equip the team, re-launch with their input.','Abandon the change altogether to maintain team morale and avoid further organisational conflict.','Implement with the willing team members; let the resisters opt out for now and join later.','Enforce the change firmly across the team — resistance must be overcome to deliver impact.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q064','SJT',NULL,'2','Leading Change','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1509,7,'Your team has delivered an exceptional outcome. Senior leadership wants to publicly recognise the work. The MOST effective response as the team\'s manager is:','Suggest the recognition go to the most senior members of the team for the achievement.','Accept the recognition graciously on behalf of the whole team in your role as the manager.','Name specific team members and contributions publicly, especially the less visible ones.','Deflect with \"It was a team effort\" to share the credit equally across the whole team.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q065','SJT',NULL,'2','Recognition','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1510,7,'You want to develop a high-potential team member by giving them a stretch assignment. The MOST effective design of this assignment is:','Give them a task far above their current capability to force rapid growth through challenge.','Assign them to shadow you on your hardest work so they can learn by close observation.','Give them more of what they already do well to build on their existing strong base of work.','Give them something challenging where success is plausible — with criteria, support, freedom.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q066','SJT',NULL,'2','Stretch Assignment','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1511,7,'Your boss asks you to take on a project that you believe is misaligned with strategic priorities. The MOST effective response is:','Share view: \"Before I commit, want to flag a concern. How are you thinking about this?\"','Take it on without comment to maintain a good working relationship with your boss going forward.','Accept the project but plan to push back on it later once you have more information.','Refuse the request and explain to your boss exactly why you think it is the wrong call.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q067','SJT',NULL,'2','Saying No to Boss','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1512,7,'You have an open role. Three candidates are similar in qualifications; two have backgrounds well-represented on your team, one has a background under-represented. The MOST appropriate approach is:','Evaluate all three on the merits; count team diversity as a meaningful performance contributor.','Run a final assessment specifically designed to differentiate them objectively on the work.','Hire the under-represented candidate specifically to improve the diversity of your current team.','Hire based purely on quantifiable criteria, ignoring background entirely in the decision process.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q068','SJT',NULL,'2','Diversity Hiring','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":2,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1513,7,'You discover that two team members in similar roles have a significant pay gap that you cannot justify on performance grounds. The MOST appropriate action is:','Quietly adjust the gap at the next compensation review cycle without flagging it explicitly.','Inform the underpaid employee directly so they can advocate for themselves with HR.','Raise with HR: present the data, advocate for correction, follow through transparently.','Maintain the status quo for now — pay history at the company is complicated to address.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q069','SJT',NULL,'2','Compensation Equity','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1514,7,'Your team has been running flat-out for 3 months and showing signs of collective exhaustion. Targets are still pressing. The MOST effective response is:','Push the team harder — the targets must be met regardless of how exhausted people feel.','Step back: cut or defer work; negotiate scope; build in real recovery time for team.','Hire more people to relieve the load on the existing team members in the short term.','Allow more flexible working hours to ease the pressure on team members across the week.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q070','SJT',NULL,'2','Team Burnout','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1515,7,'You made a decision 2 months ago that has clearly turned out to be wrong, with team consequences. The MOST effective response is:','Avoid public discussion of the issue to preserve your authority as the team\'s leader.','Move forward without dwelling on the mistake — looking back doesn\'t change the past now.','Identify contributing factors that led to the wrong decision to share context with the team.','Acknowledge to team: \"I made the call on X. Here\'s what I missed; here\'s the plan now.\"','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q071','SJT',NULL,'2','Owning Mistake to Team','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1516,7,'A senior leader is repeatedly sending you work requests at 11pm with expectations of next-morning responses. The MOST mature response is:','Address it: \"I need to draw a line on after-hours except genuine emergencies. Here\'s how.\"','Respond only during working hours and let the senior leader notice the new pattern over time.','Comply with the requests but reduce the quality of your output to manage your time better.','Comply with the requests to maintain a strong working relationship with the senior leader.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q072','SJT',NULL,'2','Boundary with Senior','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1517,7,'A junior person reaches out asking you to mentor them. You have limited capacity. The MOST appropriate response is:','Offer a bounded relationship: \"30 minutes monthly for 6 months with a specific question.\"','Decline politely and let them know you don\'t have time to take on a mentee right now.','Suggest they find someone else better suited to mentor them on the topics they care about.','Accept the request formally — investing in mentorship is important for the next generation.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q073','SJT',NULL,'2','Mentoring Junior','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1518,7,'A star performer on your team is plateauing. They\'re still hitting numbers but development has stalled. The MOST effective intervention is:','Leave them alone — they are still performing well and don\'t need any additional intervention.','Increase their compensation to maintain their motivation and reduce the risk of attrition.','Honest chat: \"Your edge is dulling. What\'s keeping you engaged? Co-design your next stretch.\"','Give them more work to keep them challenged and prevent them from getting bored over time.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q074','SJT',NULL,'2','Coaching Star Performer','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1519,7,'After 6 months of clear documented feedback and support, a team member is still not meeting standards. The MOST appropriate next step is:','Continue providing support indefinitely — give them more time to turn the situation around.','Push them to resign by making the role miserable so they choose to leave on their own.','Reduce their responsibilities and hope they stay quietly in a reduced role going forward.','Direct conversation with HR: this isn\'t working, here\'s the path, treat them well in exit.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q075','SJT',NULL,'2','Letting Someone Go','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1520,7,'I derive genuine satisfaction from developing other people, even when I don\'t get credit.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q076','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Developing Others','{\"likert\":true}'),(1521,7,'I am willing to have difficult conversations promptly rather than letting issues accumulate.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q077','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Difficult Conversations','{\"likert\":true}'),(1522,7,'I can hold strategic patience even when short-term pressure is high.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q078','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Strategic Patience','{\"likert\":true}'),(1523,7,'When someone gives me critical feedback, I can hear it without immediately defending.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q079','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Receiving Hard Truth','{\"likert\":true}'),(1524,7,'I delegate work effectively, trusting others to deliver in their own way.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q080','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Delegation','{\"likert\":true}'),(1525,7,'I stay composed and effective when those around me are stressed or in crisis.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q081','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Composure','{\"likert\":true}'),(1526,7,'I make my team\'s specific contributions visible to senior leadership.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q082','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Sharing Credit','{\"likert\":true}'),(1527,7,'I can step back from operational details and see strategic patterns.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q083','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Strategic Thinking','{\"likert\":true}'),(1528,7,'I am willing to take unpopular positions when I believe they are right.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q084','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Courage','{\"likert\":true}'),(1529,7,'I have a clear personal sense of what kind of leader I want to be.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q085','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Self-Authorship','{\"likert\":true}'),(1530,7,'I sometimes avoid hard conversations because I don\'t want to damage relationships.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q086','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','2','Avoidance','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1531,7,'When I delegate, I tend to check in more often than necessary or take work back when it\'s not done my way.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q087','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','2','Micromanagement','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1532,7,'Most of my team\'s challenges are due to factors outside my control.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q088','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','2','External Locus','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1533,7,'How often do you spend dedicated time coaching or developing your direct reports (beyond operational discussions)?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q089','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','2','Coaching Time','{\"likert\":true}'),(1534,7,'How often do you set aside time to think strategically — about your team, your function, or the business — rather than just executing? PILLAR 03  ·  PERSONALITY & COMMUNICATION Executive presence, stakeholder management, structured written and verbal communication, navigating cross-cultural and hierarchical complexity - the communication skills that determine your professional ceiling. Items in this pillar: 40','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q090','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','2','Strategic Reflection','{\"likert\":true}'),(1535,7,'A standard stakeholder mapping framework plots stakeholders on which two dimensions?','Friendliness and Difficulty score.','Power and Interest in the outcome.','Seniority and Department status.','Internal status and Tenure level.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q091','K',NULL,'3','Stakeholder Mapping','[]'),(1536,7,'In communicating with senior executives, the strongest opening line is generally:','The recommendation or insight in a single sentence.','The background context that sets up the discussion.','An anecdote chosen to engage their attention quickly.','A summary of the methodology used in the analysis.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q092','K',NULL,'3','Executive Communication','[]'),(1537,7,'Cialdini\'s principle of \'commitment and consistency\' suggests that:','Leaders are preferred when they behave consistently across contexts.','Commitments must be repeated consistently over a long time.','Small public commitments lead to larger consistent actions.','Consistent messaging is more persuasive than varied messaging.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q093','K',NULL,'3','Influence Mechanism','[]'),(1538,7,'The \'Hero\'s Journey\' narrative structure, popularised by Joseph Campbell and useful in business storytelling, follows the basic arc:','Background, action, outcome — a chronological story shape.','Setup, middle, end — a classical three-part dramatic shape.','Problem, analysis, recommendation, action — a consulting arc.','Ordinary world, call, trials, transformation, return.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q094','K',NULL,'3','Storytelling','[]'),(1539,7,'The SBI (Situation-Behaviour-Impact) feedback model frames feedback as:','Skill being assessed, behaviour observed, suggested improvement.','State of mind, belief held, and inquiry made.','Strategy in play, behaviour shown, intent inferred.','Situation, observable behaviour, and the impact it had.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q095','K',NULL,'3','Feedback Model','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1540,7,'Chris Voss\'s negotiation principle of \'tactical empathy\' is best described as:','Concealing your real position to gain a negotiating edge.','Demonstrating understanding of the other side explicitly.','Pretending to agree with the other side to build trust.','Using emotional appeals to win the argument decisively.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q096','K',NULL,'3','Negotiation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1541,7,'You have 10 minutes with the CEO to brief on a critical project. The MOST effective use of that time is:','First minute: status, decision needed, biggest risk. Next 6-7: detail. Final: explicit asks.','Present detailed analysis throughout to demonstrate the rigour of the team\'s work to date.','Open with the team\'s recent accomplishments to set a positive tone for the conversation.','Walk through the project chronologically from inception through to its current state today.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q097','SJT',NULL,'3','Executive Briefing','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1542,7,'You need to email a senior stakeholder about a significant project setback. The MOST effective email structure is:','Bottom line first; then cause, implications, recovery plan with checkpoints, your ask, offer.','Comprehensive narrative with the full context first before the recommendation at the end.','Lead with an apology, then the context, then the recovery plan for the project ahead.','Brief mention of the issue with an offer to discuss the details verbally at a later time.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q098','SJT',NULL,'3','Difficult Email','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1543,7,'Two senior stakeholders have given you contradictory direction on a project. The MOST appropriate response is:','Surface conflict to both: \"I\'m getting different direction. Could we align on this together?\"','Go with the more senior of the two stakeholders to minimise the political risk to yourself.','Pick the one who escalates more to avoid getting into trouble with the louder stakeholder.','Average the two pieces of direction to balance both viewpoints in your project\'s execution.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q099','SJT',NULL,'3','Stakeholder Conflict','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1544,7,'A senior leader (not your direct manager) asks you to do work that\'s outside your remit and would compete with your priorities. The MOST mature response is:','Comply with the request — senior leaders\' asks trump your normal priorities for the day.','Engage warmly: \"Let me check with my manager since this affects priorities. Back in 24 hours.\"','Take it on and quietly deprioritise existing work to make room for the new senior request.','Refuse the request — they should know to go through the proper channels for cross-team work.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q100','SJT',NULL,'3','Saying No to Senior Request','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1545,7,'You need to deliver tough performance feedback to a long-tenured team member who is sensitive. The MOST effective approach is:','Be clear and specific: lead with respect, share evidence, listen, co-design path forward.','Deliver the feedback via written message to give the team member space to process it alone.','Soften the feedback significantly to protect their feelings and the long-standing relationship.','Have HR present in the conversation to formalise the feedback and add appropriate weight.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q101','SJT',NULL,'3','Performance Conversation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1546,7,'In a senior meeting, a peer publicly mischaracterises your team\'s work. The MOST mature response is:','Send a written correction to all the attendees of the meeting once the session has ended.','Calmly add factual clarity: \"I want to add some context — [specific factual point here].\"','Stay silent during the meeting and address the issue with them privately afterwards.','Correct them firmly in the moment to defend your team\'s reputation in front of leadership.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q102','SJT',NULL,'3','Public Disagreement','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1547,7,'A team member comes to you upset about a workplace situation. The MOST useful first response is:','Offer your perspective and advice on what they should do about the situation immediately.','Ask what kind of support they want: \"To vent, to get advice, or for me to do something?\"','Listen quietly without responding so they have the space to fully express their feelings.','Suggest they take the issue up directly with HR if it is serious enough to warrant action.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q103','SJT',NULL,'3','Listening','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1548,7,'You are giving a major presentation to 200+ people. 5 minutes in, your slide deck fails. The MOST effective in-the-moment response is:','End the presentation early since the slides are essential to delivering the full message.','Apologise repeatedly to the audience and ask for the technical issue to be fixed quickly.','Stay composed, acknowledge briefly with humour, proceed with the content you already know.','Read your speaker notes directly to the audience until the slides come back online again.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q104','SJT',NULL,'3','Public Speaking','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1549,7,'You\'ve drafted an important email and re-read it. You realise the tone might come across as defensive or sharp. The MOST appropriate response is:','Send it as is — your point is valid and the recipient should hear it as you wrote it.','Send a shorter version of the email without the sharp parts but with the main message intact.','Set it aside for hours; re-read with fresh eyes; rewrite to be clear without being sharp.','Send with a softening note (\"apologies if this comes across strongly to you\") at the top.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q105','SJT',NULL,'3','Written Communication','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":2,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1550,7,'You meet someone influential at a conference. The MOST effective way to build a meaningful ongoing relationship is:','Wait for them to reach out to you if they are interested in building the relationship.','Connect on LinkedIn with a generic invitation message after the conference ends each day.','Within 24-48 hours: specific note, share something useful, easy way to stay connected.','Ask them directly for a follow-up coffee meeting to continue the conversation further.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q106','SJT',NULL,'3','Networking','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":2}}'),(1551,7,'Working with a global team, you notice your direct feedback style isn\'t landing well with members from cultures with less direct communication norms. The MOST effective adaptation is:','Maintain your own style — they should adapt to professional norms common in the company.','Have someone from their own culture deliver the feedback on your behalf to them instead.','Adapt: more warmth, indirectness, face-saving framing; keep content clarity, adjust form.','Stop giving feedback to those team members to avoid the issue entirely going forward.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q107','SJT',NULL,'3','Cross-Cultural Sensitivity','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1552,7,'You have important information that contradicts a senior leader\'s stated position in a meeting. The MOST mature approach is:','Stay silent — the senior leader may not appreciate being publicly contradicted in front of others.','Mention the issue privately to the senior leader after the meeting has ended that day.','Add as data: \"I have some recent data that points in a different direction. Worth factoring?\"','Contradict them firmly with the evidence to make sure the right information is on the table.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q108','SJT',NULL,'3','Speaking Up','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":2,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1553,7,'A peer has been undermining you in conversations with leadership. You have observed it twice. The MOST mature response is:','Mirror their behaviour by undermining them in conversations with leadership in return.','Escalate the issue to your shared manager and let them handle the conflict between you.','Calm direct chat: \"In two recent conversations I noticed X. What\'s going on for you?\"','Confront them privately and demand that the undermining behaviour stop with immediate effect.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q109','SJT',NULL,'3','Conflict with Peer','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1554,7,'You receive a series of urgent emails throughout the day. The MOST effective email management approach is generally:','Respond quickly to senior people only and to others whenever it is convenient to do so.','Respond immediately to every single email to maintain a reputation for being responsive.','Batch processing into 2-3 dedicated periods per day; protect deep work from interruption.','Keep email open all day to react to incoming requests in real time as they arrive.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q110','SJT',NULL,'3','Email Reply Discipline','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1555,7,'You\'re invited to a recurring weekly meeting that you find low-value. The MOST appropriate response is:','Decline all future invitations to that meeting with a brief note explaining the decision.','Speak with the owner: \"Could we discuss what\'s useful or whether async updates might work?\"','Continue attending — declining the meeting might signal disengagement to the team\'s leader.','Attend but multitask quietly to save time and complete other work in parallel during it.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q111','SJT',NULL,'3','Meeting Discipline','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1556,7,'You want to build your professional reputation on LinkedIn. The MOST effective long-term strategy is:','Post inspirational content daily to build a wide following through reach across the platform.','Comment on every post in your network to maximise visibility across the platform daily.','Share specific perspectives on your domain — from real work and real lessons, consistently.','Repost trending business content to associate yourself with what the wider industry discusses.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q112','SJT',NULL,'3','Personal Brand Online','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1557,7,'In a meeting, a stakeholder becomes openly hostile toward you. The MOST effective in-the-moment response is:','Stay silent and let them finish what they are saying before responding at the end.','Stay calm: \"This matters to you. Help me understand what\'s driving the reaction.\"','Defend yourself firmly in the moment to establish that you won\'t be bullied in meetings.','Walk out of the meeting to avoid further escalation of the hostile dynamic with them.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q113','SJT',NULL,'3','Handling Hostility','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1558,7,'You\'re aware of upcoming restructuring that will affect your team. Some team members are starting to ask if rumours are true. The MOST appropriate response is:','Deny the rumours outright to maintain team stability through the uncertain period ahead.','Confirm what you know to maintain trust with the team during the uncertain period ahead.','Be honest about what you can and can\'t share now; commit to telling them as soon as possible.','Tell them to stop spreading rumours since they aren\'t helping the team\'s morale right now.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q114','SJT',NULL,'3','Sharing Sensitive Info','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1559,7,'I am comfortable communicating with very senior leaders, including the CEO or board.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q115','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Executive Presence','{\"likert\":true}'),(1560,7,'My written communication is consistently clear, concise, and well-structured.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q116','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Written Communication','{\"likert\":true}'),(1561,7,'I am usually fully present when listening, rather than formulating my reply.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q117','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Listening Depth','{\"likert\":true}'),(1562,7,'I adapt my communication style fluidly across cultures, levels, and personalities.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q118','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Adaptable Style','{\"likert\":true}'),(1563,7,'I am comfortable speaking to large audiences (50+ people).','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q119','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Public Speaking','{\"likert\":true}'),(1564,7,'I initiate difficult conversations promptly rather than letting issues simmer.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q120','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Difficult Conversations','{\"likert\":true}'),(1565,7,'I am usually aware of what I\'m feeling in the moment, and why.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q121','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Emotional Awareness','{\"likert\":true}'),(1566,7,'I can usually read what others are feeling, even when they don\'t say it.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q122','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Other Awareness','{\"likert\":true}'),(1567,7,'I give feedback to others that is honest, specific, and actionable.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q123','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Feedback Giving','{\"likert\":true}'),(1568,7,'My sense of who I am is stable — I do not need others\' approval to feel okay.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q124','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Self-confidence','{\"likert\":true}'),(1569,7,'I stay composed and clear-thinking under stress.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q125','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Composure Under Stress','{\"likert\":true}'),(1570,7,'I speak in meetings when I have something to add, but not just to be seen.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q126','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Voice Discipline','{\"likert\":true}'),(1571,7,'I tell stories effectively to communicate business points.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q127','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Storytelling','{\"likert\":true}'),(1572,7,'When I\'m criticised, I often react before I think.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q128','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','3','Reactivity','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1573,7,'I often think of the right thing to say only after the moment has passed.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q129','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','3','Hesitation','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1574,7,'How often do you reflect after important conversations on what you communicated well and what you could have done better? PILLAR 04  ·  MENTAL WELLNESS & RESILIENCE Burnout prevention, mid-career identity, sustained performance habits, navigating career plateaus, and the wellness disciplines that determine whether a long career is energising or exhausting. Items in this pillar: 35','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q130','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','3','Communication Reflection','{\"likert\":true}'),(1575,7,'Christina Maslach\'s burnout research identifies three core dimensions of burnout:','Exhaustion, cynicism, and reduced professional efficacy.','Stress reaction, frustration, and chronic overwhelm signs.','Physical fatigue, emotional fatigue, and mental fatigue.','Anger, anxiety, and depressive symptoms taken together.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q131','K',NULL,'4','Burnout Stages','[]'),(1576,7,'Research on recovery from work strain identifies which combination as MOST effective?','More sleep alone is sufficient to recover from any work strain.','Intense exercise to compensate for mental fatigue from work.','Disengagement, relaxation, mastery activities, and autonomy.','Complete inactivity to allow the body to fully restore itself.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q132','K',NULL,'4','Recovery','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1577,7,'Research on habit formation (Lally et al. 2009) found that on average, a new behaviour becomes habitual after approximately:','66 days, with significant variation by behaviour type.','21 days, regardless of the behaviour being established.','30 days for almost any new behaviour pattern.','6 months minimum to establish any new habit.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q133','K',NULL,'4','Habit Formation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1578,7,'You feel you\'ve stopped growing in your current role. The MOST constructive response is:','Wait for the next promotion cycle in the hope that a new role will create growth again.','Accept that mid-career plateaus are normal and just continue performing in the current role.','Diagnose what\'s stalled; design action: stretch, lateral move, mentor; talk to manager openly.','Start looking for external opportunities at other companies to find your next stretch role.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q134','SJT',NULL,'4','Career Plateau','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1579,7,'Your family is struggling with your work hours. The MOST sustainable response is:','Reduce work hours immediately, taking whatever career hit that decision creates for you.','Direct chat at home and work; redesign schedule rather than just adding more personal capacity.','Tell them this is the demand of mid-career life and they need to adjust accordingly.','Promise to do better at home and try to manage with more efficiency in your existing hours.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q135','SJT',NULL,'4','Family vs Work','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1580,7,'You realise you have been burned out for over a year — chronic exhaustion, cynicism, reduced effectiveness. The MOST effective response is:','Look for a new job since the current one is probably the wrong fit for you right now.','Take a real break — vacation or sabbatical — to recover and identify structural changes.','Try meditation and exercise to rebuild your energy gradually over the coming months ahead.','Push through — this is what mid-career professional resilience really looks like in practice.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q136','SJT',NULL,'4','Long-term Burnout','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1581,7,'You realise the career you\'ve built is no longer what you want. The MOST mature response is:','Continue the current career and just tolerate the dissatisfaction since change is too hard.','Make a dramatic change immediately — quit your current role and pivot to something new now.','Explore: what\'s not working, what would, what\'s possible; small tests; 1-2 year transition.','Talk to a career coach to help you find a new direction that suits where you are now.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q137','SJT',NULL,'4','Mid-Career Identity','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":2}}'),(1582,7,'Your social media feed keeps showing peers\' apparent successes — promotions, awards, expensive purchases. It is affecting your mood. The MOST effective response is:','Quit all social media entirely to remove the source of the comparison from your daily life.','Recognise the comparison trap: curate feed, reduce passive scrolling, focus on your own goals.','Work harder to try to match the successes of your peers that you see in your feed.','Post more of your own successes to balance the comparison happening on the platform.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q138','SJT',NULL,'4','Comparison Anxiety','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1583,7,'You\'ve been feeling persistently low, with low energy and loss of interest, for 4+ weeks. The MOST appropriate action is:','Take a long vacation to reset and recover from the period of low mood you\'ve been having.','Try more meditation and exercise to rebuild your wellbeing over the coming weeks ahead.','Push through and wait for the low mood to pass naturally over the coming weeks ahead.','Talk to a trusted person and engage a mental health professional; early help is better.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q139','SJT',NULL,'4','Mental Health Help','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1584,7,'Your manager has been sending late-night requests for 3 months. You\'re exhausted. The MOST mature response is:','Direct chat: \"After-hours is affecting effectiveness. Can we manage urgency better?\"','Stop responding after 8pm and let your manager notice the new pattern over the coming weeks.','Tolerate it — managers\' demands often need to trump personal boundaries in mid-career roles.','Look for a new job at a different company since the pattern is unlikely to change here.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q140','SJT',NULL,'4','Boundary with Boss','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1585,7,'You realise you\'ve been adding commitments faster than you\'ve been removing them. The MOST effective response is:','Work harder to keep up with everything that has been added to your plate over recent months.','Take a vacation to reset and recover from the buildup before continuing as before afterwards.','Hire help to handle some of the workload so you can keep all your existing commitments.','Audit commitments: cut, defer, renegotiate; honest conversations; add nothing new for 30 days.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q141','SJT',NULL,'4','Saying No to Self','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1586,7,'I have effective ways to manage stress that work reliably for me.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q142','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Stress Management','{\"likert\":true}'),(1587,7,'I prioritise sleep consistently, even during demanding periods.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q143','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Sleep','{\"likert\":true}'),(1588,7,'I have ways to genuinely recover from intense periods, not just distract myself.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q144','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Recovery','{\"likert\":true}'),(1589,7,'I manage my energy across the day and week, not just my time.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q145','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Energy Management','{\"likert\":true}'),(1590,7,'I have a clear sense of what gives my work meaning beyond money or status.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q146','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Purpose Clarity','{\"likert\":true}'),(1591,7,'I say no to requests that would compromise my wellbeing or other priorities.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q147','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Boundary Setting','{\"likert\":true}'),(1592,7,'I am comfortable asking for help — at work or personally.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q148','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Help-Seeking','{\"likert\":true}'),(1593,7,'I have at least one person I can be completely honest with about my struggles.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q149','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Support Network','{\"likert\":true}'),(1594,7,'My sense of self does not depend entirely on my career.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q150','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Identity Beyond Work','{\"likert\":true}'),(1595,7,'I maintain my physical health (exercise, nutrition, regular check-ups).','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q151','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Physical Health','{\"likert\":true}'),(1596,7,'I think about what matters over 10+ years, not just the current quarter.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q152','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Long-term Perspective','{\"likert\":true}'),(1597,7,'When I make mistakes, I treat myself with the kindness I would offer a friend.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q153','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Self-compassion','{\"likert\":true}'),(1598,7,'I can accept things I cannot change and focus my energy on what I can.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q154','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Acceptance','{\"likert\":true}'),(1599,7,'I can find genuine appreciation for what is good even during difficult periods.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q155','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Gratitude','{\"likert\":true}'),(1600,7,'I often feel I\'m running on fumes and barely keeping up.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q156','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','4','Burnout Signals','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1601,7,'I find myself feeling more cynical about work and people than I used to.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q157','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','4','Cynicism','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1602,7,'When I\'m stressed, I turn to screens, food, or substances to numb rather than address what\'s happening.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q158','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','4','Avoidance Coping','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1603,7,'How often do you get at least 7 hours of sleep?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q159','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Sleep','{\"likert\":true}'),(1604,7,'How often do you exercise (at least 30 minutes)?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q160','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Movement','{\"likert\":true}'),(1605,7,'How often do you spend time mindfully (meditation, reflection, technology-free time)?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q161','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Mindfulness','{\"likert\":true}'),(1606,7,'How often do you have real conversations with people you care about (not just messages)?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q162','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Connection','{\"likert\":true}'),(1607,7,'How often do you say no to requests that would exceed your capacity?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q163','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Boundaries','{\"likert\":true}'),(1608,7,'How often do you take real vacations where you fully disconnect from work?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q164','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Vacation','{\"likert\":true}'),(1609,7,'How often do you spend meaningful time on activities outside work that you find energising? PILLAR 05  ·  TECHNOLOGY & DIGITAL FLUENCY AI literacy at a professional level, data interpretation, digital transformation, cybersecurity judgment, and the technology fluency required of mid-career professionals in modern organisations. Items in this pillar: 35','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q165','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Hobbies','{\"likert\":true}'),(1610,7,'Which is the MOST important practical limitation of current LLMs (like ChatGPT, Claude) for professional use?','They are too costly to use for routine professional purposes.','They work only in English and not in any other languages.','They can confidently produce false content requiring checks.','They are too slow to be useful in modern professional workflows.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q166','K',NULL,'5','AI Literacy','[]'),(1611,7,'Which is MOST effective when getting useful outputs from an AI assistant?','Send the same question multiple times to ensure accuracy.','Use the most formal language possible in your request.','Provide context, role, format, examples, and iterate.','Ask in a single short and direct question for clarity.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q167','K',NULL,'5','Prompt Engineering','[]'),(1612,7,'India\'s Digital Personal Data Protection Act (DPDP), 2023, broadly:','Applies only to data held by Indian government departments.','Governs processing of personal data of individuals in India.','Affects only companies operating in the Indian IT services sector.','Has not yet been enacted into Indian law and is still pending.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q168','K',NULL,'5','Data Privacy','[]'),(1613,7,'The three major cloud platforms most commonly used by enterprises are:','Heroku, Vercel, Netlify Hosting.','AWS, Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud.','Dropbox, OneDrive, Google Drive Storage.','Cloudflare, Akamai, Fastly Edge CDN.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q169','K',NULL,'5','Cloud Services','[]'),(1614,7,'Which of the following is the SINGLE most important cybersecurity practice for an individual professional?','Two-factor authentication plus a password manager.','Using up-to-date antivirus software on all devices.','Avoiding the use of public Wi-Fi networks entirely.','Regularly clearing browser history and cookies.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q170','K',NULL,'5','Cybersecurity','[]'),(1615,7,'In data interpretation, the difference between correlation and causation is:','Correlation shows movement together; causation shows cause-and-effect.','Correlation is a statistical concept; causation is purely anecdotal.','Correlation and causation are essentially the same in business contexts.','Causation is simply a stronger form of correlation between variables.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q171','K',NULL,'5','Data Analysis','[]'),(1616,7,'A \'p-value\' in statistical testing represents:','Size of the effect being measured by the test.','Probability that the research hypothesis is true.','Probability of the data given the null hypothesis.','Percentage of certainty in the resulting test.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q172','K',NULL,'5','Statistical Significance','[]'),(1617,7,'In modern professional work, the MOST effective use of AI productivity tools is:','Augmenting human judgment on tasks with verifiable outputs.','Limiting use to creative tasks like writing and ideation.','Restricting use to low-stakes work where errors don\'t matter.','Replacing human work entirely wherever that is feasible.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q173','K',NULL,'5','Productivity Tools','[]'),(1618,7,'\'Digital transformation\' in business is best characterised as:','Hiring more software engineers across the entire organisation.','Rethinking business models through digital capabilities.','Adopting new software tools to do existing work faster.','Moving all of an organisation\'s data into the public cloud.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q174','K',NULL,'5','Digital Transformation','[]'),(1619,7,'In Excel, INDEX/MATCH is often preferred over VLOOKUP because:','It is easier than VLOOKUP for beginners to learn and to use.','It is the only way to perform lookups in modern Excel today.','It can look up in any direction and resists column changes.','It is more accurate than VLOOKUP for numeric values overall.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q175','K',NULL,'5','Spreadsheet','[]'),(1620,7,'In project management, \'scope creep\' refers to:','Projects running over their originally scheduled completion time.','Gradual uncontrolled expansion of project scope beyond agreement.','Cost overruns that exceed the original budget allocated for work.','Team members taking on responsibilities outside their stated role.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q176','K',NULL,'5','Project Management','[]'),(1621,7,'A \'phishing\' email typically attempts to:','Steal the physical hardware from the recipient.','Crash the recipient\'s computer with a malicious payload.','Send the recipient unsolicited targeted advertising.','Manipulate the recipient into revealing credentials.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q177','K',NULL,'5','Email Security','[]'),(1622,7,'In effective remote/hybrid work, the MOST important practice is:','Default to asynchronous, written communication for decisions.','Work the same hours as the headquarters location every day.','Use as many collaboration tools as possible across the team.','Hold more frequent meetings to maintain alignment across the team.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q178','K',NULL,'5','Remote Work Tools','[]'),(1623,7,'An API (Application Programming Interface) in business context allows:','Users to log in to multiple applications with one password.','One system to request data or functions from another programmatically.','Customers to access the company\'s database directly without permission.','Companies to share their source code with their partner organisations.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q179','K',NULL,'5','API Concept','[]'),(1624,7,'When evaluating a software vendor\'s security, \'encryption at rest\' means:','Data is encrypted while stored in databases, files, and backups.','Data is encrypted only while being transmitted between systems.','Data is permanently encrypted and can never be accessed again.','Data is encrypted overnight and decrypted during work hours.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q180','K',NULL,'5','Encryption at Rest','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1625,7,'When evaluating a business analysis, the MOST important question to ask about the data is:','How was the data collected and is the sample representative?','Who collected the data and which department did they belong to?','How many data points were used in the underlying analysis?','What software was used to perform the analysis on the data?','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q181','K',NULL,'5','Analytics','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1626,7,'Your team is debating whether to adopt AI tools widely. Some are enthusiastic, others resistant. The MOST effective leadership approach is:','Wait for industry standards to emerge before the team makes any adoption decisions on AI.','Pilot with willing subset, measure impact, share openly, then data-informed wider decisions.','Mandate adoption — the efficiency gains demand it across the team as soon as possible.','Allow voluntary adoption — let each person choose whether to use AI in their workflows.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q182','SJT',NULL,'5','AI Adoption','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1627,7,'You realise a colleague has been emailing customer data to their personal email to work on it at home. The MOST appropriate response is:','Ignore the issue — they probably have a legitimate reason for working with the data at home.','Confront the colleague publicly to make sure others on the team learn from the situation.','Immediately raise with manager and security/compliance — this is a serious privacy violation.','Private chat with them and report through proper channels if the practice isn\'t resolved.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q183','SJT',NULL,'5','Data Confidentiality','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":2}}'),(1628,7,'You\'ve been using ChatGPT to help draft work products. Your company doesn\'t have a clear policy yet. The MOST appropriate approach is:','Stop using AI completely until the company has issued clear policies on what is allowed.','Continue using ChatGPT without disclosure since the company\'s policies aren\'t yet defined.','Be transparent: \"I\'ve been using AI for X. I verify outputs. Should I be more or less open?\"','Use AI heavily without disclosure to maximise the productivity advantage while you can.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q184','SJT',NULL,'5','Generative AI in Work Product','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1629,7,'You receive an email that appears to be from your CEO asking you to urgently process a wire transfer to a new vendor. The MOST appropriate action is:','Process the transfer right away — the email is from the CEO and the request is urgent.','Verify through a separate channel: call the CEO on a known number, not one from the email.','Forward the email to the finance team for them to process the transfer on your behalf.','Reply to the email asking the CEO for confirmation before processing the wire transfer.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q185','SJT',NULL,'5','Cybersecurity Suspicion','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1630,7,'You\'re presenting analytics findings to a non-technical executive who likes to drill into details. The MOST effective approach is:','Send the raw data file in advance and discuss the findings in person with the executive.','Keep the presentation high-level and dismiss requests for the granular detail they like.','Show all charts in detail upfront to satisfy their stated preference for the granular data.','Lead with insight and recommendation, simple visuals, drill-down ready when they ask for it.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q186','SJT',NULL,'5','Stakeholder Reporting','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1631,7,'Your team uses a legacy system that frustrates everyone but switching would require significant investment. The MOST effective approach is:','Wait for the system to fail before pushing for change — at that point everyone will agree.','Quantify: cost of frustration, cost of switching, risk; business case in business language.','Accept the situation since you don\'t own the decision about which systems get replaced.','Push for replacement immediately — the frustration is a real cost for the whole team daily.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q187','SJT',NULL,'5','Legacy Tech Decision','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1632,7,'You used an AI tool to research a market data point and it gave you a confident-sounding statistic. The MOST appropriate use of that statistic is:','Use the statistic with a footnote citing the AI tool that you used as the original source.','Use it without citation since the AI tool is not really a primary research source itself.','Use it directly in your presentation — the AI tool is reliable for typical market statistics.','Use as a starting point; verify from authoritative sources before any consequential use.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q188','SJT',NULL,'5','AI Hallucination','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1633,7,'A new productivity tool is being adopted across your industry. The MOST effective way to develop competence is:','Wait until you\'re forced to use it before investing time in learning the new tool well.','Watch demonstration videos online to get a feel for what the tool does before using it.','Identify a real problem; apply the tool to it; deepen through repeated application.','Take a structured course or read the full documentation first, then experiment with it.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q189','SJT',NULL,'5','Learning New Tools','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1634,7,'I use AI tools sophisticatedly — providing structured prompts, verifying outputs, and integrating them into my work judiciously.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q190','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','AI Sophistication','{\"likert\":true}'),(1635,7,'I am comfortable interpreting data and making decisions informed by it.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q191','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Data Comfort','{\"likert\":true}'),(1636,7,'I can translate technical concepts into business language and vice versa.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q192','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Tech Translation','{\"likert\":true}'),(1637,7,'I am confident in my ability to learn new digital tools as my role demands.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q193','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Learning New Tools','{\"likert\":true}'),(1638,7,'I follow strong digital security practices — 2FA, password manager, careful with links and attachments.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q194','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Cybersecurity Hygiene','{\"likert\":true}'),(1639,7,'I am effective in async/written work environments, not just synchronous meetings.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q195','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Async Comfort','{\"likert\":true}'),(1640,7,'I am genuinely curious about how technology is changing my industry, even when it\'s not directly required for my work.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q196','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Curiosity About Tech','{\"likert\":true}'),(1641,7,'When I see a data-driven claim, I instinctively ask how the data was collected and what its limitations are.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q197','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Critical Thinking About Data','{\"likert\":true}'),(1642,7,'I tend to avoid learning new digital tools unless I\'m forced to.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q198','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','5','Tech Avoidance','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1643,7,'How often do you read about technology developments affecting your industry?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q199','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','5','Tech Reading','{\"likert\":true}'),(1644,7,'How often do you invest time to deepen your skills with tools you already use, rather than just learning new ones?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:46','Q200','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','5','Tool Mastery','{\"likert\":true}'),(1645,8,'MEDDIC, a popular enterprise sales qualification framework, stands for:','Market, Evaluation, Demand, Demo, Implementation, Customer.','Method, Engagement, Decision, Discount, Investment, Close.','Metrics, Economic Buyer, Decision Criteria, Pain, Champion.','Money, Engagement, Direction, Detail, Influence, Commitment.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q001','K',NULL,'1','MEDDIC','[]'),(1646,8,'The \'Challenger Sale\' framework (Dixon & Adamson) identifies which sales profile as most consistently successful in complex B2B sales?','The Hard Worker — who exceeds activity targets consistently.','The Challenger — who teaches, tailors, and takes control.','The Lone Wolf — who works independently and instinctively.','The Relationship Builder — who prioritises rapport and ease.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q002','K',NULL,'1','Challenger Sale','[]'),(1647,8,'In enterprise B2B sales, when procurement enters the process, the primary shift is typically:','From technical evaluation to functional evaluation of fit.','From procurement review to legal contract review.','From value and relationship to commercial terms and risk.','From short-term focus to long-term value considerations.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q003','K',NULL,'1','Procurement Dynamics','[]'),(1648,8,'The typical complex enterprise B2B sales cycle in software/services is generally:','6–18 months from first contact to signed contract.','24+ months always, regardless of deal complexity.','1–3 months from first contact to a signed deal.','Identical to a typical B2C purchase cycle length.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q004','K',NULL,'1','Enterprise Sales Cycle','[]'),(1649,8,'A common failure mode of \'solution selling\' is:','Over-emphasising technical detail in customer-facing meetings.','Spending too little time on initial customer discovery sessions.','Presenting a solution before the customer\'s criteria are clear.','Including too many product features in the presentation deck.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q005','K',NULL,'1','Solution Selling Pitfall','[]'),(1650,8,'In strategic account planning, a \'red account\' typically refers to:','A small account being deprioritised by the sales team.','An account with overdue invoices and ongoing payment issues.','An at-risk account showing churn signals or disengagement.','An account currently in the active pre-sale evaluation stage.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q006','K',NULL,'1','Account Planning','[]'),(1651,8,'In B2B channel strategy, the distinction between a \'reseller\' and a \'systems integrator\' is:','Reseller and systems integrator are essentially the same role.','Resellers serve large customers; integrators serve smaller ones.','Resellers are exclusive partners; integrators are non-exclusive.','Reseller distributes; integrator builds custom solutions.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q007','K',NULL,'1','Channel Strategy','[]'),(1652,8,'TCO (Total Cost of Ownership) in a B2B sale is most useful for:','Showing the full economic picture across the lifecycle.','Calculating the upfront purchase price for the buyer.','Internal cost allocation across the buyer\'s departments.','Tax planning purposes during the procurement process.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q008','K',NULL,'1','TCO','[]'),(1653,8,'\'Land and expand\' as a B2B GTM strategy means:','Discounting heavily to win new business at any cost given.','Securing a small footprint, then growing it systematically.','Entering a market and acquiring smaller competitors there.','Targeting customers in multiple regions simultaneously.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q009','K',NULL,'1','Land and Expand','[]'),(1654,8,'A Mutual Action Plan (MAP), increasingly used in modern B2B sales, is:','A formal legal contract executed early in the sales deal.','An internal sales plan kept confidential from the customer.','A shared plan listing buyer and seller steps to a decision.','A joint marketing plan agreed between vendor and customer.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q010','K',NULL,'1','Mutual Action Plan','[]'),(1655,8,'Account-Based Marketing (ABM) is distinguished from traditional demand-generation marketing by:','Sending higher volumes of marketing emails to prospects.','Focusing only on existing customers for expansion sales plays.','Treating high-value accounts as their own target markets.','Using fewer touchpoints with each targeted prospect account.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q011','K',NULL,'1','B2B Marketing','[]'),(1656,8,'If your company has a 30% gross margin on a product, a 10% price discount requires what approximate volume increase to maintain gross profit?','100% volume increase.','10% volume increase.','33% volume increase.','50% volume increase.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q012','K',NULL,'1','Discount Math at Scale','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1657,8,'The Sandler Selling System\'s concept of \'finding the pain\' refers to:','Identifying weak competitors to attack in the account.','Uncovering the problem the customer is willing to act on.','Identifying physical injuries in industrial-equipment sales.','Negotiating down until you find the price they will pay.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q013','K',NULL,'1','Sandler','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1658,8,'Late in a major deal, procurement enters and demands a 30% discount with little justification. The MOST effective response is:','Engage procurement: understand drivers, reaffirm value with the buyer, negotiate structure.','Refuse the discount and escalate to the executive sponsor at the customer\'s company.','Concede the full discount to close the deal and move it across the line quickly now.','Offer a smaller discount in response and hope they accept it as a reasonable compromise.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q014','SJT',NULL,'1','Procurement Engagement','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1659,8,'Your internal champion at a key account has just resigned. Their replacement is unknown. The MOST effective immediate action is:','Offer the new buyer a discount to retain your influence with them in the early days.','Wait for the new champion to engage with you when they are ready in the new role.','Escalate to senior leadership at the account to drive top-down engagement immediately.','Reach out warmly to former champion, then to replacement: focus intros on continuity.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q015','SJT',NULL,'1','Champion Loss','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1660,8,'A large deal has been \'closing next month\' for 4 consecutive months. The MOST appropriate response is:','Continue tracking and forecasting the deal as before until something changes on it.','Increase the pressure on the buyer with deadline-based discounting in the next outreach.','Stop forecasting it; have a direct chat: \"I sense timing isn\'t right. Help me understand.\"','Escalate the issue to the buyer\'s manager to put pressure on the decision process.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q016','SJT',NULL,'1','Stalled Deal','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1661,8,'In a complex B2B deal, the technical buyer loves your solution; the economic buyer is sceptical of the ROI; procurement wants a 25% discount. The MOST effective approach is:','Increase the technical demonstration significantly to overwhelm objections from all sides.','Send a comprehensive written response addressing all three sets of concerns at one time.','Address each separately: deepen ROI case, find commercial structure not discount, orchestrate.','Concede to procurement; leverage the technical buyer\'s voice to override the economic buyer.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q017','SJT',NULL,'1','Multi-stakeholder Conflict','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1662,8,'A potential customer is asking for terms that would make the deal unprofitable. The MOST mature response is:','Be honest: \"At these terms it doesn\'t work for us. Let\'s find structure that works for both.\"','Lower internal commitments on the deal to make it appear profitable on paper to leadership.','Close the deal to hit quota and try to recover the margin later in the relationship.','Defer the decision entirely to your manager so they can call it from their position.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q018','SJT',NULL,'1','Walking Away','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1663,8,'A prospective customer asks for a reference. Your most successful customer is in a competing industry to the prospect, but operates similarly. The MOST appropriate approach is:','Ask the customer privately, get explicit consent, then facilitate intro with a clear brief.','Offer a generic case study instead of a live reference call with a real customer person.','Refuse the reference request entirely to protect the existing customer\'s confidentiality.','Share the customer\'s name and let the prospect contact them directly to speak openly.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q019','SJT',NULL,'1','Reference Customer','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1664,8,'You just lost a major deal you expected to win. Your manager wants a quick post-mortem. The MOST useful debrief is:','Attribute the loss to the competitor\'s lower pricing and move on to the next opportunity.','Focus the debrief on what the team did right and move on quickly to the next deal in play.','Blame internal product or engineering for not having the feature the customer wanted today.','Honest debrief with prospect if possible; internal review of discovery, stakeholders, process.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q020','SJT',NULL,'1','Lost Deal Recovery','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1665,8,'A major customer\'s renewal is in 90 days. Usage data shows declining adoption and you\'ve heard a competitor is being evaluated. The MOST effective response is:','Schedule business review now: revisit goals, surface adoption and competition openly, joint plan.','Wait until the renewal discussion in 90 days to address adoption and competitive concerns.','Pre-emptively offer a renewal discount to retain the account before competitive evaluation.','Escalate to senior leadership to engage their senior leadership and push the renewal forward.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q021','SJT',NULL,'1','Renewal at Risk','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1666,8,'A major prospect asks for significant customisation of your standard offering. The MOST commercially mature response is:','Understand the underlying need; assess fit, precedent, strategic value; negotiate scope, cost.','Defer the customisation discussion entirely until after the contract has been formally signed.','Refuse the customisation entirely to protect the integrity of your product roadmap going forward.','Agree to the customisation to win the deal — engineering will figure out the delivery later.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q022','SJT',NULL,'1','Custom vs Standard','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1667,8,'Your pricing model is being adjusted; customers in evaluation are unhappy with the change. The MOST effective response is:','Honour the old pricing for any deals currently in progress to preserve the relationships.','Hold firm on the new pricing across all customers and lose the deals if that is necessary.','Explain rationale, offer accommodations, be transparent on negotiables; move quickly on it.','Apologise to all affected customers and reverse the pricing change to restore the goodwill.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q023','SJT',NULL,'1','Pricing Architecture','{\"weights\":{\"a\":2,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1668,8,'Your strongest internal champion is enthusiastic but lacks influence at the senior decision level. The MOST effective approach is:','Continue relying on the existing champion and hope they grow in influence over time naturally.','Find a more senior champion and shift your relationship investment to that new contact.','Bypass the champion entirely and engage the senior decision-makers directly at the account.','Equip the champion: exec materials, prep for senior conversations, broaden coalition together.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q024','SJT',NULL,'1','Internal Champion Without Power','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1669,8,'You take over a major strategic account. The MOST effective first 30 days are:','Begin aggressive outreach to all stakeholders to maximise your visibility in the new account.','Wait for the customer to invite engagement when they are ready to meet you in your new role.','Send a polished introduction email to all stakeholders in the account in your first week.','Read history, talk to colleagues, meet predecessor, listen to customer, build 12-month plan.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q025','SJT',NULL,'1','Strategic Account Plan','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1670,8,'Your quarterly forecast call is in two days. A major deal is genuinely uncertain (30-50% probability in your honest assessment). Manager wants high commitment. MOST mature response:','Forecast honestly: \"I\'m at 35% — here\'s why, here\'s what would move it, what I\'m doing.\"','Forecast it as committed to please your manager and avoid difficult conversations with them.','Remove it entirely from the forecast since the probability is too uncertain to include now.','Forecast it as committed but pull back from that position if pressed later in the call.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q026','SJT',NULL,'1','Forecast Honesty','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1671,8,'A customer is happy with your core product. Your company has just released an adjacent offering. The MOST effective approach to cross-selling is:','Offer a discount on the new product specifically to encourage the customer to trial it soon.','Schedule a dedicated demo of the new product with the customer in the coming weeks ahead.','Next routine review: listen for natural relevance, introduce only if it solves a real pain.','Email the customer about the new product launch and what it could potentially do for them.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q027','SJT',NULL,'1','Cross-Sell Discipline','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1672,8,'A major customer escalates an issue directly to your CEO. The MOST appropriate response from you (the account owner) is:','Brief the CEO factually; engage customer directly: \"I want to address this personally.\"','Step back from the situation and let senior leadership handle the customer escalation directly.','Wait for the CEO to brief you on what they want you to do about the customer escalation.','Defend yourself to the CEO before they have a chance to speak directly with the customer.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q028','SJT',NULL,'1','Customer Escalation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1673,8,'Your company\'s product team has announced a roadmap change that breaks commitments you\'ve made to customers. The MOST effective response is:','Wait for the situation to be resolved by senior leadership on their own without your input.','Tell the customers nothing has changed and hope the gap doesn\'t get noticed by them later.','Engage product leadership: surface commitments at risk, propose adjustment or mitigation.','Resign from the role in protest of the broken commitments to the customers you have made.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q029','SJT',NULL,'1','Internal Misalignment','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1674,8,'A procurement leader is being unreasonable, blocking a deal the business buyers want. The MOST effective response is:','Encourage the business buyers to escalate to override procurement from above the deal.','Respectful chat with procurement: understand drivers, find structure that gives them a win.','Refuse to engage further with procurement and work only with the business buyers directly.','Escalate the issue to procurement\'s leadership to override the blocking from above.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q030','SJT',NULL,'1','Difficult Procurement','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1675,8,'Two weeks before close, the customer surfaces a major new requirement you weren\'t aware of. The MOST appropriate response is:','Push back firmly that the requirements were already locked at an earlier stage in the deal.','Understand the driver; assess honestly with engineering; respond on what\'s possible and when.','Agree to the new requirement immediately to keep the deal moving forward without delay.','Delay your response until you find a creative workaround by yourself first this week.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q031','SJT',NULL,'1','Late-Stage Surprise','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1676,8,'A potential strategic partner approaches you about co-selling. The MOST mature evaluation approach is:','Decline the partnership offer entirely since strategic partnerships are complex to manage.','Engage seriously: motivation, overlap, value, model, conflict risk; pilot before formalising.','Defer the decision entirely to senior leadership without giving any of your input first.','Agree to the partnership quickly to avoid losing the opportunity to a competitor of yours.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q032','SJT',NULL,'1','Strategic Partnership','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1677,8,'During a customer conversation, the buyer mentions \'we have a budget cycle ending in March\' (one month away). The MOST effective response is:','Mention urgency around the budget timing in every subsequent communication with the buyer.','Ignore the timing comment entirely and focus on building the value case for the buyer alone.','Acknowledge thoughtfully: \"Let\'s work backward together so we have time to do this well.\"','Offer a discount tied specifically to closing the deal before the budget cycle ends in March.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q033','SJT',NULL,'1','Reading Buying Signals','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1678,8,'A customer insists on a contract clause that would expose your company to unacceptable liability. The MOST appropriate response is:','Accept the clause and plan to address the underlying risk later as the relationship grows.','Engage legal; talk directly: what you can\'t agree and why, propose specific alternatives.','Sign with internal verbal reassurance that the problematic clause won\'t actually be invoked.','Push the customer firmly to drop the clause without offering an alternative for the concern.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q034','SJT',NULL,'1','Saying No to a Deal Term','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1679,8,'Your active champion at a B2B deal has gone silent for 3 weeks despite previously being highly engaged. The MOST effective response is:','Approach a different stakeholder at the account to bypass the silent champion entirely.','Send progressively more pressing follow-up messages to get them to respond to your outreach.','One direct outreach: \"I\'ve noticed you\'ve been quiet — has the priority shifted? Honest update?\"','Stop pursuing the deal entirely and move on to other opportunities in your pipeline now.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q035','SJT',NULL,'1','Champion Going Cold','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1680,8,'I am comfortable navigating complex, multi-stakeholder B2B sales cycles.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q036','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Enterprise Sales Confidence','{\"likert\":true}'),(1681,8,'I can uncover the real underlying business problem behind what a customer initially asks for.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q037','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Discovery at Depth','{\"likert\":true}'),(1682,8,'I instinctively map out the full set of stakeholders in any complex deal and tailor engagement to each.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q038','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Stakeholder Mapping','{\"likert\":true}'),(1683,8,'I can run the commercial math in real-time during a customer conversation (margin impact, TCO, ROI estimates).','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q039','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Commercial Math','{\"likert\":true}'),(1684,8,'I am willing to walk away from deals that don\'t make commercial or strategic sense.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q040','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Walking Away','{\"likert\":true}'),(1685,8,'I can engage procurement professionals professionally and creatively, not adversarially.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q041','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Procurement Engagement','{\"likert\":true}'),(1686,8,'I can work strategic accounts patiently, investing relationship and insight over multi-year cycles.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q042','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Strategic Patience','{\"likert\":true}'),(1687,8,'I forecast honestly based on signals, even when honest forecasts disappoint leadership.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q043','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Forecasting Honesty','{\"likert\":true}'),(1688,8,'I can identify and equip internal champions effectively, not just rely on them.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q044','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Champion Building','{\"likert\":true}'),(1689,8,'I can mobilise internal teams (product, finance, legal, services) to deliver for customers.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q045','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Cross-Functional Influence','{\"likert\":true}'),(1690,8,'I have deep, specific industry knowledge that customers find valuable in itself.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q046','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Industry Expertise','{\"likert\":true}'),(1691,8,'After major deal losses, I extract learning and move forward without lingering damage.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q047','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Resilience to Loss','{\"likert\":true}'),(1692,8,'When deals stall, my first instinct is to discount.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q048','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','1','Discount Reflex','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1693,8,'I sometimes find myself proposing solutions before I\'m sure I fully understand the customer\'s situation.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q049','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','1','Late-Discovery','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1694,8,'How often do you actively engage with your industry (events, publications, peer conversations, thought leadership)? PILLAR 02  ·  LEADERSHIP IN MATRIX ORGANISATIONS Cross-functional influence, OKRs, RACI clarity, talent management, change leadership, and the navigation skills required to lead effectively when authority is shared across reporting lines. Items in this pillar: 50','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q050','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','1','Industry Engagement','{\"likert\":true}'),(1695,8,'A \'matrix organisation\' structures reporting such that:','Each business unit operates entirely independently from others.','All employees report to a single hierarchical manager.','Decision rights are delegated to junior employees across teams.','Employees report to multiple managers across functions.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q051','K',NULL,'2','Matrix Organisation','[]'),(1696,8,'The RACI framework for clarifying roles on cross-functional work stands for:','Review, Approve, Coordinate, Implement project.','Recognise, Adapt, Communicate, Initiate change.','Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, Informed.','Recommend, Authorise, Coach, Influence team.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q052','K',NULL,'2','RACI','[]'),(1697,8,'OKRs (Objectives and Key Results), as popularised by John Doerr and used at Google and Intel, are structured such that:','Objectives are individual goals; Key Results are team-level targets.','Objectives are qualitative ambitions; Key Results are measurable outcomes.','Objectives are quantitative targets; Key Results are qualitative narratives.','Objectives are mandatory commitments; Key Results are aspirational only.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q053','K',NULL,'2','OKRs','[]'),(1698,8,'Allan Cohen and David Bradford\'s framework for \'influence without authority\' (which dominates modern matrix leadership) is built on:','Hierarchical override — invoking senior authority when needed.','Charm and likeability — building affinity to gain compliance.','Pressure and persistence — pushing until the other side yields.','Reciprocity — exchanging what each party values for benefit.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q054','K',NULL,'2','Influence Without Authority','[]'),(1699,8,'Research on strategy execution (e.g., Mankins, Steele) consistently shows that the largest failure point in strategy is:','Insufficient capital allocation to support the chosen strategy.','Inadequate communication of the strategy to all employees.','Translating strategy into actions and accountabilities.','Lack of analytical rigour in the strategy formulation phase.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q055','K',NULL,'2','Strategy Execution','[]'),(1700,8,'Patrick Lencioni\'s pyramid of team dysfunction, from base upward, is:','Results, accountability, commitment, conflict, trust.','Conflict, distrust, silos, politics, project failure.','Skill, strategy, communication, morale, broken culture.','Trust, conflict, commitment, accountability, results.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q056','K',NULL,'2','Five Dysfunctions','[]'),(1701,8,'Research on resistance to change (Kotter, Heath brothers) consistently identifies the most underrated cause of resistance as:','Genuine concerns and self-interests of those resisting change.','Lack of information about what the change will actually involve.','Lack of clear incentives tied to the change initiative itself.','Inadequate leadership presence in driving the change effort.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q057','K',NULL,'2','Change Resistance','[]'),(1702,8,'In well-designed decision processes, a useful distinction is between:','Strategic decisions versus purely tactical decisions only.','Recommender, decider, and the agreers/consulted/informed.','Group consensus versus single individual decision-making.','Decisions and recommendations, made by the same people.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q058','K',NULL,'2','Decision Rights','[]'),(1703,8,'Stephen M.R. Covey\'s \'Speed of Trust\' framework identifies the two foundational dimensions of trustworthiness as:','Strategy and execution.','Character and Competence.','Honesty and competence.','Authority and likability.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q059','K',NULL,'2','Building Trust','[]'),(1704,8,'Modern performance management research (Buckingham, Goodall, others) increasingly emphasises which shift?','Frequent, forward-looking, strengths-based conversations.','Anonymous peer feedback as the primary performance signal.','More frequent comparison of employees against each other.','Standardised numerical ratings to ensure fairness across teams.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q060','K',NULL,'2','Performance Management','[]'),(1705,8,'Roger Martin\'s concept of \'where to play and how to win\' in strategy emphasises that:','Companies should try to compete in every available market.','Strategy is about being slightly better at everything done.','Strategy is a set of integrated choices about where and how.','Strategy is fundamentally about cost reduction across functions.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q061','K',NULL,'2','Strategic Patience','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1706,8,'The \'coaching\' versus \'mentoring\' versus \'managing\' distinction (Whitmore, Goldsmith) is best framed as:','Managing tells; mentoring shares wisdom; coaching asks questions.','Coaching is for executives; mentoring is for new joining employees.','Managing is formal; mentoring and coaching are both informal kinds.','Coaching, mentoring, and managing all describe the same activity.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q062','K',NULL,'2','Coaching','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1707,8,'You\'re leading a cross-functional team of 10 people who don\'t report to you. Two members from finance are not delivering. The MOST effective response is:','Private chat with each: observations, listen to blockers, agree changes; escalate if needed.','Bring it up publicly in the next team meeting so all members understand the expectation.','Escalate the issue to the finance lead to enforce delivery from the two members directly.','Reassign their work to other team members on the project to keep it moving forward on time.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q063','SJT',NULL,'2','Cross-Functional Team Lead','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1708,8,'Engineering and product disagree fundamentally on roadmap priorities. As a senior manager involved, the MOST effective intervention is:','Bring leaders together; surface trade-offs explicitly; force resolution to a specific decision.','Escalate the disagreement to senior leadership to resolve before further roadmap work happens.','Let the two leaders work it out between themselves without further intervention from you.','Side with whichever of the two functions has priorities that seem more strategic right now.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q064','SJT',NULL,'2','Conflict Between Functions','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1709,8,'An initiative you championed has failed publicly, costing the company materially. Your CEO calls you in. The MOST mature response is:','Offer to resign from the role since the failure was significant and publicly visible to all.','Identify factors that contributed to the failure that were beyond your control as the leader.','Own directly: \"I made the call. Here\'s what I missed; here\'s what I\'d do; here\'s what now.\"','Present a detailed analysis of why the strategy was actually sound at the time you chose it.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q065','SJT',NULL,'2','Owning Strategic Failure','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1710,8,'A long-tenured, well-liked employee is no longer performing at the level the company needs. They are not aware. The MOST appropriate first conversation is:','Begin a formal performance improvement plan to set very clear expectations from the outset.','Wait for the next formal performance review cycle to deliver the difficult message to them.','Reduce their responsibilities quietly over the next quarter to manage their performance gap.','Candid respectful 1:1: anchor in respect; share gap with evidence; co-explore the unlocker.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q066','SJT',NULL,'2','Talent Difficult Conversation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1711,8,'Your direct manager and your skip-level have given you conflicting strategic direction. The MOST mature response is:','Follow your direct manager and bring up the conflict at your next formal performance review.','Follow the skip-level\'s direction since they are more senior in the organisation than the manager.','Average the two pieces of direction and hope that the resulting plan works for both of them.','Make the conflict visible: \"I want to make sure I\'m pulling in the right direction. Align?\"','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q067','SJT',NULL,'2','Boss Misalignment','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1712,8,'You have insufficient resources for everything on your team\'s plate. The MOST effective response is:','Make trade-off explicit: \"We can do 5 of 8 well. Here\'s my recommendation. Your view?\"','Hire additional people quickly without asking permission to expand the team\'s overall capacity.','Push the team harder to deliver everything on the plate within the existing resource envelope.','Quietly deprioritise some of the work without making any explicit decisions about what gets cut.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q068','SJT',NULL,'2','Resource Trade-Off','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1713,8,'You\'ve just been appointed to lead a team that is performing well but has high attrition risk. Your boss expects you to retain key talent. The MOST effective first 60 days are:','Maintain the status quo across the team to avoid creating disruption that increases attrition.','Announce a strategic vision quickly to inspire commitment from team members at risk of leaving.','1:1s with each: aspirations, what would keep them; targeted retention conversations with at-risk.','Quickly identify and incentivise the highest-flight risks on the team to reduce attrition fast.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q069','SJT',NULL,'2','New Leader Inherits Team','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1714,8,'Your boss is high-performing but communicates in scattered, last-minute, often-changing requests. The MOST mature response is:','Adapt and absorb the chaos that the boss creates as part of working with their style daily.','Push back firmly when requests come in chaotically to teach the boss a more structured pattern.','Manage up: propose weekly 1:1, weekly written update, push for clarity, create needed structure.','Look for a different role with a different boss who has a more structured communication style.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q070','SJT',NULL,'2','Managing Up','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1715,8,'A high-performing team member tells you confidentially they are considering an external offer. The MOST effective response is:','Reach out to the offering company to find out what their offer for the team member is.','Match the external offer immediately to retain the high-performer before they leave the team.','Listen first: \"What\'s drawing you there; what\'s keeping you?\" Then address what\'s missing.','Wish them well — people should follow their own growth journey wherever that leads them next.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q071','SJT',NULL,'2','High Performer Considering Leaving','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1716,8,'You sense your team is drifting from the strategy — busy and effective on tactical work but losing alignment with the bigger goals. The MOST effective response is:','Step back: what is the strategy in one sentence? Reconnect current work or refresh strategy.','Tighten operational metrics to drive performance back to the original strategic direction.','Replace the team members who seem least strategic in their focus and approach to work today.','Run a strategy refresh exercise to re-energise the team around an updated set of priorities.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q072','SJT',NULL,'2','Strategic Drift','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1717,8,'The CEO asks you to take on a project that would seriously over-extend you and your team. The MOST mature response is:','Engage: \"Let me share where we are; here are options; how would you want me to think about it?\"','Accept the request enthusiastically — opportunities from the CEO don\'t come along often.','Accept and absorb the additional work silently to demonstrate strong commitment to the CEO.','Refuse the request outright to protect your team\'s existing priorities and the work quality.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q073','SJT',NULL,'2','Saying No to CEO','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1718,8,'Two team members in similar roles have a 25% pay gap that you cannot justify on performance. The MOST appropriate action is:','Wait for the next compensation review cycle to address the gap incrementally over time.','Maintain the gap for now — pay history at the company is complicated to address properly.','Present data to HR, advocate for correction, communicate transparently to underpaid employee.','Tell the underpaid employee directly to negotiate harder with HR to close their own pay gap.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q074','SJT',NULL,'2','Equity Adjustment','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1719,8,'You face a decision where the right call professionally will damage your relationship with a powerful senior peer. The MOST mature response is:','Make the politically safe call to preserve the working relationship with the senior peer involved.','Make the right call and accept the relationship damage as a cost of doing the job properly.','Direct chat with the peer before the public call: share reasoning, acknowledge impact, decide.','Make the right call but signal to others that you wish you didn\'t have to make that call.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q075','SJT',NULL,'2','Politically Volatile Decision','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":2,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1720,8,'You want to drive a significant operational change that requires buy-in from peers across functions. Your authority alone won\'t get it done. The MOST effective approach is:','Move quickly to demonstrate momentum before opposition has time to mobilise against the change.','Build a comprehensive plan and present it to all the peers for approval before moving forward.','Get senior sponsorship and rely on the sponsor\'s authority to drive the change across the org.','Map stakeholders carefully; meet each privately; build coalition before going public; act with.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q076','SJT',NULL,'2','Building Coalition for Change','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1721,8,'You discover that a senior peer is taking credit for work done by junior team members on a cross-functional project. The MOST appropriate response is:','Make sure the affected junior employees know that you saw what happened on the project.','Stay out of it entirely — the issue is not about your team and not really your problem to fix.','Report the behaviour anonymously to HR or senior leadership to address through proper channels.','Direct private: \"I\'ve observed X. It\'s hurting [people]. Wanted to raise it before anything else.\"','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q077','SJT',NULL,'2','Ethics in Leadership','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1722,8,'You\'ve been told to reduce your team by 25%. The MOST humane and professional execution involves:','Delegate the difficult conversations to HR to handle on behalf of the team for consistency.','Apply pure last-in-first-out criteria for simplicity when making the team reduction decisions.','Announce reductions broadly first across the team, then handle individual conversations later.','Capability needs plus performance; personal delivery with notice; support; honest communication.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q078','SJT',NULL,'2','Layoffs','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1723,8,'You lead a global team across 5 countries. Meetings are dominated by 2 native-English-speaking regions; others stay quiet. The MOST inclusive approach is:','Continue with meetings as they are now — the quieter team members will speak when they\'re ready.','Address it openly in meetings with a quick \"Let\'s hear from everyone in the discussion now.\"','Redesign meetings: pre-agendas, round-robin, async channels, pre-meet 1:1s, adjust pace.','Split the global team into separate regional teams to remove the cross-cultural friction.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q079','SJT',NULL,'2','Cross-Cultural Team Leadership','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1724,8,'Your team has been running flat-out for 4 months. Key signals of burnout are appearing. Targets remain pressing. The MOST effective response is:','Push the team harder — targets must be met regardless of how exhausted everyone feels now.','Renegotiate scope: cut or simplify, honest with leadership, visible recovery time built in.','Bring in temporary contractors to relieve the load on the existing team in the short term.','Offer the team flexible Friday afternoons each week to give them a small recovery window.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q080','SJT',NULL,'2','Recognising Team Burnout','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1725,8,'You want to introduce a new approach in a function known for resistance to change. The MOST effective tactic is:','Announce the new approach with executive sponsorship to force adoption across the team quickly.','Wait for organic readiness to change to develop in the function naturally over the years ahead.','Run a small time-bounded experiment with willing volunteers; let outcomes build the wider case.','Build a comprehensive plan and present it to leadership for approval before any rollout begins.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q081','SJT',NULL,'2','Innovation in Conservative Org','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1726,8,'A strategic vendor has been underperforming. Switching has significant costs. The MOST mature response is:','Reduce your business with the vendor gradually over time without explicitly raising the issue.','Direct chat with vendor leadership: issues, impact, improvements with timeline; build alt path.','Tolerate the underperformance to avoid the significant costs of switching to a new vendor now.','Begin switching immediately to send a strong message to the vendor about consequences for them.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q082','SJT',NULL,'2','Vendor Management','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1727,8,'You believe a senior peer\'s strategy is wrong. They are not your boss; you have no authority to override. The MOST effective approach is:','Private chat with the peer: \"I see X. Might be wrong, but curious about your view on this.\"','Raise the concern with your own boss and let them handle the conversation with the peer.','Stay out of it entirely — the strategy is not in your area of direct responsibility now.','Publicly question the strategy in meetings to surface the issue with leadership in attendance.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q083','SJT',NULL,'2','Influence Over Senior Peer','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1728,8,'In calibration, your senior team rates one of your high-performing reports lower than you would. The MOST effective response is:','Present evidence; listen for learning; advocate firmly; lose with grace; tell employee honestly.','Promise the employee a higher rating in the next cycle to compensate for the calibration outcome.','Accept the calibration decision quietly without further pushing back in the calibration meeting.','Argue strongly for your rating to ensure that the high-performer gets the recognition deserved.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q084','SJT',NULL,'2','Performance Review Outlier','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1729,8,'I can think strategically about my function and connect it to enterprise priorities.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q085','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Strategic Thinking','{\"likert\":true}'),(1730,8,'I navigate matrix organisations effectively, building influence across multiple reporting lines.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q086','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Matrix Navigation','{\"likert\":true}'),(1731,8,'I initiate difficult conversations with peers, reports, and even bosses when the situation requires it.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q087','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Difficult Conversations','{\"likert\":true}'),(1732,8,'I delegate work effectively, trusting others to deliver in their own way.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q088','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Delegation','{\"likert\":true}'),(1733,8,'I stay composed under significant stress, even when others around me are not.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q089','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Composure','{\"likert\":true}'),(1734,8,'I invest in developing my reports beyond their immediate role.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q090','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Developing Others','{\"likert\":true}'),(1735,8,'I can hold strategic patience even when short-term pressures are intense.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q091','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Strategic Patience','{\"likert\":true}'),(1736,8,'I take public ownership of failures in my domain, even when others contributed to them.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q092','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Owning Outcomes','{\"likert\":true}'),(1737,8,'I can influence colleagues across functions without relying on hierarchical authority.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q093','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Cross-Functional Influence','{\"likert\":true}'),(1738,8,'I make high-quality decisions under uncertainty and incomplete information.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q094','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Decision Quality','{\"likert\":true}'),(1739,8,'I sometimes avoid difficult conversations with peers I respect, to preserve the relationship.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q095','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','2','Conflict Avoidance','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1740,8,'I make decisions partly based on how they\'ll be perceived by leadership, even when that conflicts with my best judgment.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q096','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','2','Approval-Seeking','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1741,8,'When I delegate work, I tend to check in more often than necessary.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q097','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','2','Micromanagement','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1742,8,'How often do you set aside time to think strategically about your function and the enterprise — not just execute?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q098','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','2','Strategic Reflection','{\"likert\":true}'),(1743,8,'How often do you have substantive coaching/development conversations with your reports (separate from operational reviews)?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q099','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','2','Coaching Time','{\"likert\":true}'),(1744,8,'How often do you proactively build relationships with peers across functions and external counterparts? PILLAR 03  ·  EXECUTIVE COMMUNICATION & INFLUENCE Board-level briefing, executive presence, crisis communication, structured writing, public disagreement with senior peers, and the communication maturity expected at senior corporate levels. Items in this pillar: 40','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q100','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','2','Network-Building','{\"likert\":true}'),(1745,8,'In board-level communication, the most effective opening of a written briefing is generally:','Background context that sets up the broader briefing topic.','The detailed analysis that supports the recommendation here.','The recommendation or decision in one or two sentences.','The methodology used in producing the written briefing.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q101','K',NULL,'3','Board Communication','[]'),(1746,8,'In change communication research (Heath brothers, others), the most underrated communication failure is:','Communicating before relevant decisions have been made.','Communicating in language the audience does not understand.','Communicating too little overall through internal channels.','Not communicating consistently enough across many channels.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q102','K',NULL,'3','Stakeholder Communication','[]'),(1747,8,'Robert Cialdini\'s research on influence has been extended in business contexts to emphasise which principle as particularly important in scaling change?','Social proof — visible adoption by respected peers.','Authority — top-down mandate from the leadership team.','Scarcity — limited-time offers and exclusive access.','Reciprocity — exchange of favours between people.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q103','K',NULL,'3','Influence','[]'),(1748,8,'Research on crisis communication consistently identifies which factor as most important?','Detailed root-cause analysis before any communication.','Speed, transparency, accountability, and updates combined.','Speed of response above all other communication factors.','Avoiding statements until the full facts are established.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q104','K',NULL,'3','Crisis Communication','[]'),(1749,8,'In influencing senior executives, the most effective approach to disagreement is generally:','Frame your view as additional information or a question.','Deliver written analyses for the executive to read privately.','Directly contradict the executive to show conviction.','Build extensive coalitions before raising any concerns.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q105','K',NULL,'3','Influence Up','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1750,8,'Amazon\'s famous \'memo culture\' (no PowerPoint at executive meetings, written 6-page narrative memos read in silence at meeting start) emphasises:','Writing memos is much easier than preparing slide presentations.','Structured writing forces clearer thinking and exposes weak logic.','Written documents are inherently more elegant than spoken ones.','Senior executives generally prefer reading over open discussion.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q106','K',NULL,'3','Writing Discipline','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1751,8,'You have 15 minutes to present to the board on a critical strategic initiative. The MOST effective structure is:','Walk through the analysis methodology in detail to demonstrate rigour to the board members.','Present all options to the board and let the board choose which option is right to pursue.','First 90 sec: recommendation, decision, biggest risk; then detail; then asks and next steps.','Lead with the team\'s recent accomplishments to establish credibility before the recommendation.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q107','SJT',NULL,'3','Board Presentation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1752,8,'You need to email a senior executive sharing a significant problem in a project they care about. The MOST effective email is:','Soften the bad news with positive context first to make it easier for the executive to read.','Send a comprehensive narrative with the full context up front before the recommendation.','Request a meeting to discuss the issue verbally first rather than sharing it over email.','Lead with headline; cause factually; what\'s being done; implication; what\'s needed; brief.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q108','SJT',NULL,'3','Difficult Email to Senior','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1753,8,'In a senior meeting, a peer publicly mischaracterises your team\'s position. The MOST effective response is:','Calmly add factual clarity: \"I want to add some context — [specific factual point here].\"','Send a written correction to all the attendees of the meeting once the meeting is over.','Stay silent during the meeting and address the issue with them privately afterwards instead.','Correct them firmly in the moment to defend your team\'s position in front of the leadership.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q109','SJT',NULL,'3','Public Disagreement','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1754,8,'You need to announce a major strategic shift to your 200-person organisation. The MOST effective communication design is:','Hold an all-hands meeting immediately to inform everyone at the same time with no preparation.','Send a comprehensive written announcement to everyone in the organisation simultaneously now.','Cascade: brief leaders first, all-hands in 48hr direct, written follow-up, repeat over weeks.','Communicate to senior layers first and let it cascade naturally down through the organisation.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q110','SJT',NULL,'3','Communicating Strategic Change','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1755,8,'A senior executive (not your direct chain) asks you to take on work that conflicts with your priorities. The MOST mature response is:','Take on the work quietly and absorb the additional work without raising it with anyone else.','Engage warmly: \"Let me check with my manager since this affects priorities. Back in 24 hours.\"','Refuse the request on principle since the senior executive is not in your direct chain.','Comply with the request and absorb the new work into the existing workload immediately.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q111','SJT',NULL,'3','Saying No to Senior','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1756,8,'In a senior meeting, you have information that contradicts a senior leader\'s stated direction. The MOST mature response is:','Stay silent in the meeting — the senior leader may not appreciate a public contradiction.','Add as data: \"I have data pointing in a different direction. Worth factoring into the call?\"','Contradict them directly with evidence to ensure the right information is on the table now.','Send the contradicting information privately to the senior leader after the meeting ends.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q112','SJT',NULL,'3','Speaking Up in Senior Meeting','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":2}}'),(1757,8,'A significant external crisis has just hit your company (regulatory, security breach, etc.). The MOST effective leadership communication response is:','Provide reassuring statements to all stakeholders until you have a clear path forward to share.','Acknowledge promptly: known, unknown, what\'s being done, accountable, next update; follow through.','Wait until the full facts of the situation are established before communicating with stakeholders.','Direct all communications through the PR/legal teams only to manage the message carefully.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q113','SJT',NULL,'3','Crisis Communication','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1758,8,'You are presenting to the CEO and senior team. Mid-way, the CEO interrupts with a sceptical question about your approach. The MOST effective response is:','Defer the question to after the presentation has finished to maintain your scripted flow.','Defend your approach firmly in the moment to show conviction to the CEO and senior team.','Engage: \"Fair concern — here\'s how I\'d address it. If I don\'t know, I\'ll come back by [date].\"','Acknowledge the concern and adjust your recommendation in real time to align with the CEO\'s view.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q114','SJT',NULL,'3','Executive Presence','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1759,8,'You need to deliver tough performance feedback to a long-tenured senior individual contributor who is sensitive. The MOST effective approach is:','Clear and direct, anchored in respect: tenure, observations, the gap, listen, co-design forward.','Soften the feedback significantly to protect the long-standing relationship from being damaged.','Have HR present in the conversation to formalise the difficult feedback being delivered today.','Deliver the feedback through a written formal performance review document only this time around.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q115','SJT',NULL,'3','Difficult Performance Feedback','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1760,8,'Your communication style is direct. You realise it isn\'t landing well with senior counterparts from cultures with less direct norms. The MOST mature adaptation is:','Use intermediaries from their culture to deliver the difficult messages on your behalf instead.','Adapt: relational warmth, private settings, face-preserving framing; keep content; ask what works.','Maintain your own style — the senior counterparts need to adapt to professional norms today.','Stop giving difficult feedback to those counterparts to avoid creating any further friction.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q116','SJT',NULL,'3','Cross-Cultural','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1761,8,'In a senior meeting, you sense the energy has dropped significantly mid-discussion. The MOST effective in-the-moment response is:','Suggest a quick break for the room to reset before continuing with the rest of the agenda.','Name it lightly: \"I notice we\'ve slowed down — what\'s not landing? Let\'s pause and adjust now.\"','Power through the agenda and finish the planned discussion topics at the originally set pace.','Move to less controversial topics on the agenda to restore the energy in the meeting room.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q117','SJT',NULL,'3','Reading the Room','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1762,8,'You and a senior peer have had escalating tension over recent weeks. The MOST mature initiation of repair is:','Wait for the senior peer to bring up the tension between you when they are ready to do so.','Communicate the issue through a written email exchange to be precise about your concerns.','Address the issue in a joint meeting where others are present to mediate the conversation.','Schedule private: \"Things have felt off. I value the relationship. Can we figure this out?\"','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q118','SJT',NULL,'3','Difficult Conversation Initiation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1763,8,'You made a public mistake that affected colleagues. The MOST effective apology is:','Personal apologies to those affected; specific acknowledgment; own without qualification; then public.','Move forward and demonstrate improvement through your future action rather than apologising.','Give a brief apology in the next team meeting to acknowledge the mistake to the colleagues affected.','Send a written apology to all affected parties simultaneously in a single email message thread.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q119','SJT',NULL,'3','Apology','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1764,8,'You want to build your external professional reputation. The MOST effective long-term strategy is:','Develop deep perspectives from real work; share consistently; engage genuinely; compound over years.','Wait to be invited by your reputation alone after the work speaks for itself over time.','Speak at industry conferences and write articles frequently in your area of professional focus.','Build a large social media following on professional platforms to grow your industry visibility.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q120','SJT',NULL,'3','Building External Reputation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1765,8,'You have built a significant external professional network over years. The MOST effective way to sustain it is:','Wait for organic re-engagement when others reach out to you when they have a specific need.','Reach out to the network in periodic mass outreach when you have a specific need from them.','Reach out to people only when you have something genuinely useful to offer to them yourself.','Maintain deliberately: useful contact, reciprocity, occasional substantive coffee chat.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q121','SJT',NULL,'3','Network Stewardship','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1766,8,'You believe the CEO is making a significant strategic error. You\'ve raised it once; they disagreed. The MOST mature next step is:','Build a coalition of peers to share the concern jointly to amplify the message to the CEO.','One more private chat: \"Stakes are high. Might be wrong — but here\'s my specific concern.\"','Drop the concern entirely — you\'ve already raised it once and they have made their decision.','Continue raising the concern publicly until the CEO eventually changes their position on it.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q122','SJT',NULL,'3','Saying Hard Truth to CEO','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1767,8,'I am comfortable and credible communicating with very senior leaders, including the board.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q123','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Executive Presence','{\"likert\":true}'),(1768,8,'My written communication consistently leads with the bottom line and is structured for senior readers.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q124','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Written Communication','{\"likert\":true}'),(1769,8,'I am fully present when listening, not formulating my reply.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q125','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Listening','{\"likert\":true}'),(1770,8,'I adapt my communication style to different stakeholders without losing my authenticity.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q126','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Stakeholder Calibration','{\"likert\":true}'),(1771,8,'I speak up with substance in senior meetings, even when junior to others present.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q127','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Speaking Up','{\"likert\":true}'),(1772,8,'I stay composed under sharp questioning or visible disagreement.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q128','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Composure','{\"likert\":true}'),(1773,8,'I give honest, specific, actionable feedback even when it\'s uncomfortable.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q129','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Difficult Feedback Giving','{\"likert\":true}'),(1774,8,'I can receive critical feedback without becoming defensive.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q130','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Difficult Feedback Receiving','{\"likert\":true}'),(1775,8,'I use stories and specific examples effectively to communicate complex business points.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q131','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Storytelling','{\"likert\":true}'),(1776,8,'I can move senior stakeholders to support a position when I genuinely believe in it.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q132','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Persuasiveness','{\"likert\":true}'),(1777,8,'I can read the energy and dynamics of a room and adjust in real time.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q133','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Reading Room','{\"likert\":true}'),(1778,8,'My communication is disciplined and brief — I leave out what doesn\'t serve the message.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q134','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Brevity','{\"likert\":true}'),(1779,8,'I sometimes share more context than necessary, especially under pressure.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q135','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','3','Verbosity','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1780,8,'When my approach is challenged, my first instinct is to defend rather than consider.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q136','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','3','Defensiveness','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1781,8,'How often do you re-read and edit important written communications before sending?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q137','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','3','Writing Discipline','{\"likert\":true}'),(1782,8,'How often do you ask thoughtful questions in meetings, rather than primarily sharing your views?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q138','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','3','Asking vs Telling','{\"likert\":true}'),(1783,8,'How often do you proactively maintain external professional relationships?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q139','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','3','Network Maintenance','{\"likert\":true}'),(1784,8,'How often do you reflect after significant conversations on what you communicated well and what could have been better? PILLAR 04  ·  SUSTAINED PERFORMANCE & WELLNESS Executive burnout prevention, identity beyond work, energy management, family-work integration, and the wellness foundations required for a long enterprise career. Items in this pillar: 30','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q140','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','3','Reflection','{\"likert\":true}'),(1785,8,'Research on executive burnout consistently identifies which factor as the strongest protective factor over long careers?','Recovery cycles, identity beyond work, and relationships.','Working noticeably fewer hours per week than peers.','Operating in a lower-stress role with less responsibility.','Higher compensation and significant equity ownership.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q141','K',NULL,'4','Executive Burnout','[]'),(1786,8,'Tony Schwartz\'s research at The Energy Project highlights that sustainable high performance requires:','Working longer hours during periods of peak demand.','Eliminating all non-essential activities from daily routines.','Maximising the total time spent on focused work tasks.','Managing energy across four dimensions with recovery cycles.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q142','K',NULL,'4','Performance Recovery','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1787,8,'\'Decision fatigue\' research consistently shows that:','Group decisions effectively counter individual decision fatigue.','Decision quality remains constant across the day if alert.','Important decisions should be made at the end of the day.','Decision quality declines with cumulative decisions made.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q143','K',NULL,'4','Decision Fatigue','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1788,8,'Over the past 6 months, you\'ve felt persistent cynicism about work, declining energy, and reduced satisfaction. The MOST effective response is:','Wait for things to stabilise on their own — these phases often pass naturally over time.','Push through — senior roles often demand the kind of resilience this period is testing in you.','Change roles immediately to a different position that might be a better fit for you now.','Take real action: assess driver, engage coach, make structural changes, prioritise real recovery.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q144','SJT',NULL,'4','Senior Burnout Recognition','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1789,8,'Your senior leadership culture expects 24/7 availability. You are struggling to sustain it. The MOST mature response is:','Match the expectation no matter the personal cost since it\'s the cultural norm of the role.','Leave the senior role entirely to find a position that fits your boundaries better today.','Quietly maintain different boundaries from your peers without ever discussing it explicitly.','Address directly: \"Always-on is affecting effectiveness. Need a line on after-hours.\"','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q145','SJT',NULL,'4','Always-On Culture','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1790,8,'You realise that your sense of self has narrowed almost entirely to your work identity. The MOST mature response is:','Continue as is — high-performing senior careers naturally require this kind of work focus.','Take a long sabbatical from work entirely to rediscover yourself before returning fresh.','Make a career change to a less demanding role where you can have a broader life outside work.','Take it seriously: re-invest in relationships and interests outside work; protect them carefully.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q146','SJT',NULL,'4','Identity Beyond Work','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1791,8,'You are facing a major career decision (significant role change, geographic move, family-affecting choice). The MOST mature decision process is:','Default to the higher-prestige or higher-compensation option since those tend to win out anyway.','Decide quickly based on the financial and career implications of the various options on offer.','Outsource the decision entirely to a career coach who can guide you to the right choice for you.','Take time: define decision, multiple angles, trusted people, sit with it, trust your judgment.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q147','SJT',NULL,'4','Major Decision Reflection','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1792,8,'Your family is strained by your work demands. The MOST sustainable response is:','Direct talk at home and work; redesign actual structure; accept some career trade-offs honestly.','Move to a less demanding role at a different company to remove the source of family strain.','Promise to do better at home and try to manage through the strain with more efficiency at work.','Reduce your work demands immediately to prioritise family above career considerations entirely.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q148','SJT',NULL,'4','Family Strain','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1793,8,'You\'re considering taking a 3-month sabbatical. Your role permits it but the timing is never ideal. The MOST mature approach is:','Take repeated shorter breaks across the year instead of one long 3-month period away from work.','Wait until a clear window appears in your role before taking the planned 3-month sabbatical.','Plan deliberately: identify purpose, design coverage, structure to serve purpose, follow through.','Take the sabbatical at the soonest possible date once you have decided to take it at all.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q149','SJT',NULL,'4','Sabbatical Decision','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1794,8,'You\'re feeling stuck on a recurring leadership pattern you can\'t seem to change. The MOST effective response is:','Engage a qualified executive coach or therapist; outside perspective beats self-help for patterns.','Try harder to change the recurring pattern through willpower and self-discipline over time alone.','Read leadership books on the specific topic to develop a better understanding of the pattern.','Discuss the issue with senior peers to validate the difficulty and share experiences openly.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q150','SJT',NULL,'4','Coaching for Self','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1795,8,'You\'ve achieved a senior level. You sense you may have \'enough\' — the upward climb may no longer serve you, but the culture rewards continued ascent. The MOST mature response is:','Match the ascent of your peers in the company to avoid falling behind them as time goes on.','Step back from career ambition entirely and shift your focus to other priorities in your life.','Reflect seriously on what you want; question whether ascent equals success; make conscious choices.','Continue ascending in the company — opportunities at this level don\'t last forever once paused.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q151','SJT',NULL,'4','Saying Enough','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1796,8,'I manage my energy across the day, week, and year — not just my time.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q152','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Energy Management','{\"likert\":true}'),(1797,8,'I have genuine recovery practices — not just collapse or distraction.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q153','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Recovery','{\"likert\":true}'),(1798,8,'I maintain boundaries with work even when senior colleagues and the culture don\'t.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q154','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Boundaries','{\"likert\":true}'),(1799,8,'My sense of self does not depend primarily on my career.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q155','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Identity Beyond Work','{\"likert\":true}'),(1800,8,'I invest meaningfully in my closest relationships, even during demanding work periods.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q156','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Family/Relationship Investment','{\"likert\":true}'),(1801,8,'I maintain my physical health (exercise, sleep, nutrition, regular check-ups).','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q157','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Health','{\"likert\":true}'),(1802,8,'I have at least one person outside my work hierarchy I can talk honestly with about leadership challenges.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q158','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','External Perspective','{\"likert\":true}'),(1803,8,'I set aside dedicated time for reflection on my career and life, beyond operational thinking.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q159','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Reflection','{\"likert\":true}'),(1804,8,'I have clarity on what gives my work meaning beyond status or compensation.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q160','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Purpose Clarity','{\"likert\":true}'),(1805,8,'I am willing to seek professional help (coach, therapist, mentor) for entrenched challenges.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q161','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Help-Seeking','{\"likert\":true}'),(1806,8,'I can accept what I can\'t change and focus my energy on what I can.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q162','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Acceptance + Agency','{\"likert\":true}'),(1807,8,'I extend myself the same compassion I would extend a friend facing the same challenges.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q163','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Self-Compassion','{\"likert\":true}'),(1808,8,'I find it difficult to fully disconnect from work even during personal time.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q164','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','4','Always-On','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1809,8,'I find myself feeling more cynical about work and people than I used to.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q165','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','4','Cynicism','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1810,8,'My self-worth is significantly tied to my role and external recognition.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q166','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','4','Worth Tied to Role','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1811,8,'How often do you get 7+ hours of sleep, even during demanding periods?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q167','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Sleep','{\"likert\":true}'),(1812,8,'How often do you take real vacations where you completely disconnect from work?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q168','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Vacation','{\"likert\":true}'),(1813,8,'How often do you exercise (at least 30 minutes)?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q169','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Movement','{\"likert\":true}'),(1814,8,'How often do you spend dedicated time reflecting (journaling, mindful walks, deliberate quiet time)? PILLAR 05  ·  ENTERPRISE TECH GOVERNANCE AI governance, cybersecurity ownership, data privacy regulation, vendor risk management, digital transformation, and the technology-strategy fluency expected of senior business leaders. Items in this pillar: 30','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q170','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Reflection','{\"likert\":true}'),(1815,8,'When deploying AI/LLM capabilities in customer-facing enterprise contexts, the MOST critical governance consideration is generally:','Risk management: privacy, accuracy, compliance, audit.','Speed of deployment ahead of competitor capabilities.','Cost optimisation across the AI deployment lifecycle.','User interface design for the AI-powered experience.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q171','K',NULL,'5','AI Governance','[]'),(1816,8,'The NIST Cybersecurity Framework organises cybersecurity activities into which functions?','Defend, Block, Investigate, Report, Restore.','Plan, Build, Run, Audit, Improve continuously.','Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover.','Encrypt, Backup, Update, Monitor, Patch quickly.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q172','K',NULL,'5','Cybersecurity Frameworks','[]'),(1817,8,'The leading global data privacy regulations affecting most enterprises include:','GDPR, CCPA, LGPD, DPDP, and similar regional frameworks.','Only US federal-level privacy law and its state extensions.','Industry self-regulation under voluntary trade groups.','Only GDPR, which has global extraterritorial application.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q173','K',NULL,'5','Data Privacy Global','[]'),(1818,8,'When evaluating cloud vendor risk, key questions for enterprise should include:','Only the revenue scale and the size of the vendor.','Data location, encryption, certifications, exit terms.','Only the published price of the cloud service tier.','Only the uptime SLA the vendor commits to in writing.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q174','K',NULL,'5','Cloud Risk','[]'),(1819,8,'Research on digital transformation failure rates (McKinsey, BCG, others) consistently identifies the largest cause of failure as:','Wrong technology choice from the available enterprise platforms.','Errors in vendor selection for the transformation tooling.','Insufficient change management, leadership, and cultural shift.','Inadequate budgets allocated to the transformation programme.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q175','K',NULL,'5','Digital Transformation Failure','[]'),(1820,8,'When AI systems are used in significant business decisions (hiring, credit, insurance, healthcare), the MOST important enterprise discipline is:','Speed of automation across the relevant decision workflows.','Explainability, audit trail, bias testing, oversight.','Cost reduction through the use of AI-based decision systems.','Vendor selection from the leading AI platform providers.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q176','K',NULL,'5','AI in Decisions','[]'),(1821,8,'\'Vendor lock-in\' in enterprise technology refers to:','Single source of truth maintained in the vendor\'s data.','Long-term contracts signed with technology vendors.','Exclusive partnership agreements with a single vendor.','Dependency that makes switching to alternatives costly.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q177','K',NULL,'5','Vendor Lock-in','[]'),(1822,8,'The MOST common generative AI deployment failures in enterprise environments are:','Hallucination, data exposure, IP risk, compliance gaps.','Integration challenges with existing enterprise systems.','Slow performance of the AI in production environments.','User adoption challenges across the workforce affected.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q178','K',NULL,'5','Generative AI Risk','[]'),(1823,8,'\'Technical debt\' in enterprise contexts is most accurately described as:','Legacy systems that are waiting to be retired and replaced.','Future cost created by current shortcuts in design or build.','Money still owed by the enterprise to technology vendors.','Routine maintenance costs of running existing technology.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q179','K',NULL,'5','Tech Debt','[]'),(1824,8,'In enterprise data strategy, the typical maturity progression is:','Collection, reporting, analytics, prediction, AI.','AI first, then analytics, then traditional reporting.','Cloud platforms first, then on-premise deployment.','Custom software first, then off-the-shelf software.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q180','K',NULL,'5','Data Strategy','[]'),(1825,8,'In enterprise technology decisions, the \'make vs buy\' question typically favours \'buy\' when:','The capability is non-differentiating and mature vendors exist.','Whenever the engineering team has spare capacity available.','Always — building software is more expensive in every case.','Always — building always creates valuable intellectual property.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q181','K',NULL,'5','Make vs Buy','[]'),(1826,8,'In organisations with strong IT-business alignment, a key practice is generally:','IT defines technology strategy and business adapts to it.','Business defines requirements and IT executes on them.','Joint accountability and integrated senior planning.','IT operates independently to maintain technical purity.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q182','K',NULL,'5','IT-Business Alignment','[]'),(1827,8,'Senior business leaders evaluating cybersecurity investment should think about it as:','Risk management proportional to data value and threat impact.','Insurance-equivalent — buy coverage, don\'t actively manage it.','Purely an IT department concern, not a strategic business issue.','A pure cost centre to be minimised wherever this is possible.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q183','K',NULL,'5','Security Investment','[]'),(1828,8,'When evaluating processes for automation (RPA, AI, etc.), the MOST common mistake is:','Underinvesting in change management around the automation.','Automating a broken process without first redesigning it.','Choosing the wrong automation technology for the process.','Selecting the wrong vendor to deliver the automation work.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q184','K',NULL,'5','Process Automation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1829,8,'In modern enterprises, senior leaders should think about technology talent strategy as:','A strategic question about the right capability mix.','An IT problem to be handled within the IT function alone.','A reactive response to vacancies as they arise across teams.','Purely a cost optimisation question for the finance team.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q185','K',NULL,'5','Tech Talent Strategy','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1830,8,'Your business unit is debating AI deployment for customer service. The MOST mature leadership approach is:','Pilot rigorously: scope, metrics, governance, rollback; scale based on evidence not enthusiasm.','Mandate adoption across the customer service team to drive the efficiency gains across the board.','Adopt AI immediately — competitors are moving and the unit cannot afford to fall behind now.','Wait for industry standards to emerge before the business unit makes any deployment decisions.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q186','SJT',NULL,'5','AI Adoption Decision','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1831,8,'Your company has suffered a significant data breach. As a senior leader, the MOST appropriate immediate response is:','Wait until you can announce a complete resolution to the breach before communicating outwards.','Activate response: cross-functional team, known/unknown, notification, transparent comms, update.','Issue a reassuring statement to customers to manage the perception while investigation continues.','Wait for IT to fully investigate the breach before any communication goes out to stakeholders.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q187','SJT',NULL,'5','Cybersecurity Incident','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1832,8,'Your business depends on a legacy system that frustrates everyone. Migration would be expensive and risky. The MOST mature approach is:','Quantify cost of staying vs migrating with risk; propose phased path with clear off-ramps.','Build a workaround layer on top of the legacy system to mitigate frustration without migration.','Migrate the legacy system to a modern platform immediately to remove the source of frustration.','Continue indefinitely with the legacy system since migration is too costly and risky right now.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q188','SJT',NULL,'5','Legacy System Decision','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1833,8,'Your company is increasingly using AI in customer-facing communications. The MOST mature approach is:','Disclose AI use only when legally required to do so by regulation in the relevant jurisdiction.','Use AI everywhere across customer communications to maximise efficiency for the business unit.','Be transparent with customers about AI use; ensure quality; provide easy paths to human contact.','Conceal AI use entirely to maintain a personal feel in customer-facing communications today.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q189','SJT',NULL,'5','Generative AI Disclosure','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1834,8,'Your company has become heavily dependent on a single major technology vendor. The MOST mature response is:','Request a significant discount from the vendor as leverage from the depth of the dependency.','Assess strategically; multi-year strategy: diversification, protections, exit-readiness; balanced.','Switch to a competitor vendor immediately to reduce the dependency on the single major vendor.','Continue with the vendor — switching from the single major technology vendor is too costly.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q190','SJT',NULL,'5','Vendor Strategy','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1835,8,'I can participate substantively in enterprise technology strategy conversations.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q191','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Tech Strategy Fluency','{\"likert\":true}'),(1836,8,'I understand both the capabilities and the risks of generative AI in enterprise contexts.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q192','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','AI Sophistication','{\"likert\":true}'),(1837,8,'I make decisions informed by data while remaining appropriately skeptical of data quality and limitations.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q193','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Data-Driven Decisions','{\"likert\":true}'),(1838,8,'I take cybersecurity seriously as a senior leadership accountability, not just an IT issue.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q194','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Cybersecurity Awareness','{\"likert\":true}'),(1839,8,'I can translate between business and technology stakeholders effectively in both directions.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q195','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Tech-Business Translation','{\"likert\":true}'),(1840,8,'When presented with technology vendor claims, I instinctively ask about evidence, references, limitations, and total cost.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q196','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Critical Skepticism','{\"likert\":true}'),(1841,8,'I follow strong personal digital security practices.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q197','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Digital Hygiene','{\"likert\":true}'),(1842,8,'How often do you engage with technology trends affecting your industry (publications, briefings, conversations with technologists)?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q198','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','5','Tech Awareness','{\"likert\":true}'),(1843,8,'How often do you use data to inform important decisions, rather than relying primarily on intuition?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q199','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','5','Data Use','{\"likert\":true}'),(1844,8,'How often do you personally experiment with AI tools to understand their capabilities and limitations?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q200','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','5','AI Experimentation','{\"likert\":true}'),(1845,9,'A \'strategic partnership\' (as distinct from a vendor relationship) typically requires which of the following from both parties?','Long-term exclusive contract commitments on both sides involved.','Volume-based discount terms negotiated for the relationship.','Aligned interests, joint investment, and shared risk-reward.','Equity exchange between the two parties involved in the deal.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q001','K',NULL,'1','Strategic Partnership','[]'),(1846,9,'When a customer is in the middle of being acquired, the most appropriate commercial posture is generally:','Withdraw from the relationship until the acquisition completes.','Pause major commitments and engage carefully with both sides.','Continue selling as if nothing in the relationship has changed.','Push to close major deals before the acquisition completes.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q002','K',NULL,'1','M&A Adjacency','[]'),(1847,9,'An \'ecosystem strategy\' (vs a product strategy) typically means:','Selling more products from the existing portfolio of offerings.','Diversifying the business into adjacent industries very quickly.','Building value through partners and complementor relationships.','Acquiring multiple companies in the same product category space.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q003','K',NULL,'1','Ecosystem Strategy','[]'),(1848,9,'When considering a strategic pricing change at company scale, the MOST important analysis dimension is generally:','Price elasticity and willingness-to-pay across segments.','Competitor pricing across the relevant market segments today.','Cost basis of the product across the entire production line.','Margin targets set by finance for the product line.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q004','K',NULL,'1','Pricing Strategy','[]'),(1849,9,'Direct sales versus channel (reseller / partner) sales models typically have which trade-off?','Direct and channel produce essentially identical outcomes.','Direct is always more profitable than partner channels.','Direct gives higher margin; channel gives faster reach.','Channel is always faster to scale than a direct salesforce.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q005','K',NULL,'1','Channel Strategy','[]'),(1850,9,'From a CEO/board perspective, customer concentration above ~20% of revenue from a single customer is generally:','Optimal for operational efficiency in the relationship.','Not a concern provided the customer remains satisfied.','A material risk that affects valuation and financing terms.','A sign of strong execution and customer relationship strength.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q006','K',NULL,'1','Customer Concentration Risk','[]'),(1851,9,'A \'strategic account\' (as opposed to a large account) is best defined by:','Account profitability measured against blended targets.','Account size measured by the revenue contributed annually.','Account longevity measured by years of active relationship.','Strategic importance beyond direct revenue contribution.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q007','K',NULL,'1','Strategic Account','[]'),(1852,9,'The \'bowtie\' GTM model (replacing the funnel in modern SaaS thinking) represents:','Equal-weighted acquisition and expansion stages mirrored.','A more decorated version of the traditional sales funnel.','A pricing strategy used in modern SaaS company go-to-market.','An organisational structure for the modern commercial team.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q008','K',NULL,'1','Bowtie Model','[]'),(1853,9,'In high-stakes negotiations, sending a negotiator with limited authority (the \'limited authority\' tactic) can be effective because:','It is required by most major negotiation frameworks in use today.','It allows time to consult and prevents emotional escalation.','It is unethical and should be avoided in any serious deals.','It always speeds up the pace of complex negotiations greatly.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q009','K',NULL,'1','Negotiation Authority','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1854,9,'Systematic win/loss analysis at executive level should focus most on:','Pricing analysis on the deals won and lost in the quarter.','Individual sales rep performance compared with their peers.','Patterns across deals to inform strategy and positioning.','Sales activity volume across the team and the period.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q010','K',NULL,'1','Win/Loss Discipline','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1855,9,'You are the CEO. Your largest customer\'s CEO requests a one-on-one meeting. The MOST effective preparation is:','Diligence: their strategy, recent earnings, prepare 2-3 substantive ideas you might bring.','Prepare a comprehensive update on what your company is currently doing for them right now.','Have your sales team brief you on the current state of the customer relationship today.','Bring your senior sales lead with you to the meeting so they can field operational detail.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q011','SJT',NULL,'1','CEO-to-CEO Conversation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1856,9,'Your largest customer (15% of revenue) is signalling they may not renew. The MOST appropriate executive response is:','Begin scenario planning for the customer loss while continuing routine account engagement.','Engage exec sponsor; listen, take ownership, design substantive response; diversify also.','Delegate the recovery effort to your Chief Customer Officer to handle on your behalf.','Authorise whatever discount or commercial change is needed to retain the major customer.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q012','SJT',NULL,'1','Major Customer Threatens to Leave','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1857,9,'You are negotiating a strategic partnership with a peer-company CEO. They are pushing for terms that favour them substantially. The MOST mature response is:','Escalate the negotiation to your board for guidance on how to handle the unfair terms.','Hold firm on your position and prepare to walk away from the partnership entirely now.','Concede the disputed terms to get the strategic partnership signed and moving forward.','Pause commercial detail; re-engage at strategic level: define success for both 3+ years.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q013','SJT',NULL,'1','Strategic Partnership Negotiation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1858,9,'Your team has brought you a large deal to approve. The signals (customer behaviour during negotiation, post-sale service implications, strategic fit) suggest this will be a costly customer. The MOST disciplined response is:','Structured fit review: 5-year P&L with service cost, churn risk, opportunity; decide cleanly.','Decline the deal — strategic fit is paramount and this one is misaligned for the company.','Approve the deal — large revenue volumes are hard to turn down at this point in the quarter.','Approve the deal but raise the price significantly to compensate for the projected risks.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q014','SJT',NULL,'1','Walking Away From Big Deal','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1859,9,'Your team proposes raising prices 15% on new customers. Demand is strong, switching costs are high. The MOST rigorous executive decision-process is:','Phase the increase: start with 5% across new customers first, then evaluate impact in 6 months.','Approve the price increase based on the strong team confidence in the proposal as it stands.','Defer the decision on price increases entirely — pricing changes are too risky to take on now.','Require rigour: elasticity, willingness-to-pay, competitor, signal; test on segment 90 days.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q015','SJT',NULL,'1','Pricing Power Decision','{\"weights\":{\"a\":2,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1860,9,'Your largest competitor has just been acquired by a much larger company with deeper pockets. Your team is alarmed. The MOST effective leadership response is:','Strategic review: capability change, where they\'ll move, defensible position, double down where.','Match the competitor\'s likely investment increase to maintain your relative market position.','Reassure the team that nothing has fundamentally changed in your competitive picture today.','Begin negotiating an exit or sale of your own company while the market is still strong now.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q016','SJT',NULL,'1','Competitor Acquisition','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1861,9,'Your top 5 customers represent 60% of revenue. The MOST appropriate strategic response is:','Maintain top accounts while explicitly investing in adjacent segments over 18-36 months ahead.','Begin exploring acquisitions to diversify the customer base quickly through inorganic growth.','Continue current execution since the top 5 customers are profitable for the business today.','Reduce focus on the top 5 customers to allow diversification of the base to happen naturally.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q017','SJT',NULL,'1','Customer Diversification','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1862,9,'Your sales channel partners are increasingly upset about your direct sales motion competing with them. The MOST mature response is:','Continue with both motions and let channel partners compete with direct sales for the deals.','Design clear rules of engagement: which segments are which; hold consistently; lose short-term.','Eliminate the direct sales motion entirely to preserve the channel partnerships fully going forward.','Increase partner margins to compensate them for the direct competition they are facing today.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q018','SJT',NULL,'1','Channel Conflict','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1863,9,'Your board is pushing aggressively for revenue growth that you believe would require unsustainable customer-acquisition spending. The MOST mature response is:','Push back on the board\'s request and risk losing their confidence in your leadership of the company.','Begin looking for a new CEO role since the board\'s pressure has become unsustainable for you.','Execute the growth plan as the board has requested to maintain their confidence in your strategy.','Engage: present unit economics, CAC, LTV scenarios; explicit strategic choice; then defer.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q019','SJT',NULL,'1','Board Pressure','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1864,9,'You have decided to raise prices 12% on contract renewals. The MOST effective communication approach to existing customers is:','Email all customers simultaneously with the price increase announcement for transparency now.','Apply the price increase quietly at renewal without prior notification to the customers.','Tier approach: personal exec to strategic, structured to mid-tier, standard to long-tail; runway.','Have account managers communicate the price change during routine business reviews each.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q020','SJT',NULL,'1','Pricing Communication to Existing Customers','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1865,9,'Your team has been pursuing a transformative account for 18 months without conversion. The MOST disciplined executive decision-process is:','Decline future engagement with the account based on sunk cost from the past 18 months invested.','Continue pursuing the account — strategic pursuits of this size simply take time to convert.','Structured review: learnings, probability, opportunity cost; commit explicitly or withdraw cleanly.','Replace the lead pursuit team with a fresh team that may have new ideas for the account.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q021','SJT',NULL,'1','Long-cycle Strategic Pursuit','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1866,9,'Two weeks before quarter-end, you are 8% short of guidance. The MOST mature response as CEO is:','Diagnose: quarter timing or structural? Sober call; transparent with board; don\'t engineer it.','Convene daily war-room sessions with the team to drive deal closure in the final two weeks.','Pull demand from the next quarter via aggressive incentives to make the current numbers work.','Push the team to apply aggressive discounting on open deals to close the gap before quarter end.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q022','SJT',NULL,'1','Quarterly Pressure as CEO','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1867,9,'You are about to visit the CEO of an important customer. Your sales team has shared a detailed brief. The MOST effective use of pre-visit time is:','Memorise the operational details from the team\'s brief so you can demonstrate command of the account.','Prepare a proposal for additional business that you can pitch directly during the meeting today.','Read their recent earnings; understand worries; prepare one substantive question or perspective.','Prepare a comprehensive update of your company\'s roadmap to share during the customer meeting.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q023','SJT',NULL,'1','Executive Customer Visit','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1868,9,'A potential customer is large and prestigious but their values and behaviour are incompatible with your company culture. The MOST mature response is:','Negotiate aggressive contractual terms that protect against the projected cultural mismatch.','Decline transparently to team: \"Here\'s why; here\'s what we protect. This is what discipline looks like.\"','Pursue the deal — the prestige value of having the customer\'s logo will compensate for the friction.','Decline the deal quietly without sharing any explanation with the customer or the wider team.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q024','SJT',NULL,'1','Strategic Decline of Customer','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1869,9,'Two of your strategic partners are in dispute, and each is pulling you to take sides. The MOST mature response is:','Side with the partner that is more important to your business strategically right now.','Encourage the partners to resolve the dispute before you continue engaging with either of them.','Engage neutrally: honest chats with each; decline sides; clear on principles; preserve both.','Stay out of the dispute between the two partners entirely without engaging on either side.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q025','SJT',NULL,'1','Ecosystem Dispute','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1870,9,'I am comfortable engaging at CEO/board level with substantive strategic conversation, not just relationship management.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q026','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','CEO-Level Conversation','{\"likert\":true}'),(1871,9,'I can hold strategic patience on long-cycle pursuits without losing focus or pressure-discounting.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q027','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Strategic Patience','{\"likert\":true}'),(1872,9,'I hold commercial discipline at company scale, even when individual deals tempt away from it.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q028','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Commercial Discipline at Scale','{\"likert\":true}'),(1873,9,'I think about my strategic accounts as a portfolio with deliberate investment patterns, not individually.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q029','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Strategic Account Portfolio','{\"likert\":true}'),(1874,9,'I model the discipline of walking away from bad-fit revenue for my team.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q030','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Walking Away','{\"likert\":true}'),(1875,9,'I think about my business as part of an ecosystem of partners, customers, competitors — not in isolation.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q031','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Ecosystem Thinking','{\"likert\":true}'),(1876,9,'I have built recognised industry stature through publications, speaking, or visible thought-leadership.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q032','SCI','Strongly Agree','1','Industry Stature','{\"likert\":true}'),(1877,9,'Under quarter-end pressure, I have approved discounts or terms that I later regretted.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q033','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','1','Quarterly Pressure','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1878,9,'I sometimes accept customers I should decline because of revenue pressure or board expectations.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q034','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','1','Avoidance of Hard Walk-Aways','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1879,9,'How often do you (personally, as a senior executive) spend time with your top customers\' senior leadership? PILLAR 02  ·  ORGANISATIONAL LEADERSHIP AT SCALE Strategy and execution; capital allocation; board governance; culture; talent and succession; M&A; crisis leadership; and the integrated capabilities that distinguish exceptional senior leaders from competent ones. Heaviest weight - this is the central work at senior levels. Items in this pillar: 70','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q035','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','1','Customer Executive Time','{\"likert\":true}'),(1880,9,'Roger Martin\'s \'Playing to Win\' framework defines strategy as the answer to five integrated questions, the first of which is:','What management systems do we need to support the strategy?','What capabilities must we have to execute the strategy?','How will we win in the chosen markets and segments?','What is our winning aspiration for the organisation?','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q036','K',NULL,'2','Strategy Execution','[]'),(1881,9,'Galbraith\'s \'Star Model\' of organisation design identifies five interlocking design points:','Strategy, Tactics, Goals, Roles, Metrics tracking.','Strategy, Structure, Processes, Rewards, People.','Plan, Organise, Lead, Control, Continuously Innovate.','Vision, Mission, Values, Culture, Capabilities.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q037','K',NULL,'2','Org Design','[]'),(1882,9,'In Will Thorndike\'s \'The Outsiders\' analysis of exceptional CEOs, the single most important CEO skill identified is:','Capital allocation across investment alternatives.','Cultural leadership across the senior executive team.','Operational excellence across day-to-day execution.','Deep industry expertise built up over many years.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q038','K',NULL,'2','Capital Allocation','[]'),(1883,9,'Research on M&A outcomes consistently shows that most acquisitions:','Fail to create value for the acquirer\'s shareholders.','Create more value than equivalent organic investment.','Create significant value for the acquirer\'s shareholders.','Have a neutral effect on shareholder value over time.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q039','K',NULL,'2','M&A','[]'),(1884,9,'In corporate governance, the primary fiduciary duty of board directors is to:','Whichever stakeholder group is currently most vocal.','The CEO who appointed them to the board seat.','Quarterly earnings performance and market sentiment.','The corporation and its long-term shareholders.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q040','K',NULL,'2','Board Dynamics','[]'),(1885,9,'Jim Collins\'s principle of \'first who, then what\' from \'Good to Great\' argues that:','Get the right people on board before deciding the direction.','Hire fast and fire fast to keep team performance high overall.','Hire only people who already agree with the chosen strategy.','People matter more than strategy in early-stage startup contexts.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q041','K',NULL,'2','Talent Strategy','[]'),(1886,9,'Edgar Schein\'s framework for understanding organisational culture identifies three levels, from most visible to deepest:','Artifacts, Espoused Beliefs, Underlying Assumptions.','Visible Symbols, Memorable Slogans, Recurring Stories.','Observable Behaviours, Stated Values, Shared Vision.','Documented Policies, Skilled People, Repeated Processes.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q042','K',NULL,'2','Org Culture','[]'),(1887,9,'Clayton Christensen\'s theory of \'disruptive innovation\' specifically refers to:','Any innovation that significantly disrupts a market.','Technology breakthroughs that reshape an industry.','Any aggressive new entrant into an established market.','Cheaper offerings for overlooked segments, moving up.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q043','K',NULL,'2','Disruption Theory','[]'),(1888,9,'Daniel Kahneman\'s work on decision-making distinguishes \'System 1\' and \'System 2\' thinking. Senior executives are particularly vulnerable to System 1 errors when:','They are tired, pressured, or trust their expert intuition.','Decisions are routine and have been made many times before.','They use spreadsheets to analyse the available options.','They consult with senior peers before deciding the issue.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q044','K',NULL,'2','Decision Quality','[]'),(1889,9,'In crisis communications research, the most effective initial leadership response is generally to:','Wait for full information before any communication is made.','Issue a brief denial until the facts are fully confirmed.','Communicate known and unknown promptly with accountability.','Defer all communication to the company\'s legal team only.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q045','K',NULL,'2','Crisis Leadership','[]'),(1890,9,'Research on CEO succession indicates that the single most predictive factor of successful transitions is:','Hiring an external successor with fresh outside perspectives.','Generous compensation packages for the incoming CEO leader.','A long deliberate process with multiple internal candidates.','Speed of transition to minimise the leadership uncertainty.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q046','K',NULL,'2','Succession Planning','[]'),(1891,9,'Edward Freeman\'s \'Stakeholder Theory\' argues that businesses should be managed for:','The full set of interdependent stakeholders of the firm.','Government regulators as the primary external stakeholder.','Shareholders alone, with others considered only instrumentally.','Each stakeholder weighted equally across all decisions.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q047','K',NULL,'2','ESG / Stakeholder','[]'),(1892,9,'Research on large-scale organisational transformations consistently shows that the typical failure rate of major transformation initiatives is approximately:','60–70% fail to deliver intended outcomes.','Failure rates are not reliably measurable.','30–40% fail to deliver intended outcomes.','10–20% fail to deliver intended outcomes.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q048','K',NULL,'2','Org Transformation','[]'),(1893,9,'\'Loss aversion\' (Kahneman & Tversky) refers to the empirical finding that:','People discount future losses heavily in their daily decisions.','People avoid risks in general across most decision contexts.','People prefer certainty to uncertainty across all decisions.','Pain of losing is about twice the pleasure of equivalent gain.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q049','K',NULL,'2','Behavioural Economics','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1894,9,'Research on executive compensation design has consistently found that the strongest predictor of long-term alignment between executive and shareholder interests is:','Performance bonuses tied directly to quarterly financial targets.','Higher total cash compensation paid annually to executives.','Broad profit-sharing arrangements across the executive team.','Significant equity with long vesting and holding requirements.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q050','K',NULL,'2','Compensation Strategy','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1895,9,'As CEO, your board is pressuring you to hit short-term numbers that would require deferring critical strategic investments. The MOST mature response is:','Defer the strategic investments quietly to hit the short-term numbers without further discussion.','Engage board with analysis: cost of hit vs deferral, 3-5 year value; make case with conviction.','Threaten to resign over the issue if the board insists on hitting short-term numbers this way.','Comply with the board\'s pressure — their position carries significant weight in the company.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q051','SJT',NULL,'2','CEO Decision Under Pressure','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1896,9,'A board director repeatedly pushes a position you believe is strategically wrong. The MOST effective response is:','Structured 1:1 outside boardroom: understand reasoning; share yours; see if synthesis possible.','Lobby other directors privately against the position to build opposition in the boardroom.','Defer to the director\'s seniority and accept the position even though you believe it is wrong.','Publicly disagree in the board meetings to expose the bad position to all other directors.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q052','SJT',NULL,'2','Strategic Disagreement with Board','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1897,9,'An executive on your team is consistently underperforming. They were hired by you 18 months ago at significant cost. The MOST mature response is:','Move them sideways to a less critical role where their underperformance won\'t impact as much.','Continue support — hiring decisions at this level often take more time to play out fully.','Direct conversation about the gap; clear improvement path with milestones; act if not delivered.','Hope it improves with more time and patience as they continue settling into the executive role.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q053','SJT',NULL,'2','Major Underperformer (Executive)','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1898,9,'Your CFO and CRO are in serious conflict over commercial pricing strategy. The MOST effective intervention as CEO is:','Structured session with both: present cases; surface underlying interests; decide openly; align.','Let the CFO and CRO work it out between themselves without your further involvement at all.','Split the difference between their two positions to be fair to both executives equally now.','Pick the position that aligns most with your own view on the commercial pricing strategy now.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q054','SJT',NULL,'2','CEO-CFO Conflict','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1899,9,'Market signals strongly suggest the core business is in long-term decline. A pivot would be transformational and risky. The MOST mature CEO posture is:','Transparent with board and team; rigorous analysis; sequential decisions; carry the team through.','Delegate the strategic decision to a transformation office that can focus on the work full time.','Continue optimising the core business — its cash flow funds the future strategy of the company.','Announce a dramatic pivot immediately to capture market attention and signal strategic intent.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q055','SJT',NULL,'2','Major Strategic Pivot','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1900,9,'You\'ve just been appointed CEO. You discover a deeply rooted culture of executive politicking and information-hoarding. The MOST effective intervention is:','Diagnose deeply; redesign reward systems; model the new behaviour; address politicians directly.','Bring in a top consulting firm to lead the culture transformation across the organisation soon.','Replace the executive team to break the old patterns of political behaviour across the company.','Announce a culture change initiative to signal that the new CEO takes culture seriously now.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q056','SJT',NULL,'2','Inheriting Cultural Problem','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1901,9,'Strategic necessity requires reducing headcount by 15%. The MOST humane and professionally responsible approach is:','Announce the reductions broadly first to manage the shock, then handle individuals afterwards.','Plan deeply: strategic criteria, severance exceeds standards, prepare managers, individual first.','Delegate the execution entirely to HR with broad criteria for them to apply across the company.','Use voluntary attrition naturally over a slower period to avoid the trauma of formal layoffs.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q057','SJT',NULL,'2','Layoffs at Scale','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1902,9,'A board director with strong industry credentials is bringing pet-project ideas to every meeting that distract from priorities. The MOST mature response is:','Tolerate the pattern — all boards have idiosyncratic directors with their own pet projects on hand.','Address it with the chair privately: \"Could we structure agendas to channel expertise productively?\"','Push the chair to remove the director from the board entirely at the next opportunity to do so.','Address the director directly in the next board meeting to flag the impact on the discussion.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q058','SJT',NULL,'2','External Board Director Dynamics','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1903,9,'A serious crisis hits - data breach, fatal accident, financial misstatement, or public scandal. The MOST effective initial response in the first 24 hours is:','Issue a brief initial denial of the crisis pending fuller facts becoming available later this week.','Wait for the full investigation to be complete before making any public statement on the crisis.','Mobilise rapidly: cross-functional team, communicate honestly, visible accountability, own it.','Have the PR team handle all communications during the first 24 hours of the unfolding crisis.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q059','SJT',NULL,'2','External Crisis','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1904,9,'Your strongest business unit is generating substantial cash. Multiple stakeholders advocate different uses: dividends, buybacks, M&A, organic R&D investment, debt paydown. The MOST disciplined approach is:','Distribute the capital proportionally across all of the proposed options to keep stakeholders happy.','Defer the capital allocation decision to the CFO to determine the best use of the cash flow.','Apply rigorous opportunity-cost analysis: after-tax return, strategic optionality; non-obvious calls.','Follow the industry peer practices on capital allocation since they have already worked through it.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q060','SJT',NULL,'2','Capital Allocation Tough Call','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1905,9,'Your top team is highly competent but homogeneous (same background, similar perspectives). The MOST effective response is:','Invest in cognitive diversity: hire against gaps; red teams; pre-mortems; acknowledge as risk.','Rotate the team\'s exposure to different parts of the business to broaden their perspectives over time.','Accept the senior team since it is currently highly performing and getting results for the company.','Hire external advisors to bring different perspectives into the senior team\'s decision-making.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q061','SJT',NULL,'2','Leadership Team Composition','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1906,9,'Your highest-performing executive consistently behaves in ways that violate stated company values (e.g., disrespect to peers, gaming systems). The MOST mature response is:','Tolerate the behaviour pattern since the executive\'s performance is critical to the company today.','Direct private chat: name the gap, values non-negotiable, agreed change with timeline; remove if not.','Address the issue through training or coaching to help the executive align with the values.','Reduce the executive\'s visibility across the organisation to limit damage from the values violations.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q062','SJT',NULL,'2','Performance vs. Values','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1907,9,'An activist investor has acquired a meaningful stake and is publicly criticising strategy. The MOST mature CEO response is:','Capitulate publicly to the activist\'s demands to avoid further public conflict on the strategy.','Engage with the activist exclusively through your company\'s lawyers as the official channel.','Refuse to engage with the activist publicly to maintain authority over the strategic narrative.','Engage openly: meet, listen to thesis, find legitimate critique, defend positions with evidence.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q063','SJT',NULL,'2','External Activist Investor','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1908,9,'A critical executive (whose departure would significantly damage the business) has just told you they\'re considering an external offer. The MOST mature response is:','Deep conversation about what they want next: address what\'s real; lose gracefully if right for them.','Make a heartfelt appeal to their loyalty and their commitment to the company over the years.','Accept the resignation gracefully to avoid being held hostage by retention conversations with them.','Counter with a significantly higher financial package immediately to retain them at the company.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q064','SJT',NULL,'2','Top Talent Resignation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1909,9,'A major social-political issue is dividing your customers and employees. Pressure mounts for the company to take a public stance. The MOST mature CEO response is:','Take the most popular position based on polling among your customers and your employees today.','Take a strong public stance that aligns with the dominant employee sentiment on the social issue.','Stay silent on the issue entirely to avoid alienating any of the customer or employee stakeholders.','Deliberate frame: relevant to business, stakeholders, or values? Clear principled stance; consistent.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q065','SJT',NULL,'2','Public Stance on Social Issue','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1910,9,'Two of your board directors have a serious personal conflict that is affecting governance. The MOST appropriate response is:','Have a private conversation with each director separately to understand their perspectives first.','Tolerate the conflict as a board matter that doesn\'t really require CEO direct intervention.','Side with the director whose position aligns more closely with your own on the governance matters.','Discuss openly with chair: \"I want to flag what I\'m observing. How would you like to address it?\"','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q066','SJT',NULL,'2','Conflict on Board','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1911,9,'You\'re a long-tenured CEO and sense your own thinking has become stale. The MOST mature response is:','Bring in challenging perspectives; question own assumptions; consider succession; genuine work.','Push harder on the existing company strategies that you have been executing as long-tenured CEO.','Continue in the role as is — stability of long-tenured leadership is valuable for the company.','Take an extended sabbatical from the role to refresh your thinking before returning to lead again.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q067','SJT',NULL,'2','Long-Tenure CEO Stagnation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1912,9,'An attractive M&A target has emerged. Your investment banker is enthusiastic. Strategic logic is plausible. The MOST disciplined approach is:','Hire McKinsey to validate the strategic fit of the M&A target with your company\'s strategy now.','Negotiate the price down significantly with the target to make the deal financially attractive.','Move quickly to lock in the M&A deal before competitors can bid up the target\'s price further.','Rigorous discipline: strategic fit, realistic synergy, integration, walk-away price, cultural fit.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q068','SJT',NULL,'2','M&A Decision','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1913,9,'Your compensation committee is proposing a significant increase in your pay package. The MOST mature response is:','Engage: \"Let\'s discuss design — cash vs vesting equity, how it compares to median employee pay.\"','Accept the increase but commit publicly to donating a portion of it to philanthropic causes.','Decline the proposed increase entirely to demonstrate selflessness to the board and employees alike.','Accept the proposed increase gracefully without raising any concerns about the structure of the package.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q069','SJT',NULL,'2','CEO Compensation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1914,9,'A major strategic initiative you championed has failed publicly. The MOST effective leadership response is:','Move past the failure quickly to avoid dwelling on it for too long with the leadership team.','Distance yourself from the decision that led to the failure to protect your overall credibility.','Own publicly: \"I made the call. Here\'s what I missed. Steady, accountable, learning.\"','Identify the external factors that contributed to the failure to share with the leadership team.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q070','SJT',NULL,'2','Public Failure','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1915,9,'You\'re building a new senior leadership team. The MOST important principle is:','Hire from your previous successful teams to ensure deep familiarity and high trust from day one.','Hire the most credentialed senior people available across the market for each of the open roles.','Hire for capability + values alignment + psychological maturity + complementarity with the team.','Hire for raw capability primarily across the senior leadership team being built for the company.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q071','SJT',NULL,'2','Building Senior Team','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1916,9,'You\'ve just taken over as CEO of an underperforming company. Stakeholders expect rapid action. The MOST disciplined first 90 days are:','Deep structured listening: 1:1s, observation, customer talks, board, financial; diagnose causes.','Replace the entire leadership team immediately to signal that significant change is coming now.','Wait the full 12 months in role before making any major changes to the company\'s strategy.','Announce a bold turnaround strategy in your first month to signal strong leadership to stakeholders.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q072','SJT',NULL,'2','Inheriting Underperforming Company','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1917,9,'Your business is mature and cash-generative but lacks innovation pipeline. Pressure exists to maintain margins. The MOST mature response is:','Explicit choices: % cash for innovation; separation from core; accept failures; protect portfolio.','Maintain the existing margins — innovation is overrated for mature cash-generative businesses now.','Fund innovation reactively as opportunities arise rather than as a deliberate strategic priority.','Cut R&D dramatically and return the resulting capital to shareholders as a structural strategy.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q073','SJT',NULL,'2','Innovation Investment','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1918,9,'Quarterly earnings are weaker than expected. Analyst pressure is high. The MOST effective communication is:','Emphasise the positive aspects of the quarter to manage the narrative for the sceptical analysts.','Commit to an aggressive next-quarter rebound to give the analysts a positive headline for the call.','Transparent: what happened, structural or temporary, what we\'re doing; acknowledge unknowns; defend.','Refuse to provide forward guidance for the next quarter to maintain maximum strategic flexibility.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q074','SJT',NULL,'2','Public Communication','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1919,9,'You\'re a senior executive at a founder-led company. The founder makes decisions you believe are mistakes. The MOST mature response is:','Defer to the founder\'s judgment on the company\'s strategic direction across all major decisions.','Implement the founder\'s decisions but quietly reduce your effort on the ones you disagree with.','Engage directly with respect: \"Here\'s the reasoning. Help me understand your thinking on this.\"','Build a quiet coalition with other executives to influence change in the founder\'s decisions.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q075','SJT',NULL,'2','Power Asymmetry with Founder','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1920,9,'Your business has significant exposure to a country whose geopolitical situation is deteriorating. The MOST mature response is:','Exit the country immediately to remove the geopolitical risk from the business\'s overall exposure.','Maintain operations in the country — markets often recover from geopolitical situations over time.','Hire a geopolitical advisor to monitor the situation and recommend actions to the executive team.','Scenario planning: develop concrete scenarios, decision triggers, optionality, indicators; sequential.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q076','SJT',NULL,'2','Geopolitical Risk','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1921,9,'A respected senior executive is showing signs of plateau - same performance level for 3 years. The MOST effective coaching is:','Wait for them to retire naturally rather than addressing the plateau in their performance now.','Give them more responsibility to stretch their performance back upward over the coming year ahead.','Direct generous conversation: \"Where\'s your next chapter? What would re-engage you?\" Then co-design.','Replace them with someone hungrier for the next stage of growth in the executive\'s current role.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q077','SJT',NULL,'2','Coaching Senior Underperformer','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1922,9,'You need to inform the board of a serious operational miss that wasn\'t anticipated. The MOST mature delivery is:','Reach out to chair immediately; structured briefing: facts, root cause, response plan, your asks.','Wait until the next scheduled board meeting to share the operational miss with the full board.','Frame the issue positively to maintain the board\'s confidence in the executive team during the call.','Brief the directors individually via 1:1 calls or email before convening the full board together.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q078','SJT',NULL,'2','Bad News to Board','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1923,9,'An investment opportunity has clear long-term value but takes 5+ years to pay off, with short-term P&L impact. The MOST mature response is:','Make the investment quietly without explicit communication to avoid drawing scrutiny from analysts.','Pass on the long-term opportunity entirely to protect the company\'s quarterly performance numbers.','Make the case rigorously: NPV, rationale, downside; engage board; defend through near-term pressure.','Make a smaller hedged version of the investment to balance the long-term value with the near-term P&L.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q079','SJT',NULL,'2','Long-Range Investment','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1924,9,'You\'re considering taking on an executive coach. The MOST effective use of executive coaching at senior level is:','Use coaching sparingly — executive coaches are generally for people with significant problems to solve.','Deliberate use on themes: thinking partner, mirror for blind spots, work on specific patterns.','Have monthly catch-up sessions with the coach as a form of general professional support over time.','Use the executive coach as a strategy consultant on the company\'s most important business decisions.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q080','SJT',NULL,'2','Executive Coaching','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1925,9,'I can hold strategic patience even under sustained pressure for short-term results.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q081','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Strategic Patience','{\"likert\":true}'),(1926,9,'I make sound decisions even with incomplete information and significant uncertainty.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q082','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Decision Under Ambiguity','{\"likert\":true}'),(1927,9,'I am rigorous about where I spend my own time and energy as a senior leader - matching it to highest-leverage work.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q083','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Personal Capital Allocation','{\"likert\":true}'),(1928,9,'I am skilled at building senior teams - the right people, the right composition, the right complementarity.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q084','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Building Teams','{\"likert\":true}'),(1929,9,'I am aware that my behaviour models culture for the organisation, and I behave accordingly.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q085','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Cultural Modelling','{\"likert\":true}'),(1930,9,'I work effectively with my board - using their wisdom while maintaining executive ownership.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q086','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Board Effectiveness','{\"likert\":true}'),(1931,9,'I can own visible failures publicly without ego damage that affects my subsequent leadership.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q087','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Public Failure Resilience','{\"likert\":true}'),(1932,9,'I weigh the interests of multiple stakeholders (employees, customers, community, shareholders) in my major decisions.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q088','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Stakeholder Capitalism','{\"likert\":true}'),(1933,9,'I have created conditions where people tell me uncomfortable truths.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q089','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Truth-Tellers','{\"likert\":true}'),(1934,9,'I deliberately renew my own thinking - new perspectives, challenges, learning.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q090','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Self-Renewal','{\"likert\":true}'),(1935,9,'I make hard people decisions decisively, even when emotionally costly.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q091','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Difficult People Decisions','{\"likert\":true}'),(1936,9,'In crisis, I am the calm anchor others can navigate by.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q092','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Composure Under Crisis','{\"likert\":true}'),(1937,9,'I have rigorous frameworks for capital allocation decisions, not just intuition.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q093','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Capital Allocation Skill','{\"likert\":true}'),(1938,9,'I can articulate my organisation\'s strategy in clear, simple language that cascades downward.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q094','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Strategic Clarity','{\"likert\":true}'),(1939,9,'I actively counter my own cognitive biases - especially in high-stakes decisions where I feel confident.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q095','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Bias Awareness','{\"likert\":true}'),(1940,9,'I am building succession - actively developing people who could replace me.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q096','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Succession Mindset','{\"likert\":true}'),(1941,9,'I am consistent in my values and behaviour whether I\'m with the board, employees, or peers.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q097','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Authenticity at Top','{\"likert\":true}'),(1942,9,'I own difficult strategic trade-offs personally rather than hiding them behind committees or consultants.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q098','SCI','Strongly Agree','2','Owning Hard Trade-offs','{\"likert\":true}'),(1943,9,'I have tolerated senior underperformers longer than I should have.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q099','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','2','Avoidance of Hard People Calls','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1944,9,'There are some topics or concerns I no longer raise because of the position I hold.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q100','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','2','Isolation','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1945,9,'I have continued strategies longer than I should have because of prior commitment to them.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q101','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','2','Sunk Cost','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1946,9,'My closest senior team rarely disagrees with me publicly.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q102','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','2','Surrounded by Yes','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1947,9,'How often do you spend dedicated time on talent decisions - hiring, developing, structuring teams?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q103','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','2','Time on Talent','{\"likert\":true}'),(1948,9,'How often do you actively seek perspectives outside your normal circles - different industries, generations, geographies?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q104','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','2','External Perspective','{\"likert\":true}'),(1949,9,'How often do you reflect rigorously on your major decisions - what worked, what you would do differently? PILLAR 03  ·  EXECUTIVE COMMUNICATION & INFLUENCE Board briefing, earnings calls, all-hands communication, crisis communication, written discipline, public presence, and the communication maturity expected at the top of organisations. Items in this pillar: 40','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q105','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','2','Structured Reflection','{\"likert\":true}'),(1950,9,'In executive briefings to boards, the most effective document structure is:','Bullet-pointed lists of all relevant facts in the case.','One-page executive summary with detail in the appendix.','Detailed analysis followed by the resulting recommendations.','Comprehensive narrative across background and the analysis.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q106','K',NULL,'3','Board Communication','[]'),(1951,9,'Barbara Minto\'s Pyramid Principle structures arguments such that:','Each supporting point answers the question above it.','Arguments are presented in chronological order overall.','Most important points come last within the argument.','Each section is structured into exactly three sub-points.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q107','K',NULL,'3','Pyramid Principle Mastery','[]'),(1952,9,'In communicating organisational change to thousands of employees, the most effective approach is generally:','Clear narrative through multi-channel cascaded communication.','Individual conversations with each team across the organisation.','Town halls where leadership explains the new strategy in detail.','A detailed strategic memo distributed company-wide via email.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q108','K',NULL,'3','Storytelling at Scale','[]'),(1953,9,'In Susan Scott\'s \'Fierce Conversations\', the principle that \'the conversation is the relationship\' means:','Difficult conversations should be avoided to preserve relations.','Conversations should focus on tasks and avoid feelings entirely.','All conversations are inherently relational by their nature.','Each significant conversation accumulates into the relationship.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q109','K',NULL,'3','Difficult Conversations','[]'),(1954,9,'Timothy Coombs\' situational crisis communication theory recommends that for crises where the organisation has clear responsibility, the appropriate response is:','Express sympathy for those affected without admitting fault.','Full apology with concrete rebuild and remediation actions.','Deny responsibility while preparing the legal defence.','Issue a brief statement and allow the news cycle to pass.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q110','K',NULL,'3','Crisis Communication','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1955,9,'In senior leadership listening, the most diagnostic form of listening is:','Listening primarily to formulate your reply.','Listening to confirm your existing views on the topic.','Listening for facts and information being presented.','Listening for what is unsaid in the conversation.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q111','K',NULL,'3','Listening Hierarchy','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1956,9,'You\'re delivering a quarterly earnings call with mixed results. Analysts are sceptical. The MOST effective communication posture is:','Lead the call with the positive aspects of the quarter and downplay the misses to manage perception.','Provide conservative forward guidance for next quarter to reset expectations dramatically lower now.','Transparent: address misses directly; defend strategic positions with evidence; commit credibly.','Refuse to comment on the specifics of the quarter to maintain maximum strategic flexibility.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q112','SJT',NULL,'3','Quarterly Earnings Call','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1957,9,'You\'re addressing the entire company (5,000+ employees) at a difficult moment. The MOST effective approach is:','Delegate the difficult parts of the all-hands to your Chief HR Officer to handle on your behalf.','Speak honestly: known and unknown; acknowledge impact; share conviction; open for genuine Q&A.','Deliver a fully prepared statement with no Q&A in order to maintain control over the communications.','Send a written memo to the entire company instead — less risk of saying the wrong thing live.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q113','SJT',NULL,'3','All-Hands Town Hall','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1958,9,'In a senior executive meeting, the CFO publicly disagrees with your strategic position in a way that feels personal. The MOST mature in-the-moment response is:','Stay silent in the meeting and address the public disagreement with the CFO privately later.','Match the CFO\'s energy in the moment with a sharp counter-point to defend the strategic position.','Stay composed: \"I hear your concern. Let me address [point].\" Address relationship privately later.','Defer to the CFO\'s view in the moment to maintain harmony with the senior team in the room.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q114','SJT',NULL,'3','Public Disagreement with Senior Peer','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1959,9,'A senior peer (same level as you) has been undermining your initiatives in conversations with your shared boss. The MOST mature response is:','Mirror their undermining behaviour to even the playing field between you in the relationship.','Escalate the undermining behaviour to your shared boss directly to handle the situation officially.','Document the pattern of undermining and prepare to raise it formally with HR at a later point.','Direct: \"I\'ve heard reflections of you raising concerns. Want to find a better way to work together.\"','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q115','SJT',NULL,'3','Tough Conversation with Senior Peer','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1960,9,'A major institutional investor has emailed concerns about your strategy. The MOST effective response is:','Issue a public response to the investor concerns to address them more broadly with the market.','Reply personally: thank, address each concern with evidence, offer direct conversation if useful.','Have your investor relations team draft a polite, neutral response on your behalf to the investor.','Decline to respond to the email since investor relations should be the channel for such concerns.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q116','SJT',NULL,'3','Email to Major Investor','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1961,9,'You need to brief the board on a major issue. The MOST effective document is:','A short email summary of the major issue sent to the board ahead of the next meeting on it.','1-2 page memo: issue, what happened and why, our response, asks from board, key risks; appendix.','A comprehensive 20-page analysis covering all of the angles of the major issue facing the board.','A verbal briefing only since written records of major issues can become discoverable in litigation.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q117','SJT',NULL,'3','Board Bad News','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1962,9,'You\'re being interviewed by a major business journalist who is known to be sceptical of your industry. The MOST effective preparation is:','Prepare scripted answers to all of the anticipated questions to control the interview narrative.','Speak entirely off-the-cuff during the interview to seem maximally authentic to the journalist.','Decline the interview entirely to avoid the risk of saying something that backfires later on.','Identify 2-3 key messages; prepare authentic substantive responses; practice bridging from hard.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q118','SJT',NULL,'3','Media Interview','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1963,9,'You\'re CEO of a founder-led company. The founder regularly contacts your executives directly, bypassing you. The MOST effective response is:','Direct conversation: \"Direct contact creates confusion. Let\'s find a pattern that uses your insight.\"','Resign from the CEO role if the founder\'s bypassing behaviour continues without any change.','Tolerate the founder\'s behaviour — the founder has the right as the company\'s founder to do it.','Instruct your executives to redirect founder communications back to you as the company\'s CEO now.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q119','SJT',NULL,'3','Founder Communication','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1964,9,'Your company has clearly caused harm to customers. The MOST effective public apology is:','Full responsibility: name the wrong, the harm, apologise; describe remediation; follow through.','Have your legal team review every word of the apology for liability exposure before issuing it.','Express regret about the situation publicly without acknowledging the company\'s specific fault.','Apologise broadly while emphasising the mitigating factors that contributed to the harm caused.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q120','SJT',NULL,'3','Public Apology','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1965,9,'Your largest customer is requesting a contractual concession that would set damaging precedent. The MOST mature response is:','Agree to a private version of the concession without making any public contractual commitment.','Concede the contractual point to the largest customer to keep the major commercial relationship.','Direct: \"Precedent across our customer base would damage us. Let\'s address what\'s driving this.\"','Refuse the request and let the relationship with the largest customer cool over the medium term.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q121','SJT',NULL,'3','Saying No to Major Customer','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1966,9,'In senior leadership team meetings, you notice quieter members rarely contribute on strategic topics. The MOST effective response is:','Restructure the senior leadership team toward more vocal personalities to improve the discussions.','Call on the quieter team members by name during senior leadership meetings to draw their input out.','Accept the dynamic — those team members who want to speak up on strategic topics eventually will.','Redesign: pre-share questions; round-robin; written input; 1:1s with quiet; check your own behaviour.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q122','SJT',NULL,'3','Executive Listening','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1967,9,'A serious crisis (data breach, layoffs, regulatory action) requires immediate communication to all employees. The MOST effective approach is:','Write it personally with help: direct, honest, specific, own where appropriate; all-hands next day.','Send a brief statement to all employees immediately and follow up with details over the coming days.','Delegate the crisis email entirely to your CHRO and brand team to manage the communication.','Wait for the full information about the crisis to be available before any communication is sent out.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q123','SJT',NULL,'3','Crisis Email to Workforce','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(1968,9,'You\'re keynoting a major industry conference. The MOST effective preparation is:','Read the prepared remarks verbatim during the keynote to maintain maximum message control today.','Improvise the keynote based on the energy in the room at the time of the actual presentation.','Identify 1-2 take-aways; build around them with stories; rehearse to internalise flow, not words.','Rehearse the prepared keynote speech until it is perfectly memorised word for word for the event.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q124','SJT',NULL,'3','Public Speaking at Major Event','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1969,9,'You\'re negotiating a major partnership with a senior leader from a culture with very different communication norms (high-context, hierarchical, relational). The MOST effective adaptation is:','Push for efficient transactional discussions to align with how the negotiation should proceed today.','Maintain your direct, content-focused style — they will adapt to professional norms over time.','Invest substantially in relationship first; adapt to their style; respect hierarchy; bring patience.','Bring a local cultural intermediary for all interactions to bridge the communication style gap.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q125','SJT',NULL,'3','Cross-Cultural Senior','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1970,9,'Your 360 feedback indicates you are perceived as \'intimidating\' and \'difficult to disagree with\'. The MOST mature response is:','Investigate who specifically said what in the 360 feedback to understand the underlying concerns.','Take seriously: reflect with coach; pick 2-3 behaviours to commit; share openly with team; track.','Defend yourself against the feedback — decisive leadership at senior levels requires clarity in style.','Soften your overall communication style across the board to address the 360 feedback received.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q126','SJT',NULL,'3','Receiving 360 Feedback at Senior Level','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":1}}'),(1971,9,'You\'re addressing employees during layoffs. Some are openly hostile. The MOST effective response is:','Move quickly to the next steps and the Q&A portion of the all-hands to keep the agenda moving.','Match their energy in the moment to assert leadership authority during the difficult announcement.','Stay present and composed; acknowledge the legitimacy of their pain; honest; take hard questions.','End the all-hands session early to avoid further escalation of the hostility from the employees.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q127','SJT',NULL,'3','Hostile Audience','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1972,9,'You need to communicate a complex strategic shift to senior leadership. The MOST effective format is:','Email summary of the strategic shift followed by individual conversations with each senior leader.','Amazon-style memo: structured prose, clear logic, depth; read silently; substantive dialogue follows.','Slide deck for visual impact during the senior leadership meeting about the strategic shift today.','Verbal briefing in the next senior leadership meeting to communicate the complex strategic shift now.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q128','SJT',NULL,'3','Internal Memo Discipline','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(1973,9,'A long-term friend and colleague has stopped performing at the level the role requires. The MOST mature response is:','Continue providing support out of loyalty to the long-term friendship between you over the years.','Move them to a different role at the company to avoid having the difficult performance conversation.','Have HR handle the difficult performance conversation with your long-term friend on your behalf.','Honest chat despite friendship: \"The role evolved beyond what\'s working. Talk about what\'s right.\"','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q129','SJT',NULL,'3','Difficult Conversation with Long-term Friend','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1974,9,'As a senior leader, you understand that symbolic acts (where you sit in meetings, who you spend time with, what you visibly prioritise) carry signal. In a moment of organisational stress, the MOST effective symbolic act is:','Hold a major leadership offsite to signal stability and continuity during the organisational stress.','Spend visible sustained time with front-line teams most affected: show up, listen, act on what.','Make a high-visibility executive change to signal that leadership takes the stress moment seriously.','Issue a strong public statement to acknowledge the organisational stress moment to all the staff.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q130','SJT',NULL,'3','Symbolic Acts','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1975,9,'You are preparing your annual letter to shareholders. The MOST effective approach is:','Highlight the year\'s successes; mention misses briefly to satisfy public disclosure requirements only.','Use the standard template the company has refined over years of writing shareholder letters.','Hire a professional writer to craft a polished, professional shareholder letter on your behalf.','Genuine reflective: own misses; explain logic; share what you\'re uncertain about; long-term partners.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q131','SJT',NULL,'3','Strategic Memoir','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(1976,9,'I am comfortable communicating at the highest levels - C-suite, board, investors, major media.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q132','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Executive Presence','{\"likert\":true}'),(1977,9,'I can write a clear, structured 1-page memo that captures complex strategic logic.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q133','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Written Discipline','{\"likert\":true}'),(1978,9,'In high-stakes moments under pressure, I become more composed and clear, not less.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q134','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Crisis Composure','{\"likert\":true}'),(1979,9,'I can read the dynamics of senior rooms - who has power, who\'s threatened, what\'s unsaid.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q135','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Reading the Room at Top','{\"likert\":true}'),(1980,9,'I initiate difficult conversations promptly - including with very senior people.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q136','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Difficult Conversations','{\"likert\":true}'),(1981,9,'I have created conditions where my closest team will tell me hard truths.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q137','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Listening to Hard Truth','{\"likert\":true}'),(1982,9,'I am effective speaking to large audiences (500+ people).','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q138','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Public Speaking','{\"likert\":true}'),(1983,9,'I can use stories effectively to communicate strategic positions to diverse audiences.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q139','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Storytelling','{\"likert\":true}'),(1984,9,'I adapt fluently across cultures - in negotiation, hierarchy, communication style.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q140','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Cross-Cultural Sophistication','{\"likert\":true}'),(1985,9,'I am willing to take public positions on important issues where my view matters.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q141','SCI','Strongly Agree','3','Voice in Public','{\"likert\":true}'),(1986,9,'Information often reaches me after it has been filtered or softened.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q142','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','3','Surrounded by Filter','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1987,9,'When I am criticised publicly, my first reaction is defensive.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q143','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','3','Defensiveness','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1988,9,'I have avoided difficult conversations because my position made them awkward.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q144','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','3','Avoidance','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(1989,9,'How often do you personally engage front-line employees and customers (not through layers of leadership)? PILLAR 04  ·  SUSTAINED SENIOR PERFORMANCE Executive isolation, identity beyond role, sustained energy over decades, family integration, anti-power-corruption practices, and the wellness foundations that determine whether a senior career ends in renewal or burnout. Items in this pillar: 25','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q145','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','3','Direct Engagement','{\"likert\":true}'),(1990,9,'Research on executive isolation (the \'lonely at the top\' phenomenon) consistently identifies that the strongest mitigations are:','Peer relationships outside the chain plus coaching support.','Holding more all-hands meetings across the wider organisation.','Reading more leadership books and listening to podcasts regularly.','Spending more time with family during personal off-time.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q146','K',NULL,'4','Executive Isolation','[]'),(1991,9,'Research on the psychological effects of holding power consistently finds that:','Power tends to make people more healthily decisive.','Sustained power reduces empathy and feedback intake.','Power has no measurable psychological effect on leaders.','Power tends to make people more empathetic over time.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q147','K',NULL,'4','Power and Psychology','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1992,9,'Research on post-role identity for senior executives (especially CEOs) suggests that those who navigate transitions best:','Took on multiple corporate board roles immediately afterwards.','Stayed engaged with their previous companies as advisors only.','Built identity beyond the role years before transitioning.','Continued in active executive roles as long as possible.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q148','K',NULL,'4','Identity Beyond Role','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1993,9,'You have been in a senior role for years. Energy is declining. The MOST mature response is:','Reduce your workload at the company secretly without raising it openly with the board or team.','Push through the energy decline with willpower until the natural cycle of the role shifts again.','Examine sleep, exercise, work; redesign week; take real break; be honest about role fit; decide.','Take vitamins and supplements to boost your energy levels during the demanding senior role period.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q149','SJT',NULL,'4','Sustained Energy at Senior Level','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1994,9,'Your family is showing signs of strain from your role demands. The MOST mature response is:','Tell the family this is the demand of senior roles and they need to adjust to it accordingly.','Promise to do better at home and try to manage the strain with more efficiency at the company.','Serious signal: deep talk at home; structural changes; sustainable rhythms; accept trade-offs.','Increase the household help to relieve the family\'s logistical load and reduce some of the strain.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q150','SJT',NULL,'4','CEO-Family Integration','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(1995,9,'You realise your identity has become almost entirely fused with your senior role. The MOST mature response is:','Plan for early retirement from the senior role to refocus on who you are outside it eventually.','Take time off from the role to figure out who you are outside the senior role at the company.','Take seriously: invest in interests outside role as serious identity work; build over years not weeks.','Continue as is — identity-role fusion is generally normal and expected at senior levels of business.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q151','SJT',NULL,'4','Building Identity Beyond Role','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(1996,9,'You\'ve been struggling with low mood and anxiety for months. The role makes it hard to admit. The MOST appropriate response is:','Engage a mental health professional confidentially; this is medical care, not leadership weakness.','Push through the symptoms — showing any weakness at this level undermines your leadership authority.','Try more meditation and exercise to address the persistent low mood and anxiety on your own first.','Take a sabbatical from the role to figure out the underlying issues before returning fresh later.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q152','SJT',NULL,'4','Mental Health Stigma at Top','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1997,9,'The most effective post-intense-work-cycle recovery at senior level typically involves:','Complete digital disconnection from all work systems for the entire duration of the recovery period.','Working a lighter schedule for the next few weeks rather than taking a fuller recovery break now.','Two-week vacation to a relaxing destination with your phone on for the occasional important call.','Disciplined active recovery: real disconnect, sleep, activity, restorative people, different challenge.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q153','SJT',NULL,'4','Recovery Discipline','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(1998,9,'You realise you\'re isolated at the top - few people you can speak honestly with. The MOST effective response is:','Build structures: peer CEO group, serious coach, pre-role friendships, close internal relationships.','Accept the isolation at the top as one of the natural costs of taking on senior leadership roles.','Confide more in your direct reports about the things you previously kept fully to yourself.','Talk more with your spouse about the details of work to ease the isolation you feel at the top.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q154','SJT',NULL,'4','Coping with Loneliness','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(1999,9,'You realise you no longer love the role, but it remains prestigious and well-compensated. The MOST honest response is:','Continue in the senior role — love for the work is a luxury at this senior level of leadership today.','Explore what you want next; test small experiments; transition over 2-3 years with intentionality.','Quit the role dramatically and figure out the next chapter once you have created some space.','Reduce your engagement in the current role while continuing to collect the full compensation package.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q155','SJT',NULL,'4','Career Identity Re-evaluation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(2000,9,'Multiple crises hit simultaneously (business issue, family stress, personal health concern). The MOST effective leadership posture is:','Acknowledge to inner circle; protect recovery; consequential decisions when calm; lean on team.','Power through the simultaneous crises hitting to demonstrate resilience to the team and the board.','Maintain a stoic public face while privately struggling with the simultaneous crises hitting today.','Take immediate leave from the role to deal with all of the crises before returning to lead again.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q156','SJT',NULL,'4','Sustained Composure','{\"weights\":{\"a\":3,\"b\":0,\"c\":1,\"d\":1}}'),(2001,9,'I have a clear sense of who I am outside my senior role.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q157','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Identity Beyond Role','{\"likert\":true}'),(2002,9,'I have genuine peer relationships with people at similar levels outside my organisation.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q158','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Peer Connection','{\"likert\":true}'),(2003,9,'I have at least one person I can be completely honest with about everything in my life.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q159','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Confidant','{\"likert\":true}'),(2004,9,'I have sustained the energy and engagement to operate at my best over years.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q160','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Sustained Energy','{\"likert\":true}'),(2005,9,'I take genuine breaks where I fully disconnect from work.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q161','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Recovery Discipline','{\"likert\":true}'),(2006,9,'My family relationships are healthy and I invest in them as priorities.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q162','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Family Investment','{\"likert\":true}'),(2007,9,'I maintain my physical health as a non-negotiable foundation.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q163','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Physical Health','{\"likert\":true}'),(2008,9,'I actively counter the distorting effects of holding power - through humility practices, peer accountability, direct contact with reality.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q164','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Power Humility','{\"likert\":true}'),(2009,9,'I have a clear sense of what I want this chapter of my career to be about.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q165','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Late-career Purpose','{\"likert\":true}'),(2010,9,'I treat myself with reasonable kindness when I fall short of my own standards.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q166','SCI','Strongly Agree','4','Self-compassion','{\"likert\":true}'),(2011,9,'If I lost this role tomorrow, I\'m not sure who I would be.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q167','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','4','Role Fusion','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(2012,9,'There are weeks when no one at work tells me anything I disagree with.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q168','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','4','Isolation Signal','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(2013,9,'I have prioritised work in ways that have come at meaningful cost to family relationships.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q169','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','4','Family Cost','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(2014,9,'How often do you spend genuine social time with peers outside your organisation? PILLAR 05  ·  TECHNOLOGY & DIGITAL STRATEGY GOVERNANCE Strategic engagement with AI, data, cyber, and digital transformation from the senior leader perspective: governance, capital allocation, talent, regulatory awareness, and the technology-strategy fluency expected of modern senior business leaders. Items in this pillar: 30','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q170','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','4','Peer Connection','{\"likert\":true}'),(2015,9,'From a C-suite perspective, the most important strategic question about generative AI in 2025-2026 is:','Where AI changes the basic economics of our business.','How many AI engineers to hire over the next two years.','Which AI vendor to standardise on across the organisation.','Which business functions to automate first using AI.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q171','K',NULL,'5','AI Strategy','[]'),(2016,9,'An effective enterprise AI governance framework typically includes:','Purely technical security review of AI vendor deployments.','A blanket ban on AI use until vendors prove their safety.','Risk-tiered policies, guardrails, and human oversight design.','Letting each business unit set its own internal AI policies.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q172','K',NULL,'5','AI Governance','[]'),(2017,9,'From a board oversight perspective, cybersecurity should be:','A regular board agenda item with quarterly reporting.','Reviewed annually as part of enterprise risk management.','Handled by the CISO without direct board involvement.','Delegated entirely to the audit committee oversight.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:47','Q173','K',NULL,'5','Cyber as Board Topic','[]'),(2018,9,'In modern strategic thinking, the primary competitive value of enterprise data comes from:','Regulatory compliance reporting across required jurisdictions.','Compounding strategic advantages through insight and AI.','Selling data to third parties in regulated marketplaces.','Cost reduction in internal reporting and analytics work.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q174','K',NULL,'5','Data as Asset','[]'),(2019,9,'The most common failure mode of large-scale digital transformation programs is:','Inadequate selection of the right enterprise technology choice.','Slow technology procurement processes across the firm.','Treating it as a technology project, not a business shift.','Insufficient budget allocation to the transformation programme.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q175','K',NULL,'5','Digital Transformation','[]'),(2020,9,'From a senior strategic perspective, \'technical debt\' is best understood as:','A purely engineering concern with no business implications.','Strategic constraint that limits future business agility.','A normal business cost with no strategic implications at all.','Something to be eliminated entirely across all systems.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q176','K',NULL,'5','Tech Debt Strategy','[]'),(2021,9,'For a senior executive, the most important emerging regulatory areas for digital business in 2025-2026 typically include:','Only ESG reporting standards across capital markets.','Only data privacy regulations such as GDPR and DPDP.','Only tax and trade regulation across the major jurisdictions.','Privacy, AI, cybersecurity, content, antitrust, data flows.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q177','K',NULL,'5','Regulatory Awareness','[]'),(2022,9,'In senior decisions about whether to build or buy technology capability, the most important factor is:','Whether the capability is strategically core or commodity.','Vendor reputation in the relevant technology category.','Cost — the cheaper of build versus buy is usually right.','Speed — the faster of build versus buy is usually right.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q178','K',NULL,'5','Build vs Buy','[]'),(2023,9,'From a governance perspective, the most important constraint on enterprise use of generative AI for consequential decisions is:','The speed of response from the production AI systems.','The risk of confidently false outputs (hallucinations).','The cost of API usage scaling with the volume of calls.','The available training data the AI model was built on.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q179','K',NULL,'5','AI Hallucination','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(2024,9,'In evaluating major technology vendors, the MOST important strategic risk consideration is:','Concentration risk and reversibility of the vendor choice.','Price competitiveness across the vendor and its market rivals.','The vendor\'s growth trajectory over the past few years.','Feature richness offered in the vendor\'s current product set.','a','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q180','K',NULL,'5','Vendor Risk','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(2025,9,'Your CTO advocates a major bet on a specific AI strategy. The MOST mature CEO response is:','Defer entirely to the CTO\'s deep technical expertise on the proposed major bet for the AI strategy.','Make a small experimental commitment to the AI strategy now to maintain future strategic optionality.','Engage: how this changes business model, realistic vs hype, downside, reversible; you decide.','Wait for industry leaders to commit first to the AI strategy before making the major bet yourself.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q181','SJT',NULL,'5','Major AI Bet','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(2026,9,'Your company has just suffered a major data breach affecting millions of customers. The MOST effective initial CEO response is:','Issue a brief statement on the breach and let the legal team handle all of the rest of the work.','Wait for the investigation to fully complete before any external communication about the data breach.','Defer all the data breach communications to the CISO and the legal team to handle on your behalf.','Personally own: rapid communication, full mobilisation, transparent, remediation; visible accountability.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q182','SJT',NULL,'5','Data Breach','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(2027,9,'Your team proposes deploying AI-driven decision-making in a customer-impacting process. The MOST appropriate governance response is:','Approve the AI deployment if the technical team is confident in the model\'s overall accuracy.','Allow the AI deployment to proceed with monthly review meetings about its performance and impact.','Reject all customer-impacting AI use cases in customer-facing processes for the next 24 months.','Require assessment: risk class, thresholds, oversight, human-in-loop, audit; then decide carefully.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q183','SJT',NULL,'5','AI Governance Decision','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":1,\"d\":3}}'),(2028,9,'Your business is constrained by an ageing core technology platform. Modernisation is expensive and risky. The MOST mature response is:','Approve a major replacement initiative based primarily on the CTO\'s recommended plan and approach.','Defer modernisation entirely to protect the company\'s short-term margins for the next few years.','Engage strategically: legacy cost over 5 years vs modernisation outcome; right approach; transparency.','Hire McKinsey to recommend the right modernisation path for the legacy platform across the company.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q184','SJT',NULL,'5','Legacy System Modernisation','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":3,\"d\":1}}'),(2029,9,'Your business has become deeply dependent on a single cloud / AI / SaaS vendor. The MOST mature response is:','Continue with the current vendor — switching vendors at this point is too expensive to consider now.','Assess explicitly: failure scenarios; design reversibility; multi-vendor where feasible; manage risk.','Wait for problems to materialise with the vendor before acting on the deep dependency you have built.','Switch vendors immediately to reduce the deep dependency risk before the situation gets any worse.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q185','SJT',NULL,'5','Tech Vendor Lock-In','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":0,\"d\":0}}'),(2030,9,'Mid-crisis, your security team reports they cannot guarantee the breach is fully contained. Regulators require disclosure timeline. The MOST appropriate response is:','Disclose minimally to meet just the legal requirements only without going beyond the strict letter.','Have outside counsel handle all the disclosure decisions to maintain legal privilege over the process.','Delay the regulatory disclosure to ensure the information about the breach is more fully complete.','Disclose within the required window honestly: known, investigating, response, what to do; prompt + honest.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q186','SJT',NULL,'5','Cyber-Crisis Decision','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":1,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(2031,9,'Your CTO proposes a major foundational investment that will pay off in 5-7 years (data platform, model infrastructure, security overhaul). The MOST mature response is:','Approve only the portion of the investment that shows clear ROI within the next 18 months of activity.','Take seriously as consequential decision; bring board in; explain logic; defend through pressure.','Approve the proposed investment at half the proposed budget to share the risk with the technology team.','Defer the proposed investment — the payoff horizon is too long for committee approval to support it now.','b','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q187','SJT',NULL,'5','Long-Term Tech Investment','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":3,\"c\":1,\"d\":0}}'),(2032,9,'AI capability is making 15% of your workforce roles redundant over 2-3 years. The MOST mature response is:','Announce a hiring freeze and let natural attrition handle most of the workforce reduction over time.','Bring in management consultants to manage the workforce reduction process across the impacted teams.','Quietly reduce the affected headcount as the AI capability comes online over the next 2-3 years.','Transparent: communicate logic; invest in reskilling; demonstrate paths; severance for leavers.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q188','SJT',NULL,'5','AI Workforce Impact','{\"weights\":{\"a\":1,\"b\":0,\"c\":0,\"d\":3}}'),(2033,9,'Your company struggles to attract senior technology talent because the comp packages and engineering culture don\'t compete with tech-native peers. The MOST mature response is:','Accept the reality of the current situation and continue to hire the best senior technology talent available.','Outsource technology work to specialist firms rather than building the in-house senior tech capability.','Acquire smaller tech-native companies specifically for the senior technology talent on their teams.','Address strategically: build competitive proposition or accept disadvantage; this is board-level conversation.','d','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q189','SJT',NULL,'5','Tech Talent at Senior Level','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":0,\"c\":2,\"d\":3}}'),(2034,9,'You use significant generative AI in customer-facing operations (chat, recommendations, content). The MOST appropriate disclosure approach is:','Hide the AI use from customers to maintain their perceived service quality from the company\'s brand.','Disclose the AI use only where regulation requires it in the relevant jurisdictions you operate in.','Transparent: indicate where AI vs humans, what it\'s used for, provide pathways to human assistance.','Don\'t disclose the AI use to customers — it has become standard industry practice across most companies.','c','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q190','SJT',NULL,'5','AI Disclosure to Stakeholders','{\"weights\":{\"a\":0,\"b\":1,\"c\":3,\"d\":0}}'),(2035,9,'I engage substantively in technology strategy decisions - understanding the business implications, not just signing off on technical recommendations.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q191','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Tech Strategy Engagement','{\"likert\":true}'),(2036,9,'I understand the strategic implications of AI for our business - what changes, what doesn\'t, what we should do differently structurally.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q192','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','AI Sophistication','{\"likert\":true}'),(2037,9,'I treat our data as a strategic asset - with thinking about what we capture, how we use it, and what compounds over time.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q193','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Data as Asset','{\"likert\":true}'),(2038,9,'I treat cybersecurity as enterprise risk requiring my personal engagement, not just CISO oversight.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q194','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Cyber as Strategy','{\"likert\":true}'),(2039,9,'I treat senior technical talent attraction and retention as a strategic priority requiring my personal engagement.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q195','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Tech Talent','{\"likert\":true}'),(2040,9,'I maintain genuine awareness of emerging regulations in digital, data, AI, and platform domains relevant to our business.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q196','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Reg Awareness','{\"likert\":true}'),(2041,9,'I think about technology vendor concentration risk and reversibility, not just price and feature competition.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q197','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Vendor Risk','{\"likert\":true}'),(2042,9,'I am willing to commit to foundational technology investments with 5+ year payoff horizons when the strategic logic warrants.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q198','SCI','Strongly Agree','5','Long-Horizon Tech Investment','{\"likert\":true}'),(2043,9,'I tend to delegate technology strategy decisions to my CTO/CIO and review their recommendations rather than engaging substantively.','Strongly Disagree','Disagree','Neither agree nor disagree','Agree','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q199','SCI-R','Strongly Agree','5','Tech Delegation','{\"reverse\":true,\"likert\":true}'),(2044,9,'How often do you read substantive content on technology strategy (not just news headlines)?','Almost Never (0–10% of the time)','Rarely (around 25% of the time)','Sometimes (around 50% of the time)','Often (around 75% of the time)','e','active','2026-06-25 18:00:48','Q200','BEH','Almost Always (90–100% of the time)','5','Tech Learning','{\"likert\":true}');
